1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O Nc6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. dxc5
Bxc5 9. b4 Bd6 10. Bb2 Ng4
{ We are now dealing with other possible ideas for Black, and there are lots of them. For 10... e5, see the next two subchapters. }
11. Qc2 h6 12. b5 Nce5 13. c4 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Qc7 15. h3 Nf6 16. Rac1
{ Chessable: White has the more pleasant position because his rooks can easily come into play, while Black struggles to find a good square for the light-squared bishop. }
16... b6 17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Bxe6
{ Simply wins a pawn.  Full Theoretical Overview } *

