[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 7 6... Bd6 And 8...e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Bd3 e6 5. O-O Nbd7 6. c3
{ Later in this chapter, I will explain that I prefer the Zukertort system 6 b3 against this setup. However, the Colle positions 6 c3 are important for the overall understanding of the opening. Furthermore, this position can be reached through different move orders, anytime ...c7-c5 is answered with c2-c3. }
6... Bd6
{ Black places the bishop on its most active post, not only to control the e5-square but also to go for the ...e5 break. }
7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1
{ The line's starting point. Black has various attempts here. His goal is usually to play...e5. }
8... e5 { Direct ! } 9. e4 cxd4 10. cxd4 h6 { A reasonable waiting move. } 11.
exd5 exd4 12. Ne4 Bb4 13. Bd2 Nxd5 14. Rc1
{ Chessable: White delays recapturing the pawn to bring the only undeveloped piece into play. White banks on the fact that he'll have better centralized major pieces after the exchanges in the center. }
14... N7f6 15. Bc4
{ Chessable: White begins unmasking the queen's attack on the d4-pawn and threatens to win material with Nxf6+ and Bxd5/Bxb4, depending on how Black replies. Black is pretty much forced to capture on d2, after which White will win back the d4-pawn in a few moves and enjoy better centralized pieces.  Full Theoretical Overview }
