[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 8 8...Qc7 And 9...dxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Bd3 e6 5. O-O Nbd7 6. c3
{ Later in this chapter, I will explain that I prefer the Zukertort system 6 b3 against this setup. However, the Colle positions 6 c3 are important for the overall understanding of the opening. Furthermore, this position can be reached through different move orders, anytime ...c7-c5 is answered with c2-c3. }
6... Bd6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1 Qc7 9. e4 dxe4
{ Not taking on d4 doesn't change the general ideas of the position, but it can turn out to be even more dangerous for Black. }
10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Rxe4
{ Chessable: From e4, the rook can slide to the kingside with ease. Remember this idea. }
11... Re8 12. Rh4 h6 13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. Rxh6
{ Chessable: White threatens Nf3-g5 followed by Qd1-h5, with a mating attack. }
14... Bf4 15. Rh4 f5 16. g3 Bd6 17. Qd2 Nf6 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19. Rh6
{ White has a very strong attack and analysing such positions is a big help in improving our understanding of these aggressive ideas.  Chessable: White's biggest threat is Qg5+, winning.  Full Theoretical Overview }
