[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 13 Zukertort vs 8...Qe7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O Bd6 6. b3
{ Indeed, this line is not essential as White can play 6. dxc5 and probably transpose to other lines in this book. However, I have purposefully included it as I consider it very important in order to have a good understanding of the Colle-Zukertort strategy. }
6... O-O 7. Bb2 Nc6
{ I have previously mentioned that having a knight on d7 is best against the Colle, but this line also has a very good reputation against the Zukertort. With a modern outlook on forgotten systems such as the Colle and Zukertort, I doubt that such outdated judgements will retain much value. }
8. Nbd2 Qe7
{ Not Black's only idea. There are other moves, but I want to emphasise the main point of 8... Qe7, which is that if White goes for the logical 9. Ne5, then 9... Qc7 ! is a blow to White, who has to deal with the threats on e5 and Nb4 as the pawn on c2 is hanging. Of course, another idea behind ...Qe7 is ...e5: 9. a3 e5 ! }
9. c4
{ We see that this is a usual resource which White employs to prevent Black from easily playing e5. }
9... cxd4 10. exd4 Ba3 { With the queen on e7, this is often a key idea. } 11.
Bxa3 Qxa3 12. c5
{ This type of position is usually in White's favour. It is not much at the moment, but if White manages to connect the queenside pawns with a3 and b4, this will lead to a pleasant advantage.  Full Theoretical Overview }
