[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 15 Zukertort w/ 9.Ne5 vs 6...Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6
{ This is one of the main ideas Black can employ and it is probably considered as his best option. Black develops quickly while not committing to a particular setup. One idea is to put the pieces on the most agressive squares. We will see that ...Ne4 is often an asset for Black here followed by ...f5. }
5. O-O Bb7
{ Black develops the light-squared bishop before deciding on what to do with the other. Though it resembles a Queen's Indian, differences include that White hasnt played an early c4, which may change the physiology of the position altogether. }
6. Nbd2
{ We are mostly going to look at the Zukertort setup against this line. White wants to play Nbd2, b3, Bb2, and the move order isn't critical at such an early stage. I believe that 6 Nbd2 is more flexible, saving the 7 Qe2 option, which we shall also investigate.However, 6 b3 allows for rapid Ba3 ideas that we will examine as a side option in a separate chapter. So it is up to you to choose your move order ! }
6... Be7
{ This is conservative chess, Black develops on a solid square rather than an active one. }
7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2 Nbd7 9. Ne5
{ A typical idea in the Zukertort line. Before even going c4, White places his knight on its natural square. It is very important to understand the strategical notions behind this position for both White and Black.For 9 c4,see the next two subchapters. }
9... c5 { Not the only move. } 10. f4 Ne4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Be2 f5 13. Nxd7
Qxd7 14. dxc5 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Bxc5 16. Kf2 Rfd8 17. c4 Kf7 18. a3 Be7 19. b4
{ Another good demonstration of how to transform a position into a slightly favourable endgame. 1/2-1/2, 59 moves, Kovacevic, V. 2540 - Handoko, E. 2420, Indonesia 1983.  Full Theoretical Overiew }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 16 Zukertort 9.c4 vs 6...Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2
Nbd7 9. c4
{ A logical response and in the style of the Queen's Indian. White wants to combine various ideas, most of which enabled by having a pawn on c4. }
9... c5
{ A sound response from Black. His plan is ... Rc8, ...Qc7 and so on, developing in a natural way, all the while building pressure on Whites centre with his c5- and d5-pawns. }
10. Qe2 cxd4 11. Nxd4
{ White borrows a strategy from the QGA, where pieces occupy the centre rather than pawns. }
11... Nc5 12. Bc2 dxc4 13. Nxc4 Qd5 14. f3
{ Chessable: White will kick away the centralized Black pieces with e3-e4 and b3-b4. He will put one of his bishops on b3 and place his rooks on the central files.  Full Theoretical Overiew }
