[Black "Quickstarter 25 3.e3 Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4
{ This is yet another typical idea for Black, as well as 3... Bf5. } 4. h3 Bxf3
5. gxf3
{ I am not sure that such move has previously been played, but it certainly looks interesting. }
5... e6 6. c4 c6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. Qb3 Qb6 9. Bd2 Be7 10. Qxb6
{ An interesting solution. It looks slightly anti-positional ,but that is not the case. I once faced such an idea as Black against GM Bogosavljevic. It turns out that if White is fast enough, the idea is fully justified. }
10... axb6 11. cxd5
{ When possessing the bishop pair, it's always important to open the position. }
11... exd5 12. Bd3 b5 13. a4
{ It is essential to prevent the ...Nb6 exapansion. } 13... O-O 14. b3 b4 15.
Ne2 { Full Theoretical Overview } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 26 3.e3 g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b4
{ We are entering the realm of rare ideas now.White obviously wants to prevent an early c5 while gaining space on the queenside. A later c4 will further confirm these queenside intentions. It is important to note that this line may arise from a different but also logical move order: 1 d4 Nf6 2 Nf3 g6 3 e3 Bg7 4 Be2 O-O 5 O-O d5 6 b4. The flexibility of the position requires both sides to be comfortable with the nuances here. Of course, it noticeably resembles some lines of the Grunfeld. }
6... a5 { The principled reaction, but there are other ideas as well. } 7. b5
c5 8. bxc6
{ White exchanged the b-for c-pawn, which is good from a positional point of view. On the other hand, Black achieves rapid development. }
8... Nxc6
{ Active, with Ne4 and e5 to follow. Black wants to put pressure on the centre. }
9. a4
{ A strictly positional idea. Taking control of the b5-square and limiting Black's options on the queenside. }
9... Bf5 10. Na3 Rc8 11. c3 Ne4 12. Nb5 e5 13. Ba3
{ Chessable: After the f8-rook moves, White will challenge the e4-knight, Black's most active piece, and play his rook to c1.  Full Theoretical Overview }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 27 3.e3 c6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6
{ Before deciding where to place the light-squared bishop, Black goes for this typical Slav move. Now, White has a choice between 4. c4, with a direct transpostion to the Slav, which is OK. Or, employ a line that I am trying to give more credit. Of course, you have understood that I am trying to find different ideas in this book, avoiding main lines. }
4. Bd3
{ Clearly, this is not intended to get an advantage directly from the opening. It is more important here to understand how to conduct such positions and perhaps a few of these ideas will help establish some advantage. }
4... Bg4 { Black continues in a Slav-like mannner. } 5. Nbd2 e6 6. O-O Nbd7 7.
b3 Bd6 8. Bb2
{ Indeed, the position is similar to some Slav lines, so it is no surprise that it is mainly about control over the e5-square. }
8... O-O { Black can also deviate here. } 9. c4 Re8
{ This is yet another position where Black has few other options: } 10. Qc2 e5
11. cxd5 Bxf3 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 Nxd5 15. f4
{ Chessable: After 15... Qh4, White must be careful not to fall prey to ...Bxf4, with a winning attack. He must play Kg1-h1 and Rg1-g3 with haste to stabilize the kingside. Once White reaches the desired set-up, he can press on the kingside by bringing in the other rook and advancing the f-pawn.  Full Theoretical Overview }
