[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 29 3.e3 c5 4.dxc5!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. dxc5
{ Black really has to be ready for such a reaction as it can lead to very sharp positions. }
4... e6 5. b4
{ One can notice similarities with the Noteboom line and some other reversed Slav lines, with the f3-knight being White's extra tempo. As previously mentioned in the book, having an extra tempo in sharp positions cannot be neglected, as may be the case with more solid  (closed)  positions, where tempi have less of an effect. }
5... a5 6. c3 axb4 7. cxb4 b6 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4 bxc5 11. b5 Bd6
{ We have reached a highly unbalanced position. White has passed pawns on the queenside but Black has strong control over the centre and a passed c-pawn. White does have the e4-break up his sleeve, if necessary. }
12. O-O O-O 13. Nbd2 Qc7 14. Bb2 c4 15. Qc2
{ Chessable: White completes his development and will manoeuvre to push his queenside pawns. In some games, White sacrificed a minor piece for Black's center pawns, allowing the former to focus on queenside without worrying about central counterplay.  Full Theoretical Overview }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 30 4.Nbd2 And Others"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nbd2
{ A solid and flexible approach from White. All options are still on the table and though it may seem like a bit of a slow system, we will see that there is a plethora of possibilities here. }
4... e6 5. b3 { Transposing to the Zukertort. } 5... cxd4 6. exd4 Bb4
{ With the idea to create early disturbances in White's position. } 7. Bb2 Ne4
8. Bd3 Nc6 9. O-O Bc3 10. Bxc3 Nxc3 11. Qe1 Nb4 12. Qe5
{ An interesting tactical idea. } 12... Qf6 { The most logical. } 13. Qc7 Nxd3
14. Qxc3
{ Chessable: Through the exchanging combination starting with Qe1-e5, White gets rid of one of Black's active knights and saddles the opponent with a bad light-squared bishop. White has no issues exchanging another pair of knights as that will leave him with the superior minor piece. The first player will play on the kingside with moves like Ne5 and Rae1, effectively taking out the bad Black bishop from the game.  Full Theoretical Overview }
