[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 31 4.Nbd2 cxd4 5.exd4 Nc6 6.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nbd2 cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6
{ Simplifying the situation in the centre helps Black develop his pieces without having to worry about potential dxc5 ideas. Black is now ready to go for ...Bf5 or ...Bg4. }
6. c3 { One of the main aspects of White's play; now Bd3 is in the air. } 6...
Bf5 7. Be2
{ A modest approach but a very solid one. We will see that White has a couple of interesting hidden ideas in this position. }
7... e6 8. Nh4
{ The main idea here, but there are other motives as well.  Chessable: White played Be2 because he wants to win the bishop pair. On b5, the bishop may have to be exchanged sooner or later after ...a7-a6 and possibly ...b7-b5. With the bishop on e2, White can play Nf3-h4 and win the bishop without disturbances. }
8... Bg6 9. O-O Bd6 10. g3 O-O 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. f4 Rb8 13. a4 a6 14. Bd3 b5
15. b4
{ A thematic approach borrowed from the QGD, which is valid here too. Now White also has assets as the knight can jump to the strong c5-square.  Full Theoretical Overview }
