[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 33 1...Nf6 2.Nf3 c5 3.d5 g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5
{ Of course, White can go 3 e3 here, which would probably transpose to some of the positions given in other chapters. However, I decided to give a fresh look at offbeat lines such as the Schmidt Benoni. }
3... g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 d6 6. h3 O-O 7. a4
{ White's moves are not so well known, but the ensuing positions are interesting. Of course, playing two consecutive pawn moves in the opening is not ideal as it is important to develop the pieces first. In this case, however, as the position is closed and Black's pieces don't have many active squares, the rule can be broken. }
7... Na6
{ This is the usual response in this system, Black looks for long-term play on the queenside, which will be facilitated by a knight on c7. }
8. Bc4
{ This is the main idea behind White's play. The bishop goes to c4 in one move, helping White keep control of the centre, which will be further supported by a rook on e1 and bishop on f4. The most famous game in this system must be Karpov-Korchnoi, from the Baguio match. }
8... Nc7 9. O-O e6 10. Bf4 exd5 11. Nxd5
{ My idea is to take back on d5 with pieces. It may not be much, but at least it is a new challenge for Black to face. }
11... Ncxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 { Full Theoretical Overview } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 34 1...Nf6 2.Nf3 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5
{ A reaction typical of Benko players. I decided to suggest something new against this system, that recently caught my eye. }
4. c3
{ A highly interesting and relatively new idea. White wants to trade his e-pawn for Black's b-pawn.Though this exchange may seem antipositional, it yields White harmonious play and fast development. }
4... g6
{ This isnt the only move. Black has a wide range of options here, each more logical than the next. }
5. e4
{ White's main and somewhat unusual idea is to trade e-for b-pawns, speeding up his development and opening the e-file. It has similarities to the line 1 b4 e5 2 Bb2 Bxb4, which is known to be good for Black. }
5... Nxe4 6. Bxb5 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Nf6 9. c4 d6 10. Nc3
{ White has a good central structure and easy development. Black would like to reduce the pressure along the e-file by playing ...e5, but this is easier said than done ! }
10... Nbd7 11. Bg5 Nb6 12. Bc6 Rb8 13. b3 h6 14. Bd2 e6 15. dxe6
{ Chessable: Black got rid of the weak e-pawn but new weaknesses on d6 and d5 appear.  Full Theoretical Overview }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 35 The Flexible 6.Nbd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5
{ A very popular idea amongst the Queen's and Nimzo-Indian players with Black. Its a flexible and solid system, which can also give Black good chances to play for the win. Having a pawn on d6, Black deprives White of typical attacking Colle-Zukertort ideas involving Ne5. In my personal tournament practice, I have faced this system as White a number of times. }
6. Nbd2
{ Non-committal. No decision is made between c3 or b3 yet. Therefore, White simply develops the knight while fighting for the e4-square. }
6... Be7 7. c3 { The e4-push is in the air. } 7... Nc6 8. e4
{ Uncharacteristically, we ignore Black's ...Nb4 idea here. } 8... cxd4 9. cxd4
Nb4 10. Bb1 Ba6 11. Re1 Nd3 12. Bxd3 Bxd3
{ Black has the bishop pair and even a strong bishop on d3. Here, though, time is of the essence. White wastes none and grasps the initiative. }
13. d5 { Threatening d6 ! } 13... Qc8 14. d6 Bd8 15. Ne5
{ Chessable: After the bishop retreats, White has an easy scheme of development: the d2-knight goes to f3; the b-pawn to b3; the bishop goes to a3 to support the cramping d6-pawn; and lastly, the queen goes to d2 and the a1-rook to d1.  Full Theoretical Overview }
