[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 36 The Energetic 6.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. c4
{ The most energetic reply, transposing to Queens Indian lines. Though it is no longer a Colle-Zukertort, it is still important to understand such positions, so I've decided to include it in this book. }
6... Be7 7. Nc3 cxd4 8. exd4 d5
{ A very popular line that's been around for a while now. } 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10.
Ne5 O-O 11. Qg4 f5 12. Qe2 Bf6 13. Bc4 Re8 14. Rd1 Nd7 15. Bb5
{ Chessable: Forcing the exchange of Black's dark-squared bishop for White's e5-knight. }
15... Bxe5 16. dxe5
{ Chessable: In the game Kramnik - Topalov, Skopje 2015, White played on the dark squares by taking the knights to create an opposite-colored bishop scenario. An eventual Qh5 incuded ...g7-g6 from Black and allowed Bc1-g5-f6.  Full Theoretical Overview }
