[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 37 5...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3
{ White combines various plans, but mainly refrains, at least momentarily, from playing an early c4. Naturally, such an approach gives rise to new possible ideas. }
6... e5 7. dxe5
{ This is White's normal reaction, not to allow further expansion with ...e4. This is like when Black plays ... dxe4 in the French in order to prevent White from pushing e5. Some players do it as early as move 3! }
7... Ng4 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. Nc3 Ngxe5 10. Qd2 Re8 11. Rad1 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Ne5 13.
Be2 Be6 14. Nb5 { Relocating the white knight to a more comfortable square. }
14... a6 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. c4
{ We have reached a typical position which can also arise from the King's Indian Defence. White has a slighly better pawn structure and Black is forced to remain a little passive. 1/2-1/2, 59 moves, Kramnik, V. 2792 - Vachier-Lagrave, M. 2789, Paris 2018.  Full Theoretical Overview }
