[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 38 5...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5
{ Another usual reaction. Black undermines the centre in Benoni fashion. White has many options but I decided to go for the Colle formation here. }
6. c3
{ This may look passive, but appearances can be deceptive. Black has to decide what to do with the c-pawn, to take on d4 or to keep the game closed. In both cases, White has the opportunity to reach a promising middlegame. }
6... d5 { The most ambitious approach. } 7. dxc5 Ne4 8. b4
{ Now it starts to become very sharp. White hangs on to the c5-pawn, at least for a moment. }
8... a5 { There are alternatives, but they do not promise much. } 9. Nd4 e5 10.
Nb5 Nc6 11. Nd2
{ Chessable: Black doesn't want to capture on d2 as Bxd2 stabilizes White's queenside. The alternative - to allow White to capture on e4 instead - leaves the bishop on g7 passive behind the e5-pawn. }
11... axb4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. cxb4 Nxb4 14. Nd6 Qc7 15. a4
{ A great idea. After this, it seems that only White can play for an advantage. }
15... Qxc5 16. Bc4 { White wants to play Ba3. } 16... Rd8 17. Bxf7+ Kh8 18.
Nxe4
{ Chessable: White is up a pawn and can consolidate. If Black doesn't exchange queens, White will play Qb3 and Ba3, after which all of his pieces are in play.  Full Theoretical Overview }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 39 1...Nf6 2.Nf3 d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Bg4
{ In today's chess, we often see such an approach, and it is also recomended in books  (not without good reason)  as a very practical solution for tournament play. Therefore, I decided to include it here and offer a line that goes with the rest of the book. }
4. Be2 Nbd7 5. c4 e5 6. Nc3 Be7
{ A schema that has become commonplace, so I will present here one of many possible ideas, in conjuction with the Colle-Zukertort. }
7. O-O O-O 8. b3
{ This move again, in Zukertort style. We will see many rare lines that are actually rather underestimated. }
8... c6 9. Qc2 Re8 10. Bb2 Bf8 11. dxe5
{ This is a principled reaction, reminiscent of King's Indian lines. } 11...
dxe5 12. Rad1
{ It would be a mistake to go h3 at this point. The e3-pawn  (rather than being on e4)  makes a huge difference as it restricts Black's dark-squared bishop and allows White to use the e4-square to manoeuvre his pieces, as will soon become apparent. }
12... Qc7 13. h3 { The right timing for this move. } 13... Bh5 14. Ng5
{ As previously mentioned, we want to exchange the light-squared bishops and use the e4-square as a stepping stone for our pieces. }
14... Bg6 15. Bd3
{ Chessable: Black cannot stop the exchange of light-squared bishops.  Full Theoretical Overview }
