[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter 41 1...e6 2.Nf3 f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5
{ A typical move order for Dutch players, which makes it an important line to address. The idea I have analysed is as sharp as it is rare. }
3. Bf4 { No Colle-Zukertort resemblance this time. } 3... Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. h3
O-O 6. Nbd2 b6 7. Bd3
{ The starting point of the line. White will soon have to decide where to put the queen. }
7... Bb7 8. c3 Ne4 9. Rg1
{ A cunning move. White waits before committing the queen to a square and decides to open the g-file first. }
9... d6 10. Qc2 d5 11. g4 c5 12. gxf5 exf5 13. dxc5
{ Unorthodox but strong ! White opens the position up in order to create threats. }
13... bxc5 14. O-O-O Qb6 15. Ne5
{ White is better here.    Chessable: Note that Black can't play  15...Nxf2  due to  16.Bxf5  , ∆  Bxh7+  ,  Ng6+  with a winning attack.   Full Theoretical Overview }
