[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 5...c4 and 5...Nc6"]
[Black "5...c4 Alternative - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ An important thing to say is that this book is about deeply understanding classical chess based on a modern outlook rather then looking for direct attempts for an advantage using in-depth engine analysis.Learning chess classically is of the utmost necessity to all competitive players. The Colle and Zukertort lines are not mainstream systems in todays chess, but I think that is because they were not properly analysed. Recently, weve seen a rise of the London system, to such an extent that everybody is now playing it. I think that the lines treated in this book may also be victims to such popularity in coming years. They hold such a variety of ideas, from positional to attacking, which is rarely found in chess nowadays. }
4... c5 5. O-O
{ This is essential: before deciding on c3 or b3, White must castle first. However, this gives Black the interesting possibility to close the position with ...c4 and force matters into a much slower type of game. }
5... c4
{ An important line. Black simply wants to gain space and defend it no matter what. A perfectly legitimate idea and something that White cannot neglect. }
6. Be2 b5 7. b3 Bb7 { This is the line's starting position. } 8. a4
{ White goes for solid plan.  Other ideas are also possible: A.   8.bxc4 !?  bxc4   8...dxc4  9.a4  a6  10.c3  Nbd7  11.Nbd2  If Black takes with the d-pawn on c4, White goes for e4. The position then becomes rather imbalanced.  9.Nc3  A1.  9...Nc6  A2.   9...Bb4  10.Bd2  Nc6  11.Rb1  transposes.  A3.   9...Nbd7  10.Rb1  Bc6  11.Ne5  Nxe5  12.dxe5  Nd7  13.e4 !  Interesting pawn sacrifice in order to disturb Black's logical play.  dxe4  14.Bxc4  Nxe5  15.Bb5  Qxd1  16.Rxd1  f5  17.Bf4  a6  18.Be2  Ng6  19.Be3  =∞  10.Rb1  Bb4   10...Rb8  11.e4 !?  Bb4  12.exd5  exd5  13.Rxb4  Nxb4  14.Bf4  Nc6  15.Bxb8  Qxb8  16.Qd2  O-O  17.Rb1  Re8  Black is probably OK here.  11.Bd2  O-O  12.Ne5  Rb8  13.a3  Bxc3  14.Bxc3  Ne4  15.Nxc6  Bxc6  16.Rxb8  Qxb8  17.Bb4  Rc8  18.f3  Nd6  19.Qd2  White might even consider going for advantage here.  B.   8.Nc3 !?  Kramnik's choice.  a6 !  The best and most critical.   8...b4  9.Na4  c3  10.Ne5  Bd6  11.a3  a5  12.Bb5+  Kf8  13.Nc5  Qb6  14.Nxb7  Qxb7  15.Qe2  g6  16.e4 !  Nxe4  17.Bh6+  Ke7  18.f3  Nd2  19.Rfe1  Kd8  20.Bf4  1-0 Kramnik,V. 2808 - Giri, A. 2771, Stavanger 2017. A nice miniature by the ex-world champion.  9.Ne5  B1.  Qc7  B2.   9...Nc6  10.f4  B2.1.  b4  B2.2.   10...Bd6  11.bxc4 !?  dxc4   11...bxc4  12.Rb1  Qc7  13.g4  O-O  14.g5  Nd7  15.Bg4 !  White doesnt allow ...f6 and prepares the natural idea Rf3-h3.  12.Bf3  Qc7  13.a3  O-O  14.Qe1  Ne7  15.e4  With yet another complex play.  B2.3.   10...Be7  11.a3  O-O  Another idea for White is to transfer the dark-squared bishop from d2 to h4 with  12.Bd2  The position is unclear but full of potential.  11.Na4  c3  12.a3  a5  13.e4  Nxe4  14.Bb5  Qc7  15.f5  exf5  16.Rxf5  f6  17.Bf4  Bd6  18.Qh5+  White wins.  10.Bd2  Nc6  11.f4  Bd6  12.a3   12.bxc4  dxc4 !  Its good for Black.  12...O-O  13.Qe1 !   13.Bf3  Ne7  Again, this is a good idea for Black.  13...Ne7  14.g4  Ne8  15.Qg3  f6  16.Nf3  Kh8  17.b4  with the idea to transfer the knight from c3 to f2 and bishop from e2 to c2. Its usually about plans here ! }
8... a6 9. c3
{ A positional idea for White here is to exchange the dark-squared bishops via a3 and to later on try and build some pressure along the a- or b-file. }
9... Nbd7 10. Nbd2
{ 10.Nfd2 !?  We will see the idea behind this in a few moves.  Be7  11.Ba3 !?  O-O  12.Bxe7  Qxe7  13.Na3  Bc6  14.axb5  axb5  15.Nc2 !?  That's the point ! White wants to occupy the b4-square with a knight.  Qd6  16.Nb4  Bb7  17.Qc2  g6  18.h3  with some pressure. If Black ever goes e5, then White can simply take and play Nf3. }
10... Be7 11. Ba3 O-O 12. Qc2 Bc6 13. Qb2 h6 14. h3 Rb8 15. axb5 axb5 16. Bxe7
Qxe7 17. Ra6
{ 17.Ra7  Qd6  18.Rfa1  Similar to a main line White has some pressure.1-0, 84 moves, Kurajica, B. 2551 - Bareev, E. 2734, Sarajevo 2003. }
17... Rfc8 18. b4 Ra8 19. Rfa1 Rxa6 20. Rxa6 Qd6 21. Qa1
{ White has some initiative here.@@HeaderStart@@Conclusion@@HeaderEnd@@ 5... c4 is a unique attempt Black is driving the game into a more closed position. It's a solid idea, but White still has good chances to achieve active play. After 6. Be2 b5 7. b3 Bb7 White has a few ideas:One is 8. a4 to try and exchange the darksquared bishop and to get control of the a-file.The other is to go 8. Nc3 !?, as Kramnik did. A rather sharp idea that requires a precise reaction from Black. }
