[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 5...c4 and 5...Nc6"]
[Black "9...Be7 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O Nc6 6. c3
{ We are entering the Colle system, which is defined as the c3-setup. White has a few ideas here, e4 usually being the main one. This is often only achieved when White goes dxc5 and only then e4. Due to the knight being on c6, Black is forced to take with the bishop on c5. Resemblances with the Semi-Slav are obvious and we can say that White is a clear tempo up compared to Black's perspective in the Semi-Slav, and that is often an important detail in sharp positions. }
6... Bd6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. b4 Be7
{ A slower approach to this position but also a more solid one in a way.  For   9...Bd6  see the next subchapters. }
10. Bb2 a6
{ Blacks plan is more positional here and incline more to a solid approach.  A.   10...b6  11.a3  Bb7  12.Qe2   12.c4  a5  13.b5  Nb8  14.Qe2  Nbd7  15.cxd5  Nxd5  16.Nc4  Nc5  17.Rfd1 !?  Blacks problem is that their queen lacks good squares.  12...Qc7  13.c4 !  It is important to push c4 before deciding where to put the rooks. Only after c4 can we have a clearer picture of where each rook belongs.  dxc4  14.Nxc4  Ng4  15.Rfc1 !  Escaping from potential tricks connected with mate on h2 !  B.   10...e5  11.e4  Bg4  12.h3  Bh5   12...Bxf3  13.Qxf3  d4  14.a3  dxc3  15.Bxc3  Nd4  16.Bxd4  Qxd4  17.Nb3  Qb6  18.Rac1  Rac8  19.Bc4  White is slightly better as the bishop on c4 is rather strong.  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Qc2  h6   14...Bg6  15.Bxg6  hxg6  16.b5  Na5  17.Nxe5  ±  15.b5  Na5  16.Bh7+ !  A nice tactical solution.  Kh8  17.c4  Nb4   17...Nf4  18.Bxe5  ±  18.Qe4 !  White is better. This motif of bringing the queen to the centre has already been seen in other lines, showing that it is an important asset. Back to 10... a6. }
11. a4
{ The most energetic. White does not want to allow ...b5 easily.  A.   11.a3  b5  12.a4  Rb8  13.axb5  axb5  14.Qe2  Qb6  15.Nd4  Nxd4 ?!   15...e5 !  16.exd4  Ne8  17.Nb3  Nd6  18.Bc1 !  An important aspect of this idea: White manoeuvres his pieces into better positions, improving coordination.  B.   11.Qb1 !?  b5   11...e5  12.e4  dxe4  13.Nxe4  Nh5  14.Rd1  Qc7  15.Ng3  Nxg3  16.hxg3  g6  17.Bc1  Be6  18.Be3  Rac8  19.Qb2  With unclear consequences.  12.a4  Rb8  13.axb5  axb5  14.h3  Qb6  15.Nd4  Bd7  16.N2f3  Rfc8  17.Ra3  Be8  18.Qa2  Qd8  19.Ra1  with a complicated game. }
11... e5
{ 11...b6  12.Qe2  Bb7  13.b5  axb5  14.axb5  Na5  15.c4  Nd7   15...dxc4  16.Nxc4  Nxc4  17.Bxc4  Rxa1  18.Rxa1  Qc7  19.Rc1  Rc8  20.Qd1  Qb8  21.Nd4  h6  22.Bf1  Rxc1  23.Qxc1  Bc5  24.Nc6  Although Black is close to equality, the weakness on c6 helps White to generate some pressure.  16.cxd5  Nc5  17.e4  exd5  18.Bb1  Re8  19.Rd1  Qc7  20.e5  g6  21.Ba2  Ne6  22.Rac1  Bc5  23.g3  Red8  24.Ba1  Qe7  25.h4  An unclear position. }
12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nh5
{ 13...Qc7  14.Re1  Rd8  15.Qc2  Nxe4   15...g6  16.Neg5 !?  Ng4  17.Bc1  Kg7  18.h3  Nh6  19.Bc4  f5  20.Qb3  e4  21.Nd4  Nxd4  22.cxd4  Bf6  23.Be6  White has the initiative.  16.Bxe4  g6  17.b5  axb5  18.axb5  Rxa1  19.Rxa1  Nb8   19...Na5  20.c4 !  Nxc4 ?  21.Nxe5  wins for White.  20.c4  Nd7  21.h4 !?  Whites chances are preferable. }
14. b5 Nf4 15. Bb1 axb5
{ The alternative is also rather complex:   15...Na5  16.Nxe5  Be6  17.Qf3  Ng6  18.c4  Nxe5  19.Bxe5  Nxc4  20.Bc3  White has more active pieces and this helps him to generate easier play:  axb5   20...Qc7  21.Ng3  Rad8  22.Nf5  Bxf5  23.Bxf5  axb5  24.Rab1  g6  25.Rxb5  White has some edge here.  21.axb5  Rxa1  22.Bxa1  Qd5  23.Qg3  f6  24.Re1  Qd7  25.h4  Kh8  26.h5  h6  27.Qg6  Bg8  28.Ng5 !  A nice idea but probably only leads to a draw. It still indicates that Black is under some pressure in such positions. White risks nothing, while Black has to show precise play. }
16. axb5 Rxa1 17. Bxa1 Na5 18. Nxe5 Be6 19. Qc2 f5 20. Nd2 Qd5 21. Ndf3 Nc4 22.
Nxc4 Qxc4 23. Nd4 Bc5 24. Re1 Bxd4 25. cxd4 Qxb5 26. Qd2
{ White keeps edge here. } *

