1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O Nc6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. dxc5
Bxc5 9. b4 Bd6 10. Bb2 Ng4
{ We are now dealing with other possible ideas for Black, and there are lots of them. For 10... e5, see the next two subchapters.  A.   10...Qc7  11.b5  Ne5  12.Nxe5  Bxe5  13.f4  Bd6  14.c4  Qe7  15.Rc1  Bd7   15...b6  16.Bxf6  Qxf6  17.cxd5  exd5  18.Qh5  h6  19.Qxd5  ±  16.e4  dxe4  17.Bxf6 !  Qxf6  18.Nxe4  Qd4+  19.Kh1  Bc5  20.Qc2  f5  21.Nxc5  Qxc5  22.Be2  White may be slightly better here.  B.   10...Bd7  11.b5  Ne5  12.Nxe5  Bxe5  13.Nf3  Bd6  14.c4  Qe7  15.cxd5  Nxd5  16.Qb3  White has slightly better chances.  C.   10...b6  11.a3  a5   11...Bb7  12.c4  gives White easy play in the centre.  12.b5  Ne5  13.Nxe5  Bxe5  Now White has two possible paths:  14.f4   14.Nf3  Bd6  15.c4  dxc4  16.Bxf6  gxf6  17.Be4  Ra7  18.Qc2  f5  19.Bc6  Qf6  20.Qxc4  Re7  21.g3  Bc5  22.Rfd1  e5  23.Nd2  With another complex middlegame position.  14...Bd6  15.c4  Bb7  16.cxd5  exd5  17.Re1  Rc8  18.Bf5  Rc7  19.Nf3  Bc5  20.Be5  Re8  21.Rc1  Rce7  22.Bd4  ∞  D.   10...a6  Again here White has a choice between allowing b5 or not:  11.a3   11.a4  Qe7  12.b5  Ne5  13.Nxe5  Bxe5  14.Qc2  Bd7  15.c4  Bxb2  16.Qxb2  Rfd8  17.Rfc1  dxc4  18.Bxc4  h6  19.Be2  Be8  20.h3  axb5  21.axb5  Rxa1  22.Rxa1  Qd6  23.Nc4  Qc5  24.Ne5  Rd5  25.Nf3  with equal play. That was just one possible example.  11...b5  12.a4  Rb8  13.axb5  axb5  14.Qe2  Qb6  15.Nd4  e5 !?  An interesting pawn sacrifice.  16.Nxb5  Be7  17.e4  Bg4  18.Qe3  D1.  Rfd8  D2.   18...Qxe3  19.fxe3  A highly complex endgame, lets go a little deeper.  Rfd8  20.Rf2  Bh5  21.h3  dxe4  22.Bc4  Nd5  23.Nf1  Bg5  24.Bxd5  Rxd5  25.Nc7  Rdd8  26.Na6  Rb6  27.g4  Bg6  28.Nc5  with an interesting position which may slightly favor White.  19.Qxb6  Rxb6  20.Nb3  dxe4   20...Nxe4  21.f3  Be6  22.Nc7  and White has some pressure in this endgame.  21.Bc4  We have reached a highly unbalanced end-game, the assessment of which is not easy to give, probably unclear. }
11. Qc2 h6
{ Alternatives don't equalise either. For example:   11...f5  12.b5  Nce5  13.c4  Nxd3  14.Qxd3  dxc4  15.Qc3  Qe7  16.Nxc4  Bc5  17.Rfd1  b6  18.Nce5  a6  19.a4  += }
12. b5
{ 12.a3 !?  Nce5  13.Nxe5  Nxe5  14.Be2  a5   14...Bd7  15.f4  Ng6  16.c4  This is a typical idea, White has achieved slightly better chances.  15.f4  Nd7  16.c4  axb4  17.axb4  Rxa1  18.Bxa1  b6  19.Qc3  Again, White is in the drivers seat. }
12... Nce5 13. c4 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Qc7 15. h3 Nf6 16. Rac1 b6 17. Bxe5
{ 17.Qb1  Nxf3+  18.Nxf3  Bc5 !  A defensive resource that was overlooked.  19.Qa1  Qe7  20.Ne5  Bb7  21.Be2  Rac8  22.Rfd1  Ba3  23.Nc6  Bxc6  24.Bxf6  Qxf6  25.Qxf6  gxf6  26.Rxc6  Rxc6  27.bxc6  Black managed to make a draw in this slightly worse endgame. 1/2-1/2, 33 moves, Pavlovic, M. 2482 - Berkes, F. 2678, Valjevo 2018. }
17... Bxe5 18. Bxe6 { Simply wins a pawn. } *

