{ It is important to understand that this move comes before h3 !  The alternative   12.h3  is possible but nuances are rather important here:  Bh5  Taking at once is possible, but probably its better to wait.   12...Bxf3  13.Qxf3  d4  14.a3  dxc3  15.Bxc3  Bc7  16.Nb3  Bb6  17.Rfd1  Qe7  18.Bc4  Rac8  19.Rac1  White is slighlty better.  A.  13.exd5  B.   13.Re1  Qc7 !  This is why we go Re1 first. Black can now play naturally withRad8.  14.Qb3   14.exd5  Nxd5  15.Nc4  Rad8  and Black is fine.  14...Bxf3  15.Nxf3  dxe4  16.Bxe4  Nxe4  17.Rxe4  Rad8  Black has reached a decent position.  13...Nxd5  14.Ne4   14.Qc2  Nf4 !  15.Bxh7+  Kh8  =∞  14...Bc7  15.Ng3  Nf4 !  16.Be4  Bg6  and the position is rather unclear. }
12... Re8
{ A.   12...Qc7  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Bxh7+ !  ±  That's the trick ! This would not work with the inclusion of h3 and Bh5.  B.   12...Bh5  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Qc2  Nf6   14...Bg6  15.Bxg6  hxg6  16.Rad1  +-  15.b5  Ne7  16.c4  gives White a clear advantage.  C.   12...Kh8  13.exd5 !?  Nxd5  14.h3  Be6   14...Bh5  15.g4  Bg6  16.Bxg6  fxg6  17.Ne4  Bc7  18.b5  Na5  19.Ba3  Rf7  20.Nfg5  White is almost winning.  15.Ne4  f6  16.Bc4  Be7  17.Qb3  a5  18.a3  b5  19.Bxb5  Nf4  20.Qc2  Qc7  21.Rad1  White keeps the better prospects here.  D.   12...Bc7  13.h3  Bh5  14.exd5  Nxd5   14...Qxd5  15.Ne4  Nxe4  16.Bxe4  Qxd1  17.Raxd1  f6  18.Rd7  Rac8  19.b5  Na5  20.Ba3  Rfd8  21.Bd5+  Kh8  22.Rxd8+  Rxd8  23.c4  with a promising endgame. 0-1, 42 moves, Artemiev, V. 2695 -Ponkratov, P. 2603, Sochi RUS 2017.  15.b5  Nf4  16.Bf1  Na5  Black can also pick another square for the knight:   16...Ne7  17.Qc2  Bxf3  18.Nxf3  Neg6  19.g3  Ne6  20.Rad1  Qe7  21.c4  The bishop pair favors White here.  17.c4  f6  18.Qc2  Bg6   18...b6  19.g3  Ne6  20.Bd3  Bxf3  21.Nxf3  ±  White is much better due to very strong pressure on b1-h7 diagonal.  19.Ne4 !  with g3 and Nh4 to follow. White gets good play in the centre. }
13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Qc2 h6 15. h3 Be6
{ 15...Bxf3  16.Nxf3  Qc7  17.Rad1  Nf6  18.Nd2 !  A rather important motif, White must fight for the light squares here.  Rad8   18...Rac8  19.Ne4  Nxe4  20.Bxe4  White is fine, as  Nxb4 ?  is met with  21.Qd2 !  +-  19.Ne4  Nxe4  20.Bxe4  Bf8  21.Qe2  Rxd1  22.Rxd1  Rd8  23.Rxd8  Nxd8  24.h4  a5  25.a3  Ne6  26.g3  axb4  27.cxb4  With the bishop pair and a pawn majority on the queenside,White naturally has the better chances. }
16. b5 Na5 17. Rad1 Qc7 18. c4 Nb4 19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Qe4
{ A very important manoeuvre for White, which is a huge help in obtaining the initiative. }
*

