[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 5...Nbd7"]
[Black "6.c3 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Bd3 e6 5. O-O Nbd7
{ This is considered as the best defence against the Colle system. The main idea behind this move is to be ready for dxc5. Throughout the book, we will see that dxc5 followed by e4 is often one of the key themes, but now Black is ready to recapture on c5 with the knight, thus attacking the bishop on d3. On the other hand, the d7-knight also has its limitations. }
6. c3
{ Later in this chapter, I will explain that I prefer the Zukertort system 6 b3 against this setup. However, the Colle positions 6 c3 are important for the overall understanding of the opening. Furthermore, this position can be reached through different move orders, anytime ...c7-c5 is answered with c2-c3. }
6... b6
{ Black wants to develop his light-squared bishop, letting Whites knight settle on e5.  Black can also play in more conservative way:   6...Be7  7.Nbd2  O-O  8.Qe2  b6  9.e4  dxe4  10.Nxe4  Bb7  11.Nxf6+  Nxf6  12.dxc5  Bxc5  13.Bg5  Be7  14.Rad1  Qc7  15.Ne5  Rad8  16.Bh4 !?  g6  17.Rfe1  Nh5  18.Bxe7  Qxe7  19.Be4  Nf6  20.Bxb7  Qxb7  21.c4  Here we have a typical position that can arise from many openings. In these structures, White has some edge be-cause of the possibility to create play on queenside. }
7. Nbd2 Bb7 8. Ne5
{ Let's see latest example, played again by Kramnik.   8.Qe2 !?  Be7  9.b3  O-O  10.Bb2  Rc8  11.Rac1  I am not very fond of this rook shift to the c-file, I would prefer it on d1.  Bd6  12.c4  cxd4  13.exd4  Qe7  14.Ne5  Ba3  15.Bxa3  Qxa3  16.f4  g6  17.Ndf3  dxc4  18.bxc4  Qd6  19.Qe3  Bxf3 !?  Black wants to simplify matters.  20.Nxf3  Rfd8  21.Rcd1  Nb8  22.Kh1  Nc6  23.Be2  Kg7  24.Qc1  h5  25.Qa1  Ne7  26.Ne5  Nf5  27.Rd3  with complex play ahead of us. 1/2-1/2, 44 moves, Kramnik, V. 2777 -Ding Liren 2813, Wijk aan Zee 2019. }
8... Bd6
{ 8...g6 !?  9.f4  Bg7  10.b3  O-O  11.Bb2  Qe7  12.a4  a6  13.Qe2  Rfc8  14.c4  A typical, highly complex position. }
9. f4 O-O 10. Qf3 Rc8 11. g4 { Going for it ! } 11... Rc7
{ 11...g6  12.Qg2  Ne8   12...Rc7  13.g5  Ne4 ?!  This doesnt work...  14.Nxd7  Rxd7  15.Nxe4  dxe4  16.Bxe4  Bxe4  17.Qxe4  It's a healthy extra pawn.  13.Ndf3  f6  14.Nxd7  Qxd7  15.Bd2  Be7  16.h4  Nd6  17.h5  Ne4  18.hxg6  hxg6  19.g5  ∞ }
12. Qg2
{ In many Colle games, we see that Black also gets reasonable counterchances. It is therefore highly important to understand the nuances and details here:   12.g5  Bxe5 !?  13.fxe5  Ne4 !  14.h4  f5  15.exf6  gxf6  Black has counterplay. 0-1, 40 moves, Colle, E. - Znosko Borovsky, E., Nice 1930. }
12... g6 13. g5 Nh5 14. Ng4 Qc8 15. Nf3 cxd4 16. cxd4 Ba6 17. Qe2 Bxd3 18. Qxd3
{ No side has broken through for the moment, but White somehow seems to have more space and easier play. }
*

