{ Later in this chapter, I will explain that I prefer the Zukertort system 6 b3 against this setup. However, the Colle positions 6 c3 are important for the overall understanding of the opening. Furthermore, this position can be reached through different move orders, anytime ...c7-c5 is answered with c2-c3. }
6... Bd6
{ Black places the bishop on its most active post, not only to control the e5-square but also to go for the ...e5 break. }
7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1
{ The line's starting point. Black has various attempts here. His goal is usually to play...e5. }
8... e5
{ Direct !  Apart from the main line with 8... Qc7 in the next subchapters, Black has another reasonable alternative:   8...b6  9.e4  dxe4  10.Nxe4  Be7  11.Qe2  cxd4  12.Nxd4  Bb7  13.Bg5  Re8   13...Bxe4 ?  14.Bxe4  Nxe4  15.Nc6 !  Nxc3  16.Qc4  Rc8  17.Bxe7  Rxc6  18.Qxc6  Qxe7  19.Qxc3  White is winning. 1-0, 40 moves, Marjanovic, S. 2505 - Popovic, P. 2540, Novi Sad 1985.   13...Nxe4  14.Bxe4  Bxe4  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  16.Qxe4  is similar.  14.Rad1  Nxe4  15.Bxe4  Bxe4  16.Bxe7  Qxe7  17.Qxe4  Nf6  18.Qf3  Qc5  19.h3  Rac8  20.a4  Objectively, the position is equal. In practice though, this kind of position is a little easier for White. }
9. e4 cxd4
{ A.   9...Re8  10.exd5  exd4  11.cxd4  cxd4  12.Rxe8+  Qxe8  13.Nc4 !  Bc5  14.d6  b6  15.a3  a5  16.Bf4  Bb7  17.Bg3  This appears to be in Whites favor.  B.   9...dxe4  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Rxe4 !  A key idea for White in this setup.  exd4  12.cxd4  h6  13.dxc5  Bxc5  14.Bxh6 !  gxh6  15.Rg4+  Kh8  16.Rh4  Kg7  17.Qd2  Qb6  18.b4  Bxf2+  19.Qxf2  Qxf2+  20.Kxf2  with a slightly favourable ending for White. }
10. cxd4 h6
{ A reasonable waiting move.  Black also has other ideas, but none of them seem adequate:   10...dxe4  11.Nxe4  Nxe4  12.Rxe4 !  Recapturing with the rook yet again.  f5   12...exd4  13.Rxd4  Bc5  14.Rd5  Qb6  15.Qc2  h6  16.Bf4  White has a clear advantage.  13.Rh4  Be7   13...e4  14.Bc4+  Kh8  15.Ng5  h6  16.Qh5  Qf6  17.Ne6  +-  14.Rh3  h6   14...e4  15.Bc4+  Kh8  16.Ne5 !  +-  15.Nxe5  Nxe5  16.dxe5  f4  17.Rf3  ± }
11. exd5
{ 11.b3 !?  dxe4  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Bxe4  exd4  14.Bb2  Nf6  15.Qxd4  Qb6  16.Bc2  Bb4  17.Red1  Qxd4  18.Nxd4  Bg4  19.f3  Bd7  20.Nf5  Bxf5  21.Bxf5  +=  The bishop pair gives White a shot at an advantage. }
