1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Bd3 e6 5. O-O Nbd7 6. c3
{ Later in this chapter, I will explain that I prefer the Zukertort system 6 b3 against this setup. However, the Colle positions 6 c3 are important for the overall understanding of the opening. Furthermore, this position can be reached through different move orders, anytime ...c7-c5 is answered with c2-c3. }
6... Bd6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1 Qc7 9. e4 dxe4
{ Not taking on d4 doesn't change the general ideas of the position, but it can turn out to be even more dangerous for Black.   9...cxd4  - see the next subchapter. }
10. Nxe4 Nxe4
{ A.   10...Bf4  11.Bxf4  Qxf4  12.dxc5  is good for White. This is a motif well worth noting when Black doesn't take on d4.  B.   10...b6  Probably safest.  11.Nxd6  Qxd6  12.dxc5  Qxc5  13.Be3  Qc7  14.Qd2  Bb7  15.Bf4  Qc6  16.Rad1  White has a small but stable advantage. This position can be compared to some French Defence lines, namely 3 Nd2 c5 4 exd5 Qxd5. }
11. Rxe4 Re8
{ 11...c4  Trying to expand on the queenside with tempo but blocking potential play along the c-file. However, Black is not fast enough.  12.Bc2  b5  13.Ng5 !  h6  14.Rh4  Bb7  15.Rxh6 !!  Another great theme !  gxh6  16.Qh5  Nb6  17.Bh7+ !  Kg7  18.Ne4  Bxh2+  19.Kf1  Bf4  20.Qg4+  Kh8  21.Bxf4  f5  22.Qg3  White is winning. }
12. Rh4
{ Another idea is:   12.Bc2 !?  cxd4  13.cxd4  b6  14.Rh4  h6  15.Bxh6 !   15.Be3  Bb7  16.Rc1  Qd8  17.Rh3  Nf6  with an unclear play. 1/2-1/2, 47 moves, Ree, H. 2417 - Timman, J. 2639, Amsterdam 2000.  15...gxh6  16.Qc1  Kf8  17.Qxh6+  Ke7  18.Rc1  ↑  White has a dangerous initiative. }
12... h6
{ A.   12...f5  13.Qe2  Nf6  14.Bg5  Rf8  15.Rd1  White keeps a positional edge here.  B.   12...Nf8  13.Ng5  Be7 ?!   13...h6  14.Qh5  The attack seems promising.  14.Bxh7+ !  Nxh7  15.Qh5  Bf6  16.Bf4  e5  17.Qxh7+  Kf8  18.dxe5  Bxe5  19.Re1  White should win. }
13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. Rxh6 Bf4 15. Rh4 f5 16. g3 Bd6 17. Qd2 Nf6 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19.
Rh6
{ White has a very strong attack and analysing such positions is a big help in improving our understanding of these aggressive ideas. }
19... Nh7
{ 19...Qg7  20.Ne5 !  Nd7  21.Rg6  Nxe5  22.Rxg7+  Kxg7  23.Qg5+  Ng6  24.Rd1  Be7  25.Qe3  ±  White is better. }
20. Re1 Bf8 21. Rg6+ Bg7 22. Bxf5 Rd8 23. Bd3
{ Black's king looks rather vulnerable. } *

