1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Bd3 e6 5. O-O Nbd7 6. c3
{ Later in this chapter, I will explain that I prefer the Zukertort system 6 b3 against this setup. However, the Colle positions 6 c3 are important for the overall understanding of the opening. Furthermore, this position can be reached through different move orders, anytime ...c7-c5 is answered with c2-c3. }
6... Bd6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1 Qc7 9. e4 cxd4 10. cxd4 dxe4 11. Nxe4
{ We have transposed to an isolani pawn type of position, a kind of reversed Panov Attack. In this particular case, the rook on e1 plays an important role as in the event of Nxe4, White is ready for the ultra sharp Rxe4 ! as previously mentioned, helping him fuel a dangerous attack. }
11... Nxe4
{ Black has various other options.  A.   11...Nd5  12.Nxd6  Qxd6  13.Ne5  b6  14.Qf3  Bb7  15.Bh6 !  A cute tactic.  Nxe5   15...gxh6 ?  16.Qg3+  Kh8  17.Nxf7+  +-  16.dxe5  Qd7  17.Qg3  f6  18.exf6  Nxf6  19.Rxe6  White is better.  B.   11...Be7  12.Bg5  b6  13.Ne5  Nxe5  14.dxe5  Nxe4 !?  More or less forces a rook endgame.  In a rather old game, Black played more passively:   14...Ne8 ?  15.Qg4  Kh8  16.Nf6  Bxf6  17.Qh4  h6  18.exf6  Kg8  19.fxg7  Nxg7  20.Bf6  1-0, Preinfalk, A. - Milic, B., Ljubljana 1946.  15.Bxe4  Bb7  16.Rc1  Qd8  17.Bxb7  Bxg5  18.Bxa8  Bxc1  19.Qxd8  Rxd8  20.Rxc1  Rxa8  21.Rc7 !  g5  22.Kf1  Kg7  23.Ke2  Kg6  24.a4  White retains chances to play for a win.  C.   11...b6  12.Bg5  Bb7 ?!  It is important to realise why such a logical move is actually a bad one:   12...Be7  transpose to 11... Be7.  13.Rc1  Qb8  14.Nxf6+  Nxf6  15.Bxf6  gxf6  16.Bxh7+ !  A nice sacrifice and recurring theme in such positions.Whites attack is full of potential.  Kxh7  17.Ne5 !!  Double piece sac ! Black is lost on the spot as he cannot stop either of White's rooks from delivering a lethal blow on the third rank.  D.   11...Bf4  12.Ne5 !   12.Nxf6+  Nxf6  13.Ne5  Bxc1  14.Rxc1  Qd6  15.Rc3  Bd7  16.Bc2  Rac8  17.Rg3  Rc7  18.Qd2  g6  19.Bb3  Bc6  20.Rh3  Rfc8  21.Qf4  with complicated play. 1-0, 41 moves, Djuric, S. 2535 - Zelcic, R. 2455, Nova Gorica 1997.  12...Bxe5  13.dxe5  Qxe5  14.Bd2  The bishop pair largely compensares for the pawn.  Nxe4  15.Rxe4  Qxb2  And even for two pawns.  16.Rc1  Qf6  17.Re3  White has dangerous initiative, for instance:  g6  18.Bc3  Qe7  19.Bb2  Nb6  20.Qh5 !  e5  21.Qh6  f6  22.Ba3  White is clearly better. }
12. Rxe4 { The white pieces look menacing. } 12... Nb6
{ One advantage of not having played ...b7-b6.  A.   12...Re8  13.Rh4  Nf8  14.Ng5  h6  15.Qh5  e5  16.Bd2 !  exd4  17.f4 !?   17.Rc1 !?  17...Be6  18.f5  Bd5  19.f6  Be5  20.Rf1  Rad8  21.Rg4  hxg5  22.Rxg5  g6  23.Bf4 !!  Bxf4  24.Qh6  Be3+  25.Kh1  Bxg2+  26.Kxg2  was a brilliant victory for White in a correspondence game: 1-0, Schubert, V. - Pott, B. corr. 2014. Who said the Colle was boring ?  B.   12...Nf6  13.Rh4  h6   13...Be7  14.Bf4  Qd8  15.Be5  h6  16.Qd2  +-  14.Bxh6 !  gxh6  15.Qd2  Ne8  16.Qxh6  f5  17.Qh8+  Kf7  18.Rh7+  Ng7  19.Rxg7+  1-0, Eliskases, E. - Cruz Filho, O., Rio de Janeiro 1943. }
13. Rh4 f5 14. Ne5 Bxe5
{ 14...Nd5  15.Qh5  Nf6  16.Qe2  Bd7  17.Bd2  Rac8  18.Nxd7  Qxd7  19.Re1  ±  White is better. }
15. dxe5 Rf7
{ 15...g6  16.Qe2  Bd7  17.Bg5  Bc6  18.Rd4  Nd5  19.Bc4  b5  20.Bb3  Rfc8  21.h4  a5  22.h5  White has the upper hand. }
16. Qh5 { Forcing ...g6, weakening the dark squares around Black's king. }
16... g6 17. Qe2 Bd7 18. Bg5 Bc6 19. Rc1 Qd7 20. f3 Raf8 21. h3 Qd5 22. b4
{ This position does not look very comfortable for Black. Having said that, the position is closed so converting White's advantage is easier said than done. }
*

