{ Later in this chapter, I will explain that I prefer the Zukertort system 6 b3 against this setup. However, the Colle positions 6 c3 are important for the overall understanding of the opening. Furthermore, this position can be reached through different move orders, anytime ...c7-c5 is answered with c2-c3. }
6... Bd6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1 Qc7 9. e4 cxd4 10. cxd4 dxe4 11. Nxe4
{ We have transposed to an isolani pawn type of position, a kind of reversed Panov Attack. In this particular case, the rook on e1 plays an important role as in the event of Nxe4, White is ready for the ultra sharp Rxe4 ! as previously mentioned, helping him fuel a dangerous attack. }
11... b6 12. Bg5 Bb7
{ It is important to realise why such a logical move is actually a bad one: }
13. Rc1 Qb8 14. Nxf6+ Nxf6 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Bxh7+
{ A nice sacrifice and recurring theme in such positions. White's attack is full of potential. }
16... Kxh7 17. Ne5
{ Double piece sac ! Black is lost on the spot as he cannot stop either of White's rooks from delivering a lethal blow on the third rank. }
