[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 5...Nbd7"]
[Black "Zukertort 6.b3 vs ...Qc7 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O Nbd7 6. b3
{ The Zukertort is probably the best reaction nowadays. It's far more complex than the Colle. White keeps a potential c4 up his sleeve in order to fight for the centre. }
6... Bd6 7. Bb2 Qc7
{ Black is playing for ...e5. This move also deprives White of typical Ne5 ideas.   7...O-O  8.Nbd2  A.  Qe7  The same idea, but the queen is on a safer square.  B.   8...Qc7  9.c4 !  This motif is very important. Its always a pleasure to see legendary players having such a great understanding of positional chess.  B1.  b6  A logical move, but White has an interesting resource.  B2.   9...e5  10.cxd5  exd4  11.exd4  Nxd5  12.Rc1  Nf4  13.Ne4 !  Nxd3  14.Qxd3  Bf4  15.Rc2  b6  16.dxc5  Nxc5  17.Nxc5  bxc5  18.Qc3  f6  19.Qxc5  White gets a pawn and the advantage. 1-0, 33 moves, Rubinstein, A. - Berger, J., Karlsbad 1907! Impressive positional understanding for the beginning of the 20th century !  10.cxd5  exd5  11.e4 !?  Active play, using the fact that the bishop is not yet on b7.  dxe4  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Bxe4  Bb7  14.Bxb7  Qxb7  15.Nh4 !?  The white pieces are coordinated nicely, especially when compared to their black counterparts.  g6  16.dxc5  Bxc5  17.Re1  Rad8  18.Qc1 !  Rfe8  19.Qc3  f6  20.Qc4+  Kg7  21.Qg4  White has initiative.  9.Ne5 !   9.a3  e5  leads to decent play for Black.  9...cxd4  10.exd4  Ba3  11.Bxa3  Qxa3  12.f4  This is OK for White. Although Black has managed to exchange a piece, the pressure is still on. Rf3 ideas are in the air and Black doesn't have much counterplay. }
8. c4
{ Again ! Its important to remember this positional idea, which is especially strong when the queen is on the c-file.   8.Nbd2  It is possible to ignore Black's idea altogether, although this strategy doesn't promise White much. Some precision from Black is still required nonetheless.  e5  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.Nxe5  Bxe5  11.Bb5+  A.  Bd7  B.   11...Ke7 !  A key defensive idea ! Otherwise Black would have been in trouble.  12.Bxe5  Qxe5  13.Qe2  The position is balanced, though I would take White here.  12.Bxe5  Qxe5  13.Bxd7+  Nxd7  14.c4  Nf6   14...O-O  15.Nf3  ±  15.cxd5  Qxd5  16.e4  Qc6  17.e5  Nd5  18.Nc4  O-O  19.Nd6  White has some pressure here. }
8... e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. h3
{ Simple but effective. White takes control of the g4-square and defends against threats to the h2-pawn. Meanwhile, the pressure on Blacks centre is still going strong. }
10... dxc4 11. bxc4 O-O
{ 11...Nxd3  12.Qxd3  O-O  13.Nc3  a6  14.Rad1  White is much better. } 12. Nc3
a6 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. f4
{ It is important to drive the bishop away first and only then to develop. }
14... Bd6 15. Qf3
{ Due to the immediate threat of e3-e4, White builds the pressure. } *

