9... Bb7 10. f4
{ 10.Qe2  A slower, more principled approach: develop first and then attack.  A.  Qe7  B.   10...Ne4  11.Bxe4  dxe4  12.Ndc4  Bxe5  13.dxe5  Qg5  14.Rad1  Bd5  15.Rd2  Rfd8  16.Rfd1  Nf8  17.Nd6 !?   17.Kh1  Bxc4  18.Qxc4  Rxd2  19.Rxd2  Rd8 =  1/2-1/2, 37 moves, Anton Guijarro, D. 2624 - Kotsur, P. 2559, Tromso 2014.  17...Ng6  18.h3  h5  19.Kh1  Rd7   19...Nxe5 ?!  20.Rxd5  exd5  21.Rxd5  ±  20.Qf1  Rc7  21.a4  Nh4  22.a5  ∞  C.   10...Rc8  11.Rad1  Qe7  12.f4  cxd4  13.exd4  g6  14.g4  Ba3  15.Bxa3 !   15.Ba1  Bb4  Unclear play. 1/ 2-1/2, 15 moves, Horvath, C. 2506 - Andreikin, D. 2342, Budapest 2003.  15...Qxa3  16.Ndf3  Qd6  17.g5  Ne4  18.Nxd7  Qxd7  19.Ne5  Qe7  20.Bxe4  dxe4  21.c4  f6  22.gxf6  Rxf6  23.Qe3  Looks good for White.  D.   10...Qc7  Black has many ideas,all of which are logical:  11.f4  Getting the queen to e2 early has the advantage of having better control over the e4-square.  a6   11...Ne4  12.Nxe4 !  dxe4  13.Bc4  a6  14.a4  cxd4  15.Nxd7  Qxd7  16.Bxd4  White has the better chances, and this is a rather archetypal position that can arise from the Colle and Zukertort when played correctly.  12.a4 !?  Rfc8  13.c4 !  White has firm control over the centre, so such a move doesn't come as a suprise.   13.Rad1 !?  b5 !  =∞  This is typical idea for Black which gives him good play.   13.Rf3 !?  A compelling attempt, linked to an exchange sacrifice:  c4  14.bxc4  dxc4  15.Ndxc4  Bxf3  16.Qxf3  Rab8  17.g4  b5  18.axb5  axb5  19.Nxd6  Qxd6  20.g5  Ne8  21.Bxh7+ !  +-  13...Nf8  14.cxd5  exd5   14...Nxd5  15.Ne4  Ng6  16.Ng5  +-  15.Ndf3  Ne4  16.Nh4 !  Now that the f5-square is vacant, White manages to get an attack going.  cxd4 ?!  17.Nf5 !!  White is close to winning.  11.f4  cxd4  12.exd4  Bb4  13.c3   13.Nxd7  Qxd7  14.c3  Bd6  15.Rae1  Rac8  16.f5  Qc7  17.g3  exf5  =+  0-1, 44 moves, Rakhmanov, A. 2602 - Vitiugov, N. 2734, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013.  13...Ba3  14.Bxa3  Qxa3  15.g4  → }
10... cxd4
{ Other possible ideas for Black include: A.   10...Rc8  11.Nxd7  Nxd7  12.dxc5  Rxc5  13.Bxh7+ !  Kxh7  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Bxg7 !  Well known idea of two bishops sacrifice.  Kxg7  16.Qg4+  Kh7  17.Rf3  Qf6  18.Rh3+  Qh6  19.Nf3  Be7  20.Ng5+  Bxg5  21.fxg5  Qxh3  22.Qxh3+  Kg8  23.g6  fxg6  24.Qxe6+  Kg7  25.Qxd7+  +-  1-0, 40 moves, Gelashvili, T. 2557 - Akobian, V. 2612, Philadelphia 2016.  B.   10...Ne4 !?  This move, be it here or in other lines of the Colle-Zukertort, is usually quite confusing and knowing how to react against it is at the essence of positional understanding.  11.Bxe4   11.Nxe4 !?  dxe4  12.Bc4  Nf6  13.Ng4  Be7  14.f5  exf5  15.Rxf5  g6  16.Re5 !?  promises an eventful middlegame.  11...dxe4  12.Ndc4 !  Be7   12...Nxe5  13.dxe5  Be7  14.Qg4  Ba6  15.Rfd1  Qe8  16.Nd6  Bxd6  17.Rxd6  +=  13.Nxd7  Qxd7  14.dxc5  Qxd1  15.Rfxd1  Bxc5  16.Ba3  Bxa3  17.Nxa3  Rfd8  18.Nb5  a6  19.Nd4  Rd6  20.c4  += }
11. exd4
{ Also deserving of attention is:   11.Nxd7  Qxd7  12.Bxd4 !?  White's idea becomes clear: keep the diagonal open.  Qe7  13.Qf3  Rac8  14.Qg3   14.Qh3 !?  Ne4  15.a4  h6  16.Nxe4  dxe4  17.Bc4  Bc5  18.c3  Bxd4  19.cxd4  Bd5  20.f5  Bxc4  21.f6  Qd8  22.bxc4  White has the initiative.  14...Bc5  15.Nf3  Bxd4  16.Nxd4  a6  17.Qh3  g6  18.g4  e5  19.fxe5  Qxe5  20.Rf4  Rce8  21.Raf1  Nd7  22.R1f3  Nc5  23.Qh6  Ne6  24.Nxe6  Rxe6  25.g5  Creative chess allowed White to put some pres-sureon his opponent. 1/2-1/2, 54 moves, Krasenkow, M. 2620 -Zhao Zong Yuan 2539, Canberra 2017. }
11... Ne4 12. Qe2
{ 12.Nxe4  dxe4  13.Bc4  Qc7  14.Kh1  Rac8  15.Rc1  This is highly unbalanced position.  Bd5   15...a6  16.a4  Nf6  17.f5 !  exf5  18.Rxf5  With initiative for White.  16.Bb5  Nb8  17.c4  Ba8  18.d5  Though the position is complicated, Whitesplay looks much more logical. 1/2-1/2, 32 moves, Slavin, A. 2364 - Bocharov, D. 2585, Sochi rapid 2017. }
12... f5 13. Nxe4
{ The theme is worth remembering.  White can try with slower but not necessarily weaker plan:   13.Ndf3 !?  Such positions are often confusing for both sides, and this is something that I have tried to address with the utmost care in this book. I think that this is one of the reasons why the Colle and Zukertort are not very popular openings. In this particular position, although the e4-knight is strong, Black has a problem: he has no central pawn breaks, while White still has the c4 break at his disposal.  Rc8  14.a3  Qe7  15.Kh1  Rf6  16.Rg1  Rh6  17.g4  Rh3  A funny rook manoeuvre.  18.Raf1  Ndf6  19.Bc1  Kh8  20.gxf5  exf5  21.Ng5  This is yet another possible line with normal play from both sides, and here too, White has better chances. }
13... fxe4
{ 13...dxe4 !?  14.Bc4  A nice example of how White can proceed in this type of position.  Qe7  15.a4  a6  16.Rac1   16.g4  Nf6  17.gxf5  Nd5 !  ⇆  16...Nf6  17.Qf2  Rac8  18.Be2  Having the c4-square as an asset helps White a lot.  Qc7  19.Qg3  Another complex middlegame in which I would take White. }
14. Bb5 Nxe5 15. fxe5 Be7
{ 15...Bc7 ?  16.Ba3  +-  Rf5  17.Qg4  Qg5  18.Qxg5  Rxg5  19.Bd7  Rg6  20.Be7  White is clearly better. 1-0, 28 moves, Dzagnidze, N. 2522 - Lei Tingjie 2528, Riyadh blitz 2017. }
16. Qg4 Qc8 17. Rxf8+ Bxf8 18. Rf1 a6 19. Be2 Qd7 20. Qh3 Re8 21. Bh5 g6 22.
Bg4 b5 23. Qg3 b4 24. Bc1 { White has a lasting initiative. } *

