1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O Nbd7 6. b3 Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2
b6 { A very natural move. } 9. Ne5 { White should seize this opportunity. }
9... Bb7 10. f4 cxd4 11. exd4 Ne4 12. Qe2 f5
{ White can try with slower but not necessarily weaker plan: } 13. Ndf3
{ Such positions are often confusing for both sides, and this is something that I have tried to address with the utmost care in this book. I think that this is one of the reasons why the Colle and Zukertort are not very popular openings. In this particular position, although the e4-knight is strong, Black has a problem: he has no central pawn breaks, while White still has the c4 break at his disposal. }
13... Rc8 14. a3 Qe7 15. Kh1 Rf6 16. Rg1 Rh6 17. g4 Rh3
{ A funny rook manoeuvre. } 18. Raf1 Ndf6 19. Bc1 Kh8 20. gxf5 exf5 21. Ng5
{ This is yet another possible line with normal play from both sides, and here too, White has better chances. }
