[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 5...Nbd7"]
[Black "6.Nbd2!? - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O Nbd7 6. Nbd2
{ White remains flexible without revealing his intentions, meaning it is not yet clear if we will see a Colle or a Zukertort. Either way, the knight belongs on d2 in both lines. }
6... Bd6
{ A.   6...b6  7.b3  Bb7  8.Bb2  transposes to Chapter 4.  B.   6...c4  7.Be2  b5  8.c3   8.b3  c3  9.Nb1  b4  10.a3  Qa5 !  ∓  It is almost impossible to untangle pieces from this situation.  8...Bb7  9.b3  transposes to other analysed lines.  C.   6...Qc7  7.b3 !?  e5  Thematic, but the timing is questionable.   7...Bd6  8.c4 !  transposes to positions in other chapters.  8.dxe5  Nxe5  9.Nxe5  Qxe5  10.Bb5+  Bd7  11.Bxd7+  Nxd7  12.Rb1  It isn't easy for Black to develop here due to Bb2 ideas combined with c4.  Bd6  13.Nf3  Qh5  14.c4  Nb6  15.cxd5  Qxd5  16.Qxd5  Nxd5  17.Bb2 !  With g7 hanging and Rfd1 coming, Black has tactical problems.   17.Rd1 ?  Nc3  ∓  17...O-O  18.Rfd1  Rad8  19.Rxd5  Bxh2+  20.Nxh2  Rxd5  21.Nf1  Rfd8  22.Rc1  b6  23.f3  ±  with good winning chances. }
7. Re1 O-O 8. e4
{ An intriguing idea. In the Colle, White goes c3 first, but this is a more direct attempt.  A transposition to the Colle via   8.c3  is perfectly fine. }
8... dxe4
{ 8...c4  9.Bf1  Nxe4   9...dxe4  10.Nxc4 !  exf3  11.Nxd6  fxg2  12.Bxg2  ±  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Nd2 !  f5   11...Qc7  12.g3  Nf6  13.Nxc4  ±  12.Nxc4  Bc7  13.a4  Nf6  14.Ne5  Qe7  15.c3  Rd8  16.Qb3  ∞  Leads to a complicated middlegame. }
9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Rxe4 Be7
{ Other defensive ideas include: A.   10...b6  11.Rh4  f5  12.Qe2  Nf6  13.dxc5  Bxc5  14.Bd2  ±  White is better here thanks to harmonious development and a target on e6.  B.   10...Nf6  11.Rh4 !  cxd4   11...b6  12.Bg5  g6  13.Be4  Rb8  14.dxc5  White is clearly better.  Be7  15.Qxd8  Bxd8  16.c6  Nxe4  17.Bxd8  Rxd8  18.c7  +-  And White wins.  12.Bg5  g6  13.Bxg6 !!  fxg6  14.Rxd4  +-  C.   10...Re8  C1.  11.dxc5  C2.   11.Rh4  Nf8  12.Ng5 !?  f5 !?   12...h6  13.Qh5  Re7  14.Bh7+ !!  Nxh7  15.Nxh7  Kxh7  16.Bxh6 !  White wins.   12...g6  13.Qf3  f5  14.Qh3  h5  15.Bd2  cxd4  16.Rxd4  Bxh2+  17.Qxh2  Qxd4  18.Bc3  Qc5  19.Bc4 !  ±  with a strong attack.  13.Qh5  g6  14.Qh6  Be7  White has several options with which to proceed in order to keep a small a edge like  15.dxc5 !?  and 15 Rh3 !?.  But   15.Nxh7 ?!  only needs to a draw:  Bxh4  16.Nxf8  Rxf8  17.Qxg6+  Kh8  18.Qh6+ =  11...Bxc5  12.b4 !?  Be7  13.Rb1  Bf6   13...b6  14.Bf4  Bb7  15.Rd4  ±  14.Bf4  Nf8  15.Re3  Ng6  16.Bg3  a5  17.a3  axb4  18.axb4  b6  19.c4  Bb7  20.Qc2  Rc8  21.c5  → }
11. Qe2 cxd4
{ A.   11...b6  12.d5 !  Nf6  13.dxe6  Bxe6  14.Rxe6 !  A typical exchange sacrifice.  fxe6  15.Ng5  Qd6  16.Nxe6  Rfe8  17.Bf4  +-  B.   11...Nf6  12.Rh4  g6  13.dxc5  White seized initiative. }
12. Rxd4 Bf6 13. Rc4 Nb6 14. Rg4 g6 15. Bh6 Re8 16. Ne5
{ White's pieces are developed and active, which is more than can be said for Black. }
