[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 5...Nbd7"]
[Black "Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O Nbd7
{ Putting the knight on d7 is universally considered to be the antidote to the Colle. The idea is simple: Black deprives White of dxc5 followed by e4, as can be seen in lines where the knight is on c6. The lines in this book cast doubt over this universal truth.The Zukertort is about having a bishop on b2. Similarities with Queens Indians with 4. e3 are often obvious, which makes the system fully playable, and potentially dangerous. Furthermore, not playing c4 too early can help White as the square can be used for pieces on many occasions.   We have examined both the Colle and the Zukertort, but I believe the latter  6.b3  to be the trickier system to handle from Blacks point of view in this  5...Nbd7  line. Illustrating this, we saw that Blacks attempt at an early  ...e5  doesn't come so easily.   Finally, we uncovered that  6.Nbd2 !?  is an interesting and flexible move order in order to keep one's options open before committing to either line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 5...Bd6"]
[Black "Chapter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

