[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 5...Bd6"]
[Black "Zukertort vs 8...Qc7, 8...Qe7 and 8...b6 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O Bd6 6. b3
{ Indeed, this line is not essential as White can play 6. dxc5 and probably transpose to other lines in this book. However, I have purposefully included it as I consider it very important in order to have a good understanding of the Colle-Zukertort strategy. }
6... O-O 7. Bb2 Nc6
{ I have previously mentioned that having a knight on d7 is best against the Colle, but this line also has a very good reputation against the Zukertort. With a modern outlook on forgotten systems such as the Colle and Zukertort, I doubt that such outdated judgements will retain much value. }
8. Nbd2 Qe7
{ Not Black's only idea.  There are other moves, but I want to emphasise the main point of 8... Qe7, which is that if White goes for the logical   9.Ne5  ,  then  9...Qc7 !  is a blow to White, who has to deal with the threats on e5 and Nb4 as the pawn on c2 is hanging.  Of course, another idea behind ...Qe7 is ...e5:   9.a3  e5 !  A.   8...b6  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.c4  dxc4  11.Nxc4  Bb7  12.Qe2  Qe7  13.Ng5  Rfd8  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.Bxh7+  Kf8  16.Ne4  Qh4  17.Nxc5  bxc5  18.Bc2  leads to easier play for White.  B.   8...Qc7  9.dxc5 !  Bxc5  10.c4  A typical move, especially when the queen is on c7.  B1.  Rd8  B2.   10...dxc4  11.Nxc4  Nb4  12.Ng5  Rd8  13.Be5  Qd7  14.Bxf6 !   14.Ne4  Nxe4  15.Bxe4  f5  16.Qxd7  Rxd7  17.Bf3  Nd5  18.Rfd1  b5  19.Na5  Bb6  20.b4  Bxa5  21.bxa5  with some pressure in the endgame .1-0, 57 moves, Brousek, J. -Zednik, M., Corr. 2004.  14...gxf6  15.Ne4  Be7  16.Qg4+  Kh8  17.Ncd6 !  +-  11.cxd5  Rxd5  12.Qe2 !   12.Bc4  Rd8  13.Qe2  Bd6  14.Rac1  Qe7  15.Rfd1  Ba3  ∞  1-0, 45 moves, Nikolov, T. 2200 - Gunev, Z. 2275, Ruse 1984.  12...Rd8  13.Rac1  Qe7  14.Ne4  Nxe4  15.Bxe4  Bd7  16.Qc2  Another example which gives White big advantage. }
9. c4
{ We see that this is a usual resource which White employs to prevent Black from easily playing e5.  The alternative is also logical:   9.dxc5  Bxc5  A. Even:  10.c4  B.   10.a3 !?  e5 !?   10...Rd8  11.b4  Bd6  12.c4  dxc4  13.Nxc4  e5  14.Qc2  a6  15.Ng5  h6  16.Ne4  Nxe4  17.Bxe4  Bc7  18.Rac1  Bd7  19.f4  White's chances are preferable. 1-0, 70 moves, Brousek, J. - Da Silva, F., Corr. 2003.   10...a5  11.c4  gives White slightly better chances.  11.b4  Bb6   11...Bd6  12.c4  e4  13.Bxf6  Qxf6  14.Bxe4  White is clearly better.  12.b5  e4  13.bxc6  bxc6  14.Bxf6  gxf6  15.Nd4  exd3  16.Nxc6  Qd6  17.Nd4  dxc2  18.Qxc2  I am not sure that White has any advantage here, perhaps it is only that Whites play is easier.  10...Ba3  11.Bxa3  Qxa3  12.e4  Rd8  13.Qe2  Qe7   13...dxe4  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Bxe4  Bd7  16.Qe3  Be8  17.h4  h6  18.g4  b6  19.g5  Qc5  With aproximate equality.  14.exd5  exd5  15.Qxe7  Nxe7  16.c5 !  Nc6  17.a3  a5  18.Rfe1  g6  19.Bb5  Kg7  20.Bxc6  bxc6  21.Rac1  with a slight edge for White in this endgame. }
9... cxd4 10. exd4 Ba3 { With the queen on e7, this is often a key idea. } 11.
Bxa3 Qxa3 12. c5
{ This type of position is usually in White's favour. It is not much at the moment, but if White manages to connect the queenside pawns with a3 and b4, this will lead to a pleasant advantage. }
12... b6 13. Qc1 Qxc1 14. Rfxc1 Bb7 15. a3 bxc5 16. dxc5
{ A double edged idea.  It is also possible to play more safely:   16.Rxc5  a5  17.Rac1  Rfc8  18.h4  h6  19.g3  Kf8  20.Bb5  Ne7  21.Ne5  Nf5  22.Ndf3  with nice play in the endgame for White. }
16... a5
{ 16...e5  17.Bb5  Nd7  18.b4  a6  19.Ba4  Ndb8  20.Rd1  Rd8  21.Nf1  d4  22.Bb3  also gives White better chances. }
17. Rab1 e5 18. Bb5 Na7 19. Ba4
{ White managed to maximise his advantage in this endgame. } *

