1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O Bd6 6. b3 O-O 7. Bb2 Nc6 8. Nbd2
Nb4
{ A logical response, Black pushes the strong bishop away from its active square.  Another alternative is also possible and was played at high level. Black released the tension by taking on d4:   8...cxd4  9.exd4  b6  10.a3  Bb7  11.Qe2   11.Ne5  Qc7  12.Qe2  Ne7  13.f4  b5  14.Rf3  Rac8  The idea behind this move is to play the knight to e4.  15.Rc1  b4  16.a4  Ng6  17.Rcf1  Ne4  18.Rh3  f5  19.Bxe4  dxe4  20.Qh5  +-  1-0, 28 moves, Bruzon Batista, L. 2652 - Anand, V. 2803, Leon 2006.  11...Ne7  12.Ne5  Rc8   12...Ng6  13.f4  Qc7  14.Rae1  Rac8  15.Rf2 !  Rce8  16.g3  Ne7  17.g4  Nd7  18.Qe3  Ng6  19.Qh3  Ndxe5  20.fxe5  Be7  21.Nf3  f5  22.Bc1  Bc8  23.Ref1  ±  A good example of how White can obtain an attacking position. 1-0, 37 moves, Balashov, Y. 2414 - Miroshnichenko, P. 2202, Moscow 2011.  In the following game White played more cautious: A.  13.Rfe1  B.   13.f4  Bb8  The point of this move is to transfer the knight from e7 to d6, from where it will have firm control over the e4-square.  14.Rf3  B1.  g6  B2.   14...Nf5  15.Rh3  Ne4  16.Nxe4  dxe4  17.Bxe4  Bxe4  18.Qxe4  f6  19.Ng4  Qd5  20.Qd3  Bxf4   20...b5  21.Rf1  a6  22.Ne3  Nxe3  23.Qxh7+  Kf7  24.Rxe3  Though White is a pawn up, Black does have some compensation. 0-1, 67 moves, Jussupow, A. 2608 - Jobava, B. 2646, Turin 2006.  21.c4  Qd7  22.Rf1  Bb8  23.d5  ±  White's initiative looks strong.  15.Rh3  h5  16.Rf1  Nf5  17.Ndf3  For now, Black's position looks solid enough on the kingside, though still I prefer White's chances. Let's play a few more moves.  Ne4   17...Kg7  18.Ng5 !  Qe7  19.c4  a5  20.Kh1  Kg8  21.c5  →  18.c4  Bd6  19.g4 !  hxg4  20.Nxg4  Nf6  21.Bxf5  exf5  22.Nh6+  Kg7  23.c5 !  White is better.  13...Ng6  14.g3  Qe7  15.f3 !?  Planning Nf1-Ne3 and avoiding ...Ne4.  Rc7  16.Nf1  Rfc8  17.Ne3  Bxe5  18.dxe5  Nd7  19.f4  Nc5  20.Bd4  Nxd3  ∞  The draw was perhaps agreed upon prematurely as I think this positon slighlty favors White. 1/2-1/2, 20 moves, Tomashevsky, E. 2702 - Schroeder, J. 2552, Berlin 2018. }
9. Be2 b6 10. a3 Nc6 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. Qe2 Rc8
{ Black maintains the tension in the centre. } 13. Rad1
{ Played only once but its a suitable strategy; White centralises his play. }
13... Qe7
{ A.   13...cxd4  14.exd4  Qe7   14...Ne7  15.Ne5  Nf5  16.Rfe1  Bb8  17.Nf1  Nd6  18.c4  White achieves harmonious play, with decent chances for an advantage.  15.Ra1 !  Although White has lost a tempo, Black has made an early pawn exchange on d4, which White is happy about as the e4-square is better guarded and he can try his usual plan with f4 and Rf3 without worrying about counterplay linked with.. .Ne4.  Qc7   15...Rc7  16.Ne5  Rfc8  17.f4  Qf8  18.Rf3  Ne7  19.c3  leads to a typical play for White.  16.g3  Ne7  17.Rac1  Qb8  18.Ne5   18.Rfe1  Rc7  19.Ng5  Qc8  20.h4  b5  21.c4  bxc4  22.bxc4  h6  23.Nxe6  fxe6  24.c5  ∞  1/2-1/2, 43 moves, Rakhmanov, A. 2676 - Azarov, S. 2582, Minsk 2017.  18...Nf5  19.f4  with the initiative for White.  B.   13...Ne7  14.dxc5  bxc5  15.c4  gives White preferable chances. }
14. dxc5 bxc5 15. e4 Nd7 16. Rfe1 d4
{ 16...Qd8  17.exd5  exd5  18.Bf5  Rc7  19.Nc4  White is better. } 17. Nc4 Nce5
18. Nfxe5 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Qh5 Qc7 21. Bc1 Bf4 22. Bxf4 Qxf4 23. e5 g6
24. Qe2
{ With equal chances, though we can still say that it was White who was trying for an intiative the whole time. @@HeaderStart@@Conclusion@@HeaderEnd@@ This is another way of handling this line for Black. In the position arising after 8. Nbd2, Black has a few ideas. Generally speaking, he develops in a harmonious way and complex play normally follows.White will use the e5-square to generate attacking chances while Black will try and play along the c-file and eventually transfer his knights to better squares. }
