{ Another alternative is also possible and was played at high level. Black released the tension by taking on d4: }
8... cxd4 9. exd4 b6 10. a3 Bb7 11. Qe2 Ne7 12. Ne5 Rc8 13. f4 Bb8
{ The point of this move is to transfer the knight from e7 to d6, from where it will have firm control over the e4-square. }
14. Rf3 g6 15. Rh3 h5 16. Rf1 Nf5 17. Ndf3
{ For now, Black's position looks solid enough on the kingside, though still I prefer White's chances. Let's play a few more moves. }
17... Ne4 18. c4 Bd6 19. g4 hxg4 20. Nxg4 Nf6 21. Bxf5 exf5 22. Nh6+ Kg7 23. c5
{ White is better. } *

