[Black "Chapter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7
{ Variation 1  6.Nbd2  Be7  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  Nbd7  9.Ne5   Variation 2  6.Nbd2  Be7  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  Nbd7  9.c4   Variation 3  6.Nbd2  Be7  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  Nbd7  9.c4  with 10 Rc1.   Variation 4  6.Nbd2  Bd6  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  Nbd7  9.c4   Variation 5  6.Nbd2  Bd6  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  Nbd7  9.Ne5   Variation 6  6.Nbd2  Bd6  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  c5   Variation 7  6.Nbd2  Bd6  7.Qe2   Variation 8  6.Nbd2  Bd6  7.Qe2  with 10 Ne5.   Variation 9  6.b3  Bd6  7.Ba3! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 4...b6"]
[Black "Zukertort w/ 9.Ne5 vs 6...Be7 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6
{ This is one of the main ideas Black can employ and it is probably considered as his best option. Black develops quickly while not committing to a particular setup. One idea is to put the pieces on the most aggressive squares. We will see that ...Ne4 is often an asset for Black here followed by ...f5. }
5. O-O Bb7
{ Black develops the light-squared bishop before deciding on what to do with the other. Though it resembles a Queen's Indian, differences include that White hasnt played an early c4, which may change the physiology of the position altogether.   5...Ba6  6.Bxa6  Nxa6  7.c4  Nb8  8.Nc3  Nbd7  9.Qa4  Be7  10.cxd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Qc6  White wins a pawn. Just a small example how to fight against such ideas. }
6. Nbd2
{ We are mostly going to look at the Zukertort setup against this line. White wants to play Nbd2, b3, Bb2, and the move order isn't critical at such an early stage. I believe that 6 Nbd2 is more flexible, saving the 7 Qe2 option,which we shall also investigate.However, 6 b3 allows for rapid Ba3 ideas that we will examine as a side option in the last subchapter. So it is up to you to choose your move order ! }
6... Be7
{ This is conservative chess, Black develops on a solid square rather than an active one.  Going against basic opening rules, developing the knight first can create a problem for Black, and deprives him of positional ideas involving Ba6:   6...Nbd7  7.Qe2   7.c4  Bd6  8.Qe2  Ne4  9.cxd5  exd5  10.Ba6  Qc8  11.Bxb7  Qxb7  12.b3  O-O  13.Bb2  Rae8  didn't yield much in: 1/2-1/2, 18 moves, Tomashevsky, E. 2710 - Jakovenko, D. 2710, Sochi rapid 2017.  7...Ne4  8.Ba6 !?  Bxa6  9.Qxa6  Nxd2  10.Bxd2  Bd6  11.c4  += }
7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2 Nbd7 9. Ne5
{ A typical idea in the Zukertort line. Before even going c4, White places his knight on its natural square. It is very important to understand the strategical notions behind this position for both White and Black.For 9 c4,see the next two subchapters. }
9... c5
{ Not the only move.  Black can copy White, leading to a very complex strategical game: A.   9...Nxe5  10.dxe5  A1.  Nd7  A2.   10...Ne4  11.f4 !?  Nxd2  12.Qxd2  f6  13.Rad1   13.exf6  Bxf6  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.Rae1  e5  16.Qc3  ∞  13...fxe5  14.Bxe5  Bf6  15.Qe2  Qe7  16.h4  Bxe5  17.Qh5  g6  18.Qxe5  Even if Black swaps queens, White retains an edge due to the better bishop.  11.f4  g6  12.Qg4  Nc5  13.Nf3  Nxd3  14.cxd3  Re8  15.h4  h5  16.Qh3  Kg7  17.Rad1  Qc8  18.Ng5  Rh8  19.f5 !  with a strong attack.   19.Qg3  +=  1/2-1/2, 37 moves, Vasiljevic, D. 2385 - Dokhoian, Y. 2570, Igalo 1994.  B.   9...Ne4  B1.  10.f4  B2.   10.Nxe4  Nxe5   10...dxe4  11.Nxd7  Qxd7  12.Bc4  b5  13.Be2  a5  14.c4  b4  15.Qc2  c5  16.Rad1  f5  17.Rd2  Rad8  18.Rfd1  Qc7  19.dxc5  Rxd2  20.Rxd2  +=  11.Nf6+  Bxf6  12.dxe5  Be7  13.Qg4  c5  14.a4  Qc7  15.a5  bxa5  16.Ra4 !?  Bc6  17.Rf4 !  with an attack. A noteworthy rook manoeuvre.  10...f5  11.Nxd7  Qxd7  12.Nf3  Bd6  13.c4  c5  14.Qe2  Qe7  15.a4  a5  16.Rac1  Rac8  17.Rfd1  Rfd8  18.cxd5  exd5  19.Ne5 !  →  Preparing g2-g4.   19.dxc5  bxc5  20.Be5  ∞  0-1, 32 moves, Kosanovic, G. 2403 - Vidic, S. 2284, Palic 2014. }
10. f4 Ne4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Be2
{ 12.Bc4  Nxe5  13.fxe5 !?  Even after   13.dxe5  Black has some problems:  Qxd1  14.Raxd1  Rad8  15.g4  Rxd1  16.Rxd1  Rd8  17.Rxd8+  Bxd8  18.Kf2  Bh4+  19.Kg2  White has the better endgame. 1-0, 35 moves, Fominykh, M. 2240 - Sachdev, T. 2189, Heraklio 2002.  13...Qc7  14.Qe2  Rac8  15.Rf2 !  ↑  White wants to double alongthe f-file and play Qg4, with mounting pressure on f7. 1-0, 32 moves, Vasiljevic, D. 2361 - Krabbe Rachut, H. 1705, Bad Zwischenahn 2003. }
12... f5 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. dxc5 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Bxc5 16. Kf2 Rfd8 17. c4 Kf7 18.
a3 Be7 19. b4
{ Another good demonstration of how to transform a position into a slightly favourable endgame. 1/2-1/2, 59 moves, Kovacevic, V. 2540 - Handoko, E. 2420, Indonesia 1983. }
*

