[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 4...b6"]
[Black "Zukertort 9.c4 vs 6...Be7 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2
Nbd7 9. c4
{ A logical response and in the style of the Queen's Indian. White wants to combine various ideas, most of which enabled by having a pawn on c4. }
9... c5
{ A sound response from Black. His plan is ... Rc8, ...Qc7 and so on, developing in a natural way, all the while building pressure on Whites centre with his c5- and d5-pawns.  Playing as if the bishop were on d6 is possible for Black, though not advisable:   9...Ne4  10.Rc1  A.  f5  B.   10...Bd6  B1.  11.cxd5  B2.   11.Qc2  f5  12.Rfd1  Qe7  13.cxd5  exd5  14.Ne5 !  c5 ?!  Better was   14...Rac8  15.Ndf3  c5  16.Qe2  with a slight edge for White due to the strong outpost on e5.  15.Nxe4  fxe4  16.Bxe4 !  Nice idea, resourceful tactics along the d-file !  dxe4  17.Nxd7  Qxd7  18.dxc5  Bxh2+  19.Kxh2  Qc7+  20.Kg1  Rac8  21.Qc4+  +-  1-0, 31 moves, Mamedyarov, S. 2736 - Idani, P. 2569, Baku 2015.  11...exd5  12.Ne5  Nxd2  13.Qxd2  Nf6  14.Qe2  Qe7  15.Rc2  c5  16.Nf3  Ne4  17.Ba6  Rad8  18.Bxb7  Qxb7  19.Rd1  Rfe8  20.Nd2  Qe7  21.dxc5  bxc5  22.Nxe4   22.Qg4  Nf6  23.Bxf6  Qxf6  24.g3  Bf8  25.Qf3  ∞  1/2-1/2, 46 moves, Miles, A. 2630 - Sowray, P. 2350, England 1997.  22...Qxe4  23.Rcd2  Bc7  24.Qf3  White has preferable chances here.  11.Qe2  c6  12.Rc2  Bd6  13.Rfc1  Qe7  14.cxd5  cxd5  15.Ba6 !  White's main focus here is the c-file and this move is part of the plan.  Ndf6  16.Ne5  Nxd2  17.Rxd2  Rac8  18.Rdc2  Rxc2  19.Rxc2  Bxe5  20.dxe5  Ne4  21.Bd4  Rb8  22.f3  Ng5  23.Rc3  White is better. 1-0, 40 moves, Taimanov, M. 2406 - Meiling, H. 2028, Naumburg 2002. }
10. Qe2 { 10.Rc1 !?  See the next subchapter. } 10... cxd4
{ Black can also go for another typical idea:   10...Ne4  A.  11.cxd5  B.   11.Rfd1  Qc7   11...cxd4  12.exd4  Ndf6  13.Ne5  Bd6  14.Nf1  Be7  15.Rac1  Nd7  16.cxd5  exd5  17.Nc6  Bxc6  18.Rxc6  Ndf6  19.Rdc1  +=  Old games are often very instructive and show how deep an understanding those players already had at that time. 1-0, 35 moves, Petrovs, V. - Reilly, B., Warsaw 1935.  12.Rac1  Bf6  13.cxd5  exd5  14.Bb5 !?   14.Ba6 !?  or 14 Bb1 !? also makes sense.  14...Nd6  15.Ba6  Rfe8  16.Rc2  Rac8  17.Rdc1  Nb8  18.Bxb7  Nxb7  19.h3  +=  White is in the driver's seat. 1-0, 52 moves, Hoi, C. 2390 - Sarbok, T. 2285. Germany 2000.  11...exd5  12.Rfd1  f5  13.Ba6  Qc8  14.Bxb7  Qxb7  15.Nf1  Rac8  16.dxc5 !  These structures aren't easy to manage for Black, even if the engine thinks they are playable.  bxc5  17.Ne5  Nxe5  18.Bxe5  Bf6  19.Bxf6  Rxf6  20.Rac1  f4  21.f3  Nd6  22.exf4  Nb5  23.Ng3  Nd4  24.Qd2  Qf7  25.b4  ±  1-0, 34 moves, Eliskases, E. - Maderna, C., Buenos Aires 1953. }
11. Nxd4
{ White borrows a strategy from the QGA, where pieces occupy the centre rather than pawns.  Taking with the pawn is also possible:   11.exd4  Re8  12.Rac1  Rc8  13.Rfd1  Bf8  14.Ne5  A.  Nxe5  B.   14...dxc4  15.bxc4  Nxe5   15...Qc7  16.f4 !  Taking full control of the centre.  g6  17.Rf1  Bg7  18.Ndf3  Bxf3  19.Qxf3  Qd6  20.h3  Nb8  21.Rfd1  Nfd7  22.Be4  Qc7  23.Rc2  White has better chances. 1-0, 47 moves, Koneru, H. 2607 - Kosintseva, T. 2496. Beijing 2013.  16.dxe5  Nd7  17.Be4  Qc7  18.Bxb7  Qxb7  19.Ne4  Nc5  20.Nd6  Bxd6  21.exd6  f6  22.Bd4  Nd7  23.h4  Qc6  24.h5  White managed to obtain the initiative. 1-0, 49 moves, Mamedyarov, S. 2804 - Ju Wenjun 2572. Internet rapid 2018.  15.dxe5  Nd7  16.cxd5  Bxd5  17.Nc4 !   17.Rxc8  Qxc8  18.a3  Nc5  ∞  1/2-1/2, 57 moves, Dalton, J. 2045 - Turner, M. 1933. Newcastle 2018.  17...Nc5  18.Bb1  Qg5  19.g3  Red8  20.Nd6  Bxd6  21.exd6  with the initiative for White. }
11... Nc5 12. Bc2 dxc4
{ Black can also play:   12...Qd7  13.Rfd1  Rfd8  14.a3  Rac8  15.Rac1  Ba6  16.N2f3  dxc4  17.bxc4  Qb7  18.Nb5  Rxd1+  19.Rxd1  Qa8  20.Be5  Bb7  21.Nd6  Bxf3  22.gxf3  Rd8  23.f4  g6  24.a4  h5  25.h3  The position remains complicated. }
13. Nxc4 Qd5 14. f3 Ba6 15. e4 Qb7 16. b4 e5 17. Nf5 Ne6 18. Bxe5 Bxb4 19. Kh1
Nd7 20. Bb2 Qc7 21. Bb3
{ Of course, Kramnik shows his deep understanding of such semi-closed positions. His pieces are very well coordinated. 1-0, 67 moves, Kramnik, V. 2777 - Riazantsev, A. 2646, Berlin 2015. }
