1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2
Nbd7 9. c4 c5 10. Rc1
{ A reasonable alternative. The idea is to play against a potential queen on c7. }
10... Rc8
{ 10...Ne4  11.Qe2  Rc8  12.cxd5  exd5  13.Ba6   13.Rfd1  is another good option, with the idea of Ne5 when Black goes ... Ndf6. For example,  Rc7  14.Ba6  Bxa6  15.Qxa6  with pressure on the d-file. Black is less organised than in Byrne's game.  13...Bxa6  14.Qxa6  Ndf6  15.Rfd1  Qc7 ?!  16.dxc5  bxc5  17.Nxe4 !   17.Be5 ?!  Qd7  18.Nxe4  Nxe4  19.Rd3  Bf6  20.Bxf6  Nxf6  21.Qa5  Qe7  22.Rdc3  Ne4  23.R3c2  with an edge for White anyway. 1-0, 47 moves, Byrne, D. - Seidman, H., Pittsburgh 1946.  17...dxe4  18.Ne5  would have given White a clear advantage. }
11. Qe2 Rc7
{ This is considered the best here. Nonetheless, the position remains full of life.  A.   11...cxd4  12.Nxd4 !?  Nc5  13.Bb1  ∞  B.   11...Re8  12.Rfd1  Rc7  13.cxd5  exd5   13...Nxd5  14.Ne5  White is slightly better.  14.Bf5   14.Ne5  Bd6  15.Nxd7  Nxd7  16.Ba6  Ba8  17.Bb5  Re6  18.Nf3  I think White is doing well here, too.  14...Bd6  15.dxc5  bxc5 !?   15...Nxc5  16.b4  Ba6  17.b5  Bb7  18.Nb3 !  Nfe4  19.Nfd2  Nxd2  20.Qxd2  Qg5  21.Nd4  I managed to gain some advantage from this comlicated line. 0-1, 41 moves, Pavlovic, M. 2190 - Gligoric, S. 2480, Belgrade 1998.  16.Nc4  Bf8  ∞  C.   11...dxc4  12.Bxc4 !?  A noteworthy reaction. White usually takes with the knight, but this move leads to a different plan altogether.  Rc7  13.dxc5  Nxc5  14.Nd4  a6  15.a4  Qa8  16.f4 !  The d2-knight stays put to cover the e4-square while the minor pieces on c4 and d4 thrive in the centre.  Rfc8  17.N2f3  Bd5  18.f5  Bxc4  19.Rxc4  Qd5  20.Rd1  Nxb3  21.Nc6  Rxc6  22.Rxd5  Rxc4  23.Rd1  Rxa4  24.Nd4  Nc5  25.Qf3  Rd8  26.Nc6  White got a better position.1-0, 37 moves, Markus, R. 2632 - Horvath, D. 2356, Hungary 2015. }
12. Rfd1 Qa8 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Ne5
{ This is probably critical here, before Black successfully consolidates with ...Rd8 for example. }
14... Nxe5
{ A.   14...cxd4  15.Rxc7  Nxe5  16.Bxh7+  Kxh7  17.Rxe7  Nxe7  18.Qh5+  Kg8  19.Qxe5  Rd8  20.exd4  Ng6  21.Qg3  White keeps the pawn.  B.   14...Rd8 ?  15.Bxh7+ !  Thematic !  Kxh7  16.Qh5+  Kg8  17.Qxf7+  Kh7  18.dxc5  White wins. }
15. dxe5 Nb4
{ 15...Rd7  16.Nc4  Rfd8  17.a3  Nc7  18.f3  Bc6  19.Qc2  Kh8  20.Nd6  Bxd6  21.exd6  Rxd6  22.b4  White has compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
16. Bb1 Rd7 { 16...Bxg2  17.e4  wins for White. } 17. a3 Nc6 18. Nc4 Rfd8 19.
Rxd7 Rxd7 20. Rd1 Rxd1+ 21. Qxd1 g6 22. Nd6 Qd8 23. Bc2 Ba8 24. Bc3
{ In this rather unusual endgame White has better chances. } *

