1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2
Nbd7 9. c4 c5 10. Rc1
{ A reasonable alternative. The idea is to play against a potential queen on c7. }
10... Rc8 11. Qe2 dxc4 12. Bxc4
{ A noteworthy reaction. White usually takes with the knight, but this move leads to a different plan altogether. }
12... Rc7 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Nd4 a6 15. a4 Qa8 16. f4
{ The d2-knight stays put to cover the e4-square while the minor pieces on c4 and d4 thrive in the centre. }
16... Rfc8 17. N2f3 Bd5 18. f5 Bxc4 19. Rxc4 Qd5 20. Rd1 Nxb3 21. Nc6 Rxc6 22.
Rxd5 Rxc4 23. Rd1 Rxa4 24. Nd4 Nc5 25. Qf3 Rd8 26. Nc6
{ White got a better position.1-0, 37 moves, Markus, R. 2632 - Horvath, D. 2356, Hungary 2015. }
