[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 4...b6"]
[Black "Zukertort Quick c2-c4 vs 6...Bd6 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. b3
{ One of the most logical ideas. } 7... O-O 8. Bb2 Nbd7 9. c4
{ We don't play with an early queen to e2 here, as the focus is on different plans.  For   9.Ne5 !?  see the next subchapter. }
9... Ne4
{ An aggressive setup, which is typical for Black in these types of positions. }
10. cxd5
{ With a specific plan in mind. There are, of course, other plans.  A. Premature is:   10.Ne5  Nxd2  11.Qxd2  Bxe5  12.dxe5  Nc5  Black is OK.  B.   10.Rc1 !?  f5  11.cxd5  Only now White goes for the Ne5 idea.   11.Ne5  Bxe5 !  12.dxe5  Ndc5  Again we see that this motive works well for Black so White has to be more carefull when entering on e5.  11...exd5  12.Ne5  Qe7  13.Ndf3 !  The plan is to take on d7, replace the exchanged knight with the other, and then play f3.  B1.  c5  B2.   13...Ndf6  14.Nh4  g6  15.g3   15.f3 !  It is possible to go without g3.  Ng5  16.Qd2 !  Due to an exposed kingside structure, Black will struggle to defend against White's threats.  15...c5  16.f3  Ng5  17.Qd2  Bxe5   17...Nf7  18.Nhxg6 !  hxg6  19.Nxg6  Qe6  20.Nh4 !  cxd4  21.Bxd4  ↑  18.dxe5  Nd7  19.f4  Ne4  20.Bxe4 !  dxe4   20...fxe4  21.Qe2  ↑  /\Qg4, f5/e6  21.Rfd1  White is clearly better.  14.Nxd7  Qxd7  15.Ne5  Qe6  16.f3  Nf6  17.Qe1 !  Of course, White goes for the king side, trying to create additional pressure.  Rac8  18.Qh4  The next plan is to go h3 and g4, making the f5-pawn a target.  Bxe5  19.dxe5  Nd7  20.f4  c4  21.Be2  b5  22.b4 !  Taking control of the c5-square while intending Bd4 followed by g4. }
10... exd5 11. Ne5 Qe7 12. f4
{ A compelling setup. Exchanging the c-pawn for the e-pawn allows White to create a certain imbalance on the kingside. }
12... Nxd2
{ A.   12...Ndf6  13.Rf3 !?  Nxd2  14.Qxd2  Ne4  15.Qe2  f6  16.Bxe4  gives White an edge.  B.   12...f6  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Bc4+  Kh8  15.Ng6+ !!  hxg6  16.f5 !  +-  C.   12...f5  13.g4 !?  Nxe5   13...g6  14.gxf5  gxf5  15.Bxe4  dxe4  16.Kh1  White has a strong attack.  14.dxe5  Bc5  15.Qe2  Nxd2  16.Qxd2  fxg4  Sacrificing a pawn, but White can afford it.  17.Qf2 !  Coming to g3  g6  18.Qg3  Bc8  19.h3 !  with a strong initiative. }
13. Qxd2 Nf6
{ 13...f6  14.Nf3 !  To assess the position is the most difficult part of these sytems. Here, White cunningly avoids further exchanges as the knight on f3 is a better piece than its counterpart on d7, as we will see.  Rfe8  15.Rae1  c5  16.Qc2   16.h4 !?  The idea is h5 and Nh4.  Rac8  17.h5  c4  18.Bf5  Ba6  19.bxc4  Bxc4  20.Rf2  White has created good attacking chances.  16...Nf8  17.dxc5  bxc5  18.Nh4  g6  19.Rf3  with a strong attack. }
14. Qe2
{ Another typical attacking idea is   14.Rf3 !?  a5  15.Rh3  Ne4  16.Qd1  g6  17.Rc1  f6  18.Bxe4  dxe4  19.Nc4  Bd5  20.f5  g5  21.Rh5  with a complex position. White intends to go h4. }
14... a5
{ Black logically seeks counterplay.   14...Ne4  15.Bxe4  dxe4  16.f5  Qg5  17.Rf4 !  f6  18.Rg4 !  Qh6   18...Qxf5  19.Qc4+  Kh8  20.Ng6+  Qxg6  21.Rxg6  hxg6  22.a4  White is better. The plan is to get the bishop to a3.  19.Rg3  fxe5  20.dxe5  Bc5  21.f6  with a strong attack. 1-0, 26 moves, Malakhov, V. 2691 - Predojevic, B. 2614, Mali Losinj 2017. }
15. Rf3 { And now, an example of how the game could develop: } 15... a4 16.
bxa4 Rxa4 17. Rh3 Bc8 18. f5 Bb7 19. Bc2 Ra7 20. a4 Rfa8 21. g4 Ne4
{ 21...h6  22.g5  hxg5  23.Qg2  Black's king begins to tremble.  Ne4 ?!  24.Bxe4  dxe4  25.Qg4  wins ! }
22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. g5 Qxg5+ 24. Rg3 Qh6 25. Kh1 Rxa4 26. Rag1 Ra2 27. Qg4
{ White has strong attack. } *

