{ White has other tries.  A. Another logical idea is:   10.f3 !?  Nxd2  11.Qxd2  f6  12.Nxd7  Qxd7  13.e4 !?  c5   13...e5  14.dxe5  Bxe5  15.Bxe5  fxe5  16.exd5  White is better as the pawn on e5 is weak.  14.e5  fxe5  15.dxe5  Be7  16.Qe2  We have reached a complex, asymmetrical position. White intends f4 followed by Qg4.  a6 !   16...Rad8  17.f4  d4  18.h4  Qd5  19.Qg4  Qc6  20.Rf3  b5  21.a4  a6  22.Rd1  White is better.  17.a4  Bg5  18.g3  d4  19.h4  Be3+  20.Kh2  White is forced to go Bc1 and later on f4, with mutual chances.  B. This next idea is solid but requires Black to be precise in order to avoid some unpleasantness:   10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Bb5 !?   11.Bc4  Nf6 !  ⇆  B1.  11...Nf6  B2.   11...Nxe5 !  The best in order to maintain the balance.  12.dxe5  Bc5  13.Qg4  a6  14.Rfd1  Qe7  15.Bf1  Rfd8  16.g3  Rxd1  17.Rxd1  Rd8  18.Rxd8+  Qxd8  19.Bc3 =  12.c4 !?  Qc8   12...a6  13.Ba4  Qe7  14.Qc2  Bxe5  15.dxe5  Nd7  16.b4 !  Rfd8  17.Bc3  Qg5  18.Bxd7  Rxd7  19.a4  Rd3  20.h3  h6  21.Qb2  Rad8  22.a5  b5  23.cxb5  axb5  24.Ra3  White has nicer play.  13.c5 !  bxc5  14.dxc5  Bxc5  15.Nd7  Nxd7  16.Bxd7  Qd8  17.Qg4  g6  18.Bxe6  Qe7  19.Bc4  Rad8   19...Bd6  20.f4 !  ±  20.Qf4  Rd6  21.Qh6  with a strong attack. }
10... f6
{ 10...Ndf6  A.  11.Rf3 !?  leaves Black no choice:  B.   11.c4 !?  Again here we see a plan of changing c for e pawn.  Qe7  12.cxd5  exd5  13.Rf3  a5   13...Ba3  14.Bxa3  Qxa3  15.Rh3  Qd6  16.Nxe4  dxe4  17.Bc4  White got his usual attacking chances.  14.a4  Bb4  15.Nf1  c5  16.Rh3  Bc8  17.g4  h5 !?  18.Bxe4  dxe4  19.d5  Bxg4  20.Nxg4  hxg4  21.Bxf6  Qxf6  22.Qxg4  Qxa1  23.Qh5  f5  24.Qh7+  Kf7  25.Rh6  leads to a draw.  11...Nxd2  12.Qxd2  Ne4  13.Qe2  f6   13...Qe7  14.Rh3 !  planning to meet ...f6 with Qh5.  14.Ng4  Qe7  15.Rh3  a5  16.a4  Bc6 !?   16...f5  17.Ne5  followed by g4. White gets exactly what he is looking for.  17.c4  Be8 !  18.Nf2  Bg6  19.Qc2  Nxf2  20.Kxf2  Bxd3  21.Qxd3  f5  22.g4  White has a favourable position.  Rad8  23.Rg1  g6  24.gxf5  ± }
