1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Qe2
{ Intending a rapid e4. } 7... Ne4
{ A critical response.   7...c5  8.dxc5 !?  This motif again.  Bxc5   8...bxc5  9.e4  c4  10.Bxc4  dxc4  11.e5  ±  9.e4 !  The main idea of the Colle is fully demonstratedin this game.  Nc6  10.c3  dxe4  11.Nxe4  Be7  12.Bf4 !  Nd5  13.Bg3  O-O  14.Rad1  Qc8  15.Nd6  Bxd6  16.Bxd6  Rd8  17.Bg3  h6  18.Bb1  Nf6  19.Rxd8+  Qxd8  20.Rd1  Qe8  21.Nd4  White is happy with his opening.1-0, 65 moves, Kramnik, V. 2810 - Hou Yifan 2635, Medias rapid 2016. }
8. b3 O-O 9. Bb2 Nd7 10. c4
{ This move is another particular aspect of these systems, which can be played in many situations and contains many nuances. Here I will deal with this specific move order.  For   10.Ne5 !?  see the next subchapter. }
10... f5
{ A.   10...Qe7  11.Rac1  c5  12.dxc5  Ndxc5  13.Bb1  Nxd2  14.Nxd2  Rad8  15.Rfd1  Bb8  16.b4 !?  N   16.Qh5  h6  17.h4  f5  18.Qg6  Rf7  19.h5 !?  ∞  A bit of a wild approach, typical of Mamedyarov's style, but certainly not a necessary one. 1-0, 33 moves, Mamedyarov, S. 2799 - Bocharov, D. 2583, Riyadh blitz 2017.  16...Na4  17.Ba1  Qxb4  18.Qg4  e5  19.Nf3  f6  20.Nh4  White has the initiative.  B.   10...a5  Adams employs a typical theme in these systems, often seen in tournament practice.  11.Rfd1   11.Rfc1 !?  with an idea that after  a4  12.bxa4  Rxa4  13.cxd5  exd5  14.Bb5 !  Ra7  15.a4  is an improvement for White, since ...c6 is not possible.  11...Qe7  12.Rac1  a4  13.Nf1  axb3  14.axb3  Ra2  15.Bb1  Rxb2  16.Qxb2  Ba3  ∞  with balanced play. 1/2-1/2, 39 moves, Kramnik, V. 2809 - Adams, M. 2748, London 2016. }
11. Rac1
{ 11.Rfc1 !?  An interesting solution.  Qf6  12.Rc2  c6  13.Nf1  The rook on a1 can sometimes be used to support a potential a4-a5 thrust.  g5  14.Ng3  A.  Qg6  B.   14...g4  15.Bxe4 !  dxe4  16.Ne5 !  Nxe5   16...Rad8  17.Nh5  Qh6  18.Nf4  White has a pair of beautiful knights.  17.dxe5  Bxe5  18.Nh5  Bxh2+  19.Kxh2  Qh4+  20.Kg1  Qxh5  21.Rd2  Same idea as in 11. Rac1. White has a strong position.  C.   14...Nxg3  15.hxg3  Now play could for example develop in the following way:  g4  16.Nh4  a5  17.Rac1  Rfc8  18.cxd5  cxd5  19.Bb5  Rxc2  20.Rxc2  Nf8  21.e4 !?  fxe4   21...dxe4  22.d5 !  would yield White huge compensation  22.Qxg4+  Qg7  23.Qe2  Rc8  24.Rxc8  Bxc8  25.Bc1  Bd7  26.Be3  ∞  15.Ne5  is good for White. }
11... Qf6 12. c5
{ This unusual pawn sacrifice takes us to a rather unusual tactics.  Another option was   12.Rc2  c6  A.  13.c5  B.   13.Rfc1 !?  Rac8  14.Nf1   14.cxd5  exd5  15.Ba6  Bxa6  16.Qxa6  Rc7 !  17.Qe2  Rfc8 =  14...g5  15.Ng3 !?  g4  16.Bxe4 !  dxe4  17.Ne5  Nxe5  18.dxe5  Bxe5  19.Nh5 !  Bxh2+  20.Kxh2  Qh4+  21.Kg1  Qxh5  22.Rd2  =∞  Although two pawns down, the bishop on b2 is a monster when compared to it scounterpart on b7; so it is fair to say that White has the initiative.  13...Bc7  14.b4  bxc5  15.bxc5   15.dxc5 !?  e5  16.Ba6  Rab8  17.a3  ∞  15...a5  16.Rb1  Ra7  17.Nf1  a4  18.Ne1  Qe7  19.f3  Nef6  20.Bc3  g6  21.f4  Ne4  22.Nf3  ∞  1-0, 60 moves, Saric, A. 2483 - Palac, M. 2557, Stari Mikanovci 2010. }
12... bxc5 13. dxc5 Qxb2 { 13...Bxh2+ ?  14.Nxh2  Qxb2  15.Nxe4  +- } 14. cxd6
Nc3
{ A.   14...Nxd2 !?  15.Nd4 !?  c5  16.Rc2  Qa3  17.Nb5  Qb4  18.Qxd2  Qxd2  19.Rxd2  Although unusual, it seems that this endgame is slightly preferable for White. For example:  Kf7  20.Rc1  Rfd8  21.f3  a6  22.Nc7  B.   14...cxd6  15.Nxe4  Qxe2  16.Bxe2  dxe4  17.Nd4  Bd5  18.Nb5  a5  19.Nxd6   19.g3  Rad8  ⇆  19...a4  20.bxa4  Nb6  21.a3  Rxa4  22.Rc3  Rd8  23.Nb5  leads to an equal endgame. }
15. Qe1 Nc5 16. Nb1 N3e4 { 16...Nxd3  17.Qxc3  += } 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Nd4 Nd3
