1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Qe2 Ne4 8. b3
O-O 9. Bb2 Nd7 10. Ne5
{ A rare sight actually but an interesting one nonetheless. } 10... f5
{ Black has couple of interesting possibilities.  A.   10...Nxd2  11.Qxd2  Nxe5  12.dxe5  Be7  13.Qe2  c5  14.f4  Qc7  15.Rf3 !  c4  16.Bxh7+ !  Kxh7  17.Rh3+  Kg8  18.f5 !  White wins.  B.   10...f6  11.Nxd7  Qxd7  12.c4  c5   12...f5  13.cxd5  exd5  14.Nf3  with the idea of Ne5 followed by f3.  13.cxd5  Nxd2  14.Qxd2  Bxd5   14...exd5  15.Rfd1  Qe6  16.dxc5  bxc5  17.e4 !  White is a slightly better.  15.dxc5  Bxc5  16.Qc2 !  h6  17.Rfd1  Qb7  18.e4  Bc6  19.Qc4  Rae8  20.b4  Bd6  21.b5  Bd7  22.Be2 !  +=  With small crafty ideas, White has managed to create an unbalanced position which maybe slightly in his favour.  C.   10...a6  11.f4  f6  12.Nxe4  dxe4  13.Bc4 !  White has initiative. }
11. Rad1
{ At this stage, it is not easy to determine where the rooks belong, and this is true for both players. The answer to such a question rarely comes easily in the Zukertort, making it a very complicated opening positionally speaking. }
11... Bxe5
{ A. Black can try various ideas:   11...Rf6  12.f4  Rh6  13.Nxe4  fxe4  14.Bb5  White has pressure here.  B.   11...Qe7  12.f4  Ndf6   12...c5  13.Nxd7  Qxd7  14.dxc5  bxc5  15.Nf3  with the idea of Ne5, followed by Rf3 and potentially g4.  B1.  13.Nxe4 !?  B2.   13.Rf3 !?  Nxd2  14.Rxd2  Ne4  15.Rd1  Bxe5  16.dxe5 !  Only like this is the b2-bishop allowed to reach its potential. It is worth noting that dxe5 is a crucial aspect in Colle-Zukertort lines.  Bc6   16...c5  17.Rh3  Bc6  18.g4  Be8  19.gxf5  White has some initiative.  17.h3  Be8  18.Bxe4 !   18.g4  Bg6  18...dxe4  19.Rff1  Rd8  20.Ba3  c5  21.Rxd8  Qxd8  22.Rd1  White gets better chances due to the d6-square.  13...Nxe4   13...dxe4  14.Bc4  a6  15.a4 !?  c6  16.Qf2  b5  17.Be2  A complicated but typical position for Colle-Zukertort systems.   13...fxe4  14.Bb5  a6  15.Bc6  Bxc6  16.Nxc6  Qe8  17.Ne5  with c4 to come.  14.g4 !  with a clear plan of Kh1, Rg1 and so on. }
12. dxe5 Ndc5 13. Nf3
{ Black wanted to exchange both on d2 and d3.   13.f4  Nxd2  14.Rxd2  Nxd3  15.cxd3  a5  16.a4  Ba6  ⇆ }
13... a5 14. Nd4 Qe8 15. f3
{ 15.a4 !?  Nxd3  16.cxd3  Ba6  17.f4 !?  with Qc2 in mind.   17.Qc2  c5  18.Ne2  Ng5  19.Rc1  Rc8  20.Qd2  Nf7  21.d4  Nd8  22.Ba3  Nb7  23.Rc3  Rf7  24.Rfc1  Rfc7  25.h4  Bxe2 !  26.Qxe2  Rc6  27.Qa6  Qd7  28.g3  Though White seems better, converting this advantage may be a demanding task.  17...Nc5  18.Qc2  Rf7  19.h3  Nb7  20.g4  c5  21.Nf3  With yet another complex struggle . }
15... Nxd3 16. cxd3 Ng5 { Now White missed a really strong plan: } 17. Qd2
{ In a stem game, White opted for more usual reaction.   17.f4  Nf7  18.Nf3  c5  19.Rf2  a4  20.d4  Qd7  ∞  21.dxc5  bxc5  22.Rc1  Rfc8  23.h3  axb3  24.axb3  Ba6  25.Qc2  Bb5  26.g4  g6 ?!   26...Nh6 !  27.Rg2  ∞  27.gxf5  gxf5  28.Kh2  Nh6  29.Rg2+  Kh8  30.Qf2  Rg8  31.Rxg8+  Rxg8  32.Qh4  ±  1-0, 40 moves, Lobron, E. 2550 - Dautov, R. 2602, Frankfurt 2000. }
17... c5 18. Ne2 { The knight is transferred to a healthier square: f4 ! }
18... Nf7 19. Rc1 { 19.Nf4  Nh8 !  ⇆  +=3 ...Ng6 } 19... Qe7 20. Nf4 Rfc8 21.
d4
{ White is on top as both his minor pieces are better than their counterparts. }
