{ A purely positional idea. Not the most ambitious, but not without danger either. By eliminating thebishop on d6,White wants to focus on attacking Black's centre. Moreover, the bishop might become a dangerous attacking asset for Black.   8.cxd5  So that Black cannot really consider...Nxd5 at a later stage, though this choice is questionable if Black manages to achieve equality.  exd5  9.Ba3 !?  Indeed, it doesn't look revolutionary, but this is true for most of classical chess. It's more about understanding the positional aspects of a position and being able to employ them properly, rather than blindly listening to whether engines give an advantage or not.  A.  Re8  B.   9...Bxa3  See notes under 8 Ba3.  C.   9...Ne4  10.Qc2  a6  11.Rc1 !?  An interesting concept, White puts immediate pressure on the c7-pawn.  c5   11...Nc6 ?!  12.Bxe4  dxe4  13.Qxe4  Na5  14.Qf5  g6  15.Qh3  c5  16.Nbd2  White is better. 1/2-1/ 2, 33 moves, Dominguez Perez, L. 2739 - Hammer, J. 2631, Internet blitz 2018.  12.dxc5  bxc5  13.Bxe4  dxe4  14.Nfd2  Qh4  15.Nf1  Rd8  16.Nbd2  Nd7  17.Nc4  Bc7  18.Rd1  With an edge for White.  D.   9...c5  10.Nc3  Nbd7  11.Rc1  Re8  12.Bf5 !  A typical move.  Bf8  13.dxc5  Nxc5   13...bxc5  14.Bxd7  Qxd7  15.Na4  +=  14.Bb2  g6  15.Bd3 !   15.Bh3 ?!  Ba6 !  16.Ne2  Nd3  17.Bxf6  Qxf6  ∓  0-1, 55 moves, Dominguez Perez, L. 2739 - So, W. 2788, Saint Louis 2017.  15...Rc8  16.Ne2  Though the position remains very complicated, White achieved his goal of creating an isolani on d5, which is considered quite an achievement for many players.  10.Bxd6  Qxd6  11.Nc3  a6  12.Rc1  Nbd7  13.Bf5  Nf8  14.Qc2  g6  15.Bh3  The idea is partly to put the bishop on g2. An unusual fianchetto !  Re7  16.Rfd1  Bc8  17.Bxc8  Rxc8  18.Qd3  Ra8  19.Rc2 !  Ne6  20.h3  c6  21.Na4  Rb7  22.Rdc1  Nd8  23.Ne5 !  c5  24.Nf3  ±  This game illustrates many important parts of White's play, such as doubling the rooks on the c-file. Everything looks simple when Kramnikis playing ! 1-0, 51 moves, Kramnik, V. 2803 - Pelletier, Y. 2574, Geneva 2013. }
8... Bxa3
{ 8...c5  9.cxd5   9.dxc5  bxc5  10.Nc3  Nbd7  11.Rc1  Rc8  12.cxd5  exd5  13.Bf5  Qe7  14.Re1  a6  15.Rc2  Rc7  16.Bh3  Rd8  Black is fine here. 1/2-1/2, 55 moves, Eperjesi, L. 2381 - Balogh, C. 2235, Budapest 1999.  9...exd5  10.Nc3  Nbd7  11.Nb5  Bb8  12.Rc1  a6  13.Nc3  Bd6  14.Qe2   14.Bf5  is unclear.  14...b5  15.dxc5  Nxc5  16.Bxc5  Bxc5  17.Nxb5  Bb6  18.Nbd4  White is better. 1-0, 53 moves, Dominguez Perez, L. 2739 - Hammer, J. 2631, Internet blitz 2018. }
9. Nxa3 Nbd7 10. cxd5
{ 10.Nb5  a6  11.Nc3  c5  12.cxd5  Nxd5 !?  Now it is the correct response.  13.Nxd5  Bxd5  14.Be2  Qe7  15.Rc1  Rfd8  16.Qc2  Bb7  17.Rfd1  Rac8  18.Qb2  a5  19.h3  g6  20.Rc2  cxd4  21.Rxc8  Rxc8  22.Qxd4  Rc7  23.Ne5  Nxe5  White didn't achieve much. 1/2-1/ 2, Epishin, V. 2536 - Cuenca Jimenez, J. 2489, Roquetas de Mar 2018. }
10... exd5 11. Rc1
{ 11.Nb5 !?  a6  12.Nc3  Qe7  13.Rc1  Typical play for White here.  g6  14.Re1  Rfe8  15.Bf1  c5  16.Re2  Rac8  17.Rec2  Qd6  18.a4 !?  Rc7  19.dxc5  bxc5  A.  20.a5 !?  An idea worth noting asthe a5-pawn restricts Black and the knight can put pressure on the c5-pawn from a4.  B.   20.b4 !?  c4  21.Rb1  Another standard approach in such positions.  20...Rec8  21.Na4  Rc6  22.g3  Rb8  23.Bg2  Ba8  24.Nd2  with complex play ahead. 1/2-1/2, 72 moves, Iordachescu, V. 2581 -Almasi, Z. 2689, Reykjavik 2015. }
11... a6 12. Nb1 Re8 13. Nc3 Nf8 14. b4
{ Correct play for when Black hesitates to push ...c5. } 14... Ng6 15. Qb3 Ne4
16. Rc2 Re7 17. Rfc1 Qd6 18. Ne2 Rae8 19. Ng3
{ A nice manoeuvre, heading to f5, thus more or less forcing a knight exchange all the while protecting the white king. }
19... Nxg3 20. hxg3 h6 21. Bxg6 fxg6 22. Ne5
{ White has achieved his dream position in this line. 1-0, 55 moves, Bruzon Batista, L. 2659 - Grigoriants, S. 2603, Berlin 2015. }
