1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. b3 Bd6
{ Against other moves, White plays similarly or can just transpose to 6 Nbd2 ideas. }
7. c4 O-O 8. cxd5
{ So that Black cannot really consider...Nxd5 at a later stage, though this choice is questionable if Black manages to achieve equality. }
8... exd5 9. Ba3
{ Indeed, it doesn't look revolutionary, but this is true for most of classical chess. It's more about understanding the positional aspects of a position and being able to employ them properly, rather than blindly listening to whether engines give an advantage or not. }
9... Re8 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Nc3 a6 12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. Bf5 Nf8 14. Qc2 g6 15. Bh3
{ The idea is partly to put the bishop on g2. An unusual fianchetto ! } 15...
Re7 16. Rfd1 Bc8 17. Bxc8 Rxc8 18. Qd3 Ra8 19. Rc2 Ne6 20. h3 c6 21. Na4 Rb7
22. Rdc1 Nd8 23. Ne5 c5 24. Nf3
{ This game illustrates many important parts of White's play, such as doubling the rooks on the c-file. Everything looks simple when Kramnikis playing ! 1-0, 51 moves, Kramnik, V. 2803 - Pelletier, Y. 2574, Geneva 2013. }
