[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 4...b6"]
[Black "Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7
{ After 6 Nbd2, we reached one of the most important positions. Both sides claim the e5- or e4-square in mirror fashion. This concept is just the tip of an intricate positional ice-berg and, in my opinion, understanding it is a large step towards mastering positional chess.   Black can opt for  6...Be7  , a solid approach. After  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  c5  White has a choice between  9.c4   And the more direct  9.Ne5.  (Both paths lead to interesting positional games.)   Black may prefer  6...Bd6  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  Nbd7  , a more aggressive setup. Black imitates White in the hope of establishing balanced play. White has various ideas, all of which deserve attention: A.  9.Qe2  The move order is a little different. Forcing Black to go  ...Ne4  , which is answered by  Ne5.  A rather peculiar and unexplored position in general theory.   B.  9.c4  A very logical option. Before committing to anything, White brings another pawn to the central battle and will decide on development later: either to bring a knight to  e5  , or play along the c-file.   C.  9.Ne5  White can go for this move early on in an attempt to make use of his extra tempo and break the symmetry.  We also uncovered two alternatives to the Nbd2 and b3 setup:   1. Playing Nbd2 and Qe2.   2. Or b3 followed by c4 and Ba3.   Both options also provide White with decent chances and interesting play. }
*

