1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5
{ One of many typical plans here for Black, this one is in the spirit of the Slav opening. }
4. Bd3
{ An unusual and rare choice, White is heading towards a regular line with e3 against the Slav but wants to simplify matters with this move order. }
4... Bxd3
{ Taking on d3 is the main option but Black also has other ideas.  A.   4...e6  5.O-O  Ne4  6.c4  Nd7  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Qc2  Bg6  9.Nc3  Ndf6   9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  +=  10.Ne5  c6  11.f3  Nd6  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Ne2  Qc7  14.h3  Rh4  15.Bd2  Qe7  White is better here but I missed  16.b4 !  ±  And it isn't easy to find a good move for Black. Pavlovic - Elianov, Biel Rapid 2018.  B.   4...Bg6  5.O-O  e6  6.Qe2  Nbd7  7.Nbd2  B1.  Be7  B2.   7...c5  8.Bxg6  hxg6  9.c4 !?   9.e4 !?  dxe4  10.Nxe4  cxd4  11.Rd1  Qb6  12.Rxd4  Be7  13.c3  O-O  14.Neg5  Rad8  15.Be3  Bc5  16.Rb4  Qc7  17.Rh4  also an interesting idea for White.  9...cxd4  10.cxd5 !  Nxd5  11.Nxd4  Qc7   11...N7f6  12.Rd1  White has some edge here. Faster development and the idea of e4 helps get the initiative.  12.h3  O-O-O  13.N2b3 !  Kb8  14.Bd2  White is better here. Castling long has only helped White.  B3.   7...Ne4 !?  8.Ne5 !?  Nxe5  9.dxe5  c6  10.f4 !  This is an important idea and an improvement that I managed to use in tournament practice.  B3.1.  Be7  B3.2.   10...Nc5  11.Bxg6  hxg6  12.a4  a5  13.b3 !  By provoking a5, White makes ...O-O-O harder to con-siderfor Black.  B3.3.   10...Nxd2  11.Bxd2  Qb6  12.a3 !?  +=   12.Kh1  Bb4 !  A good move that I simply missed.  13.Bc1 !  Be7  14.b3  a5  15.Bb2  a4  16.f5  exf5  17.Bxf5  Bxf5  18.Rxf5  c5  19.e6 !  +=  1/2-1/2, 41 moves, Pavlovic, M. 2482 - Banusz, T. 2612, Valjevo 2018.  11.Bxe4 !  The main idea. Now White wants to take advantage of the d6-square.  dxe4  12.b3  O-O  13.a4  h5  14.Nc4  Qc7  15.Ba3  c5  16.Rad1  With some edge to White. The bishop on g6 is a bit out of play.  8.Bxg6  hxg6  9.e4  dxe4  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Qxe4  c6  12.c4  O-O  13.Bf4  += }
5. Qxd3 c6 6. O-O e6 7. Nbd2 Nbd7 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Nf6
{ 10...Be7  11.c4  O-O  12.Rd1  a5 !?   12...Nf6  13.Qe2  transposes to main line.  13.Qe2 !?  Intending d5.  a4  14.Bf4  Qa5 ?!   14...Nf6  15.Ne5  with the idea of Rd3 and Rad1.  15.d5 !  Nc5  16.dxc6 !  Stronger than advancing to d6.  bxc6  17.Ne5  Rac8  18.Rab1 !  Already, it's not easy to find good moves for Black.  Qa8  19.Be3  Ne4  20.Nd7  +-  1-0, 42 moves, Pavlovic, M. 2477 - Ivanisevic, I. 2611, Ruma 2017. }
11. Qe2 Be7 12. c4 O-O 13. Rd1
{ This is a starting point in this line, it may not seem threatening ,but it's sharper than it looks. White wants to put the bishop on f4, the knight on e5 and the rook on d3. If he manages that, it will not be easy for Black to get any play. }
13... Qc7
{ A.   13...h6  Such waiting move can be a serious mistake and the following example clearly demonstrates that:  14.Rd3  Qc7  15.Ne5  Rad8  16.Bf4  Qc8  17.Rad1  c5  18.Be3  Nd7  19.Ng4 !  Bg5  20.Nxh6+ !  Bxh6  21.Bxh6  gxh6  22.Qh5  Kg7  23.Rg3+  Kf6  24.Qh4+  Kf5  25.Qxh6  1-0, Rashkovsky, N. 2505 - Lundin, A. 2285, Moscow 1996.  B.   13...Qa5  14.Ne5  Rad8  15.Bg5  Rfe8  16.Rd3  This is a key idea for White.  B1.  c5  Usually this is Black's main source of counterplay.  B2.   16...Nd7  17.Bxe7  Rxe7  18.Rad1 !  Qc7   18...Nxe5  19.dxe5  Rxd3  20.Rxd3  Re8  21.a3 !  As White controls the only open file, we can say that there are some chances to increase pressure.  19.Nf3 !  Nf8  20.g3  f6  21.h4 !  It is important here to bring a pawn to h5, thus preventing the activation of the f8-knight. As long as that knight stays passive, White may increase the pressure.  c5  22.b3  a6  23.h5  h6  24.dxc5  Rxd3  25.Rxd3  Qxc5  26.Nh4  Kf7  27.Ng2 !  Rd7  28.Nf4  White managed achieve a slight edge. 1/2-1/2, 73 moves, Grachev, B. 2660 - Vuckovic, B. 2623, Moscow 2011.  17.dxc5  Qxc5   17...Rxd3  18.Nxd3  Bxc5  19.Bxf6  gxf6  20.Nxc5  Qxc5  21.Rd1  White has an edge here: a pawn majority on the queenside, an open file, and Blacks weak king are all assets.  18.Bxf6  Bxf6  19.Nd7 !  Qe7  20.Rad1 !  This idea is of great importance and a very intersting motif in general. White is now ready to launch his queenside pawns with c5, b4, etc.  b6  21.g3  g6  22.b4  Bg7  23.Rd6  Rc8  24.c5  bxc5  25.bxc5  Red8  26.c6  h5  27.Qa6  with a huge advantage. }
14. Ne5 Rad8 15. Bf4 Qc8 16. a3
{ A key move and a new idea ! Its a rather discrete move but a crucial one. We will see that it generates entire idea for White.   16.Rd3  c5 !  Black is fine . }
16... c5
{ B.   16...a5  17.c5 !  An important idea. Somehow with a pawn on a5 it becomes much stronger as this pawn suddenly becomes a target.  Nd5  18.Bg3 !  The knight will come to c4 from where it will attack the pawn on a5 and have access to the strong d6-square.   18.Bd2  Qc7  19.Nc4  Ra8  20.b4  Bf6  21.Qe4  axb4  22.axb4  Rxa1  23.Rxa1  Rd8  24.g3  h6  25.Kg2  with more or less equal play. }
17. dxc5 Qxc5 18. b4 { That's the key: we start our play on queenside. } 18...
Qc8 19. h3
{ 19.Be3 !?  a6  20.Bb6  Rxd1+  21.Rxd1  Bd8  22.Qe3  Also gives White some initiative. }
19... Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Rd8 21. Rxd8+ Qxd8 22. Qf3 Qc8 23. Be3 a6 24. c5
{ This is more or less the type of position that we are aiming for, and we can say that White has an edge, or at least easier play. }
*

