[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5
{ One of many typical plans here for Black, this one is in the spirit of the Slav opening. }
4. Bd3
{ An unusual and rare choice, White is heading towards a regular line with e3 against the Slav but wants to simplify matters with this move order. }
4... Bxd3 { Taking on d3 is the main option but Black also has other ideas. }
5. Qxd3 c6 6. O-O e6 7. Nbd2 Nbd7 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Nf6 11. Qe2
Be7 12. c4 O-O 13. Rd1
{ This is a starting point in this line, it may not seem threatening , but it's sharper than it looks. White wants to put the bishop on f4, the knight on e5 and the rook on d3. If he manages that, it will not be easy for Black to get any play. }
13... Qc7 14. Ne5 Rad8 15. Bf4 Qc8 16. a3
{ A key move and a new idea ! Its a rather discrete move but a crucial one. We will see that it generates entire idea for White. }
16... a5 17. c5
{ An important idea. Somehow with a pawn on a5 it becomes much stronger as this pawn suddenly becomes a target. }
17... Nd5 18. Bg3
{ The knight will come to c4 from where it will attack the pawn on a5 and have access to the strong d6-square. }
*

