[White "Systems with ...d5: 3.e3"]
[Black "3.e3 Bg4 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4
{ This is yet another typical idea for Black, as well as 3... Bf5. } 4. h3
{ 4.Qd3 !?  An interesting anti-computer idea. White simply ignores the pin and creates the threat of Ne5.  Nbd7  5.Ne5  Bh5  6.Qb3  Rb8  7.f3 !?  The idea is g4 and h4.  Nxe5   7...e6  8.h4 !  +=  +=3 g4  8.dxe5  Nd7  9.Qxd5  e6  10.Qd4  Qg5  11.Nc3  Bc5  12.Qf4  Qxe5  13.Qxe5  Nxe5  14.Bd2  O-O  15.O-O-O  Rfd8  16.Be2  Admittedly, this wasn't forced but one of the many ideas available. In this particluar position though, I think that White has somewhat better chances in the endgame. The bishop on h5 is not badly placed. Let's explore a little further.  Rd7   16...Bb4  17.a3  Bxc3  18.Bxc3  Nc6  19.h4  White is better.  17.g4  Bg6  18.f4  Nc6  19.h4  h6  20.h5  Bh7  21.Na4  Be7   21...Bb6  22.Nxb6  axb6  23.Bc3  White is better.  22.Bf3  Rbd8  23.Bc3  Rxd1+  24.Rxd1  Rxd1+  25.Kxd1  White has some pressure here. }
4... Bxf3
{ 4...Bh5 ?!  5.g4  Bg6  6.Ne5 !  This is already better for White.  Nfd7   6...e6  7.h4  ±   6...Nbd7  7.h4  ±  7.Nxg6  hxg6  8.Bg2  c6  9.c4  e6  10.Qb3  Qb6  11.Nc3  Na6  12.Bd2  g5  13.cxd5  Qxb3  14.axb3  exd5  15.e4  dxe4  16.Bxg5  gives White better chances. Just one of the many ideas of how to conduct play. }
5. gxf3
{ I am not sure that such move has previously been played, but it certainly looks interesting.   5.Qxf3  e6  6.Bd3  c5  7.c3  Nc6  8.O-O  Bd6  9.Nd2  O-O  10.Qe2 !  e5  11.dxc5 !  Bxc5  12.e4  is a possible plan, and a typical Colle idea. }
5... e6 6. c4 c6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. Qb3 Qb6 9. Bd2 Be7 10. Qxb6
{ An interesting solution. It looks slightly anti-positional ,but that is not the case. I once faced such an idea as Black against GM Bogosavljevic. It turns out that if White is fast enough, the idea is fully justified. }
10... axb6 11. cxd5
{ When possessing the bishop pair, it's always important to open the position. }
11... exd5
{ 11...cxd5  12.Bb5 !  White has the initiative, that is actually one of the main points behindtaking on b6 and then on d5, in order to discourage Black from taking back withcxd5. }
12. Bd3 b5 13. a4 { It is essential to prevent the ...Nb6 exapansion. } 13...
O-O
{ 13...bxa4  14.Rxa4  O-O  15.Ke2  Nb6  16.Rxa8  Rxa8  17.Rb1  White has some pressure here. }
14. b3 b4 { 14...bxa4  15.bxa4  With an idea of Ke2 and Rhb1. } 15. Ne2
{ We have reached playable endgame for White. } *

