[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 3.e3"]
[Black "3.e3 g6 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b4
{ We are entering the realm of rare ideas now.White obviously wants to prevent an early c5 while gaining space on the queenside. A later c4 will further confirm these queenside intentions. It is important to note that this line may arise from a different but also logical move order: 1 d4 Nf6 2 Nf3 g6 3 e3 Bg7 4 Be2 O-O 5 O-O d5 6 b4. The flexibility of the position requires both sides to be comfortable with the nuances here. Of course, it noticeably resembles some lines of the Grunfeld. }
6... a5
{ The principled reaction, but there are other ideas as well.   6...b6  7.Bb2 !  c5   7...Qd6  8.c4 !  This is improvement over my game with Kuzubov from Serbian League 2018  dxc4  9.Nfd2  b5  10.Bf3  c6  11.a4  Nd5  12.axb5  cxb5  13.Ra5  Attacking not only b5 but also c4.  e6  14.Rxb5  Ba6  15.Nxc4  Qd8  16.Rc5  Nd7  17.Nbd2  Nxc5  18.bxc5  White has compensation.  8.bxc5  bxc5  9.c4 !  The best plan in my opinion.  Nbd7  Other moves are possible as well:   9...Nc6  10.dxc5 !  dxc4  11.Nbd2  Rb8  12.Nxc4  Qc7  13.Rc1  ±   9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  Bb7  11.Nd2  Nc6  12.Rc1  Rc8  13.Qb3  Na5  14.Qb4  Qb6  15.Ba3  Qxb4  16.Bxb4  Nxc4  17.Nxc4  dxc4  18.Bxc4  ±  10.Nbd2  Rb8  11.Rb1  Qa5  12.dxc5 !  Nxc5   12...Qxa2  13.Bd4  ±  13.Nb3 !  Nxb3  14.axb3  +=  A typical reaction in such positons. White strengthens his pawn structure and will try to put pressure on the a7-pawn. }
7. b5 c5 8. bxc6
{ White exchanged the b-for c-pawn, which is good from a positional point of view. On the other hand, Black achieves rapid development. }
8... Nxc6
{ Active, with Ne4 and e5 to follow. Black wants to put pressure on the centre.  Taking with the pawn is possible, too:   8...bxc6  9.Ba3 !  Ne4   9...Nbd7  10.Nbd2  Re8  11.c4  e5  12.dxe5  Nxe5  13.Nxe5  Rxe5  14.Bb2  Re8  15.Rc1  +=  White is slighly better here.  10.Nfd2 !  The knight on e4 must be challenged.  Nd6   10...Nxd2  11.Nxd2  Ba6  12.c4  Nd7  13.Rb1  Re8  14.cxd5  cxd5  15.Bxa6  Rxa6  16.Rb7  Qc8  17.Qb3  White has an edge here.  11.c4  e5  Critical ! Other move gives White easy play.   11...Na6  12.Nc3  e6  13.Rb1  White has a more harmonious position.   11...Ba6  12.cxd5  cxd5  13.Nc3  e6  14.Rb1  White has developed nicely.  12.Nf3  exd4  13.Nxd4  dxc4  14.Nc3  Re8  15.Rc1  =∞ }
9. a4
{ A strictly positional idea. Taking control of the b5-square and limiting Black's options on the queenside.  We will see that White cannot really activate here with the usual:   9.c4 ?!  dxc4  10.Bxc4  Ne4  11.Ba3  Nb4  12.Nbd2  Nd6  13.Bb3  Bf5  Black is very much active. }
9... Bf5
{ 9...Ne4  10.c3  e5  11.Nfd2  Nxd2  12.Nxd2  Bf5  13.Ba3  Re8  14.Rc1  Rc8  15.Nf3 !?  The idea is to answer ...exd4 with Nxd4 ! Or simply provoke e4, after which Nd2 followed by c4 is pleasant.  h5  16.Qb3 !?  In any case, we have a very interesting and complex game ahead of us, and White has a solid position. }
10. Na3 Rc8 11. c3 Ne4 12. Nb5 e5
{ 12...g5  13.Ba3  Re8  14.Nd2  This is better for White. } 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Rc1
Qd7 15. Nd2 Nxd2 16. Qxd2 exd4 17. cxd4 Bf8 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 19. Rc5
{ We see that White has achieved certain positional gains. Black, on the other hand, has a very solid position. Hence, White is slightly better. }
*

