[White "Systems with ...d5: 3.e3"]
[Black "3.e3 g6 Variation 11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b4
{ We are entering the realm of rare ideas now.White obviously wants to prevent an early c5 while gaining space on the queenside. A later c4 will further confirm these queenside intentions. It is important to note that this line may arise from a different but also logical move order: 1 d4 Nf6 2 Nf3 g6 3 e3 Bg7 4 Be2 O-O 5 O-O d5 6 b4. The flexibility of the position requires both sides to be comfortable with the nuances here. Of course, it noticeably resembles some lines of the Grunfeld. }
6... a5 { The principled reaction, but there are other ideas as well. } 7. b5
c5 8. bxc6
{ White exchanged the b-for c-pawn, which is good from a positional point of view. On the other hand, Black achieves rapid development. }
8... Nxc6
{ Active, with Ne4 and e5 to follow. Black wants to put pressure on the centre. }
9. a4
{ A strictly positional idea. Taking control of the b5-square and limiting Black's options on the queenside. }
9... Ne4 10. c3 e5 11. Nfd2 Nxd2 12. Nxd2 Bf5 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Rc1 Rc8 15. Nf3
{ The idea is to answer ...exd4 with Nxd4 ! Or simply provoke e4, after which Nd2 followed by c4 is pleasant. }
15... h5 16. Qb3
{ In any case, we have a very interesting and complex game ahead of us, and White has a solid position. }
