[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 3.e3"]
[Black "3.e3 c6 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6
{ Before deciding where to place the light-squared bishop, Black goes for this typical Slav move. Now, White has a choice between 4. c4, with a direct transpostion to the Slav, which is OK. Or, employ a line that I am trying to give more credit. Of course, you have understood that I am trying to find different ideas in this book, avoiding main lines. }
4. Bd3
{ Clearly, this is not intended to get an advantage directly from the opening. It is more important here to understand how to conduct such positions and perhaps a few of these ideas will help establish some advantage. }
4... Bg4 { Black continues in a Slav-like mannner. } 5. Nbd2 e6 6. O-O Nbd7 7.
b3 Bd6 8. Bb2
{ Indeed, the position is similar to some Slav lines, so it is no surprise that it is mainly about control over the e5-square.  We will study the alternative   8.c4 !?  in the next subchapter. }
8... O-O
{ A.   8...Qe7  9.h3  Bh5   9...Bxf3  10.Nxf3  e5  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Re1 !?  O-O  13.e4  Nxd3  14.cxd3  dxe4  15.dxe4  Bb4  16.Re2  Rfe8  17.Qc2  Rad8  18.Rd1  Rxd1+  19.Qxd1  Bc5  20.Be5  with a playable position.  10.c4  e5  11.e4  dxe4  12.Bxe4 !  Avoiding too many exchanges. This move is not a usual reaction in such postions, but here it is fully justified.  O-O   12...Nxe4  13.Nxe4  ±  13.Bf5  exd4  14.Re1  Qd8  15.Bxd4  +=  with a direct transposition to the 8. c4 line.  B.   8...e5  9.dxe5  Bxe5 !?   9...Nxe5  10.Be2  Nxf3+  11.Bxf3  Bxf3  12.Qxf3  O-O  13.c4  Due to simultaneous pressure on d5 and f6, Black has some problems to resolve.  10.c3 !?  Avoiding simplifications, which would lead to equality.  O-O  11.Qc2  Re8   11...Bd6  12.c4  +=  12.h3  Bh5  13.Nxe5  Nxe5  14.Bf5  Bg6  15.Bxg6  hxg6  16.Rad1  Qe7  17.c4  dxc4 !   17...Rad8  18.cxd5  +=  18.Bxe5  Qxe5  19.Nxc4  Qc5  20.Rd4  Rad8  21.Rfd1  Rd5 =  After precise play, Black has equalised. }
9. c4 Re8
{ This is yet another position where Black has few other options:  A.   9...a5  10.Qc2  Qb8  11.h3  Bh5  12.Ng5 !  The main idea here, White forces matters. He simply wants to double pawns on g6, thus giving the knight on g5 a comfortable spot, from where it may cause some problems.  Bg6  13.Bxg6  hxg6  14.a4  Bb4  15.Ndf3  Nh7  16.Nxh7  Kxh7  17.e4  Nf6  18.Ng5+  Kg8  19.e5  Nh7  20.h4  Qd8  21.Nf3  +=  This game is perfect example how White should treat such positions. 1-0, 54 moves, Andreikin, D. 2712 - Korobov, A. 2652, Huai'an blitz 2017.  B.   9...Qe7  10.Qc2  e5  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Bxe5  Bxe5  13.Nxe5  Qxe5  14.h3  Be6   14...Bh5  15.cxd5  cxd5  16.Rac1  +=  15.Nf3  Qh5  16.Nd4  dxc4  17.bxc4  +=  with possible pressure along the b-file.  C.   9...Qb8  10.Qc2  Bh5  11.h3  Bg6  12.Bxg6  hxg6  13.Ng5 !  The idea is f4.  e5  14.cxd5  cxd5  15.dxe5  Bxe5  16.Ndf3 !  +=  The g5-knight stays put and acts as a thorn in Black's kingside.  D.   9...e5  10.cxd5  Bxf3   10...cxd5  11.dxe5  Bxe5  12.Qb1  Bxb2  13.Qxb2  Nc5  14.Bc2  Qd6  15.Rac1  Rac8  16.h3  Bxf3  17.Nxf3  g6  18.b4  Nce4  19.a3  Rfd8  20.Bd3  +=  It isn't much, we have reached a typical isolani position, but it is somehow easier to handle for White.  11.Qxf3  cxd5  12.dxe5  Bxe5  13.Bxe5  Nxe5  14.Qf5  White must act fast because f5-queen and d3-bishop are not on their ideal squares.  Qe7   14...Re8  15.Bb5 !  Re6  16.Rfd1  Rc8  17.Be2  g6  18.Qb1  White managed to consolidate and we can say that his chances are slightly better.  15.Nf3 !  Nxf3+  16.Qxf3  Rac8  17.Qf4 !  White has played well, so we have achieved a good position again.  h6   17...Rc6  18.Rfc1  Rfc8  19.Rxc6  bxc6  20.Rd1  c5  21.Be2  g6  22.g4  Qe6  23.Bf3  Again here we have better chances for White.  18.Rfc1  Qa3  19.Rd1  Rc6  20.g3  a5  21.Kg2  Rfc8  22.Rd2  White can play for an advantage. }
10. Qc2 e5 11. cxd5 Bxf3
{ The alternative leads to a typical play:   11...cxd5  12.dxe5  Rc8  13.Qb1  Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Bxe5  15.h3  Bh5  16.Bxe5  Rxe5  17.Qb2  += }
12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 Nxd5 15. f4 Qh4 16. Kh1 Be7 17. Rg1 Bf6
18. Bxf6 Nxf6 19. Rg3 g6
{ 19...Kh8  20.Rag1  g6   20...Rg8  21.Bf5 !  +-  with the winning idea Rh3.  21.Qb2  += }
20. f5
{ White has managed to create some pressure, giving him a certain edge. } *

