[Black "3.e3 c6 Variation 8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6
{ Before deciding where to place the light-squared bishop, Black goes for this typical Slav move. Now, White has a choice between 4. c4, with a direct transpostion to the Slav, which is OK. Or, employ a line that I am trying to give more credit. Of course, you have understood that I am trying to find different ideas in this book, avoiding main lines. }
4. Bd3
{ Clearly, this is not intended to get an advantage directly from the opening. It is more important here to understand how to conduct such positions and perhaps a few of these ideas will help establish some advantage. }
4... Bg4 { Black continues in a Slav-like mannner. } 5. Nbd2 e6 6. O-O Nbd7 7.
b3 Bd6 8. Bb2
{ Indeed, the position is similar to some Slav lines, so it is no surprise that it is mainly about control over the e5-square. }
8... O-O { Black can also deviate here. } 9. c4 a5 10. Qc2 Qb8 11. h3 Bh5 12.
Ng5
{ The main idea here, White forces matters. He simply wants to double pawns on g6, thus giving the knight on g5 a comfortable spot, from where it may cause some problems. }
12... Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. a4 Bb4 15. Ndf3 Nh7 16. Nxh7 Kxh7 17. e4 Nf6 18.
Ng5+ Kg8 19. e5 Nh7 20. h4 Qd8 21. Nf3
{ This game is perfect example how White should treat such positions. 1-0, 54 moves, Andreikin, D. 2712 - Korobov, A. 2652, Huai'an blitz 2017. }
*

