[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 3.e3"]
[Black "3.e3 c6 w/ 8.c4 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 4. Bd3 Bg4 5. Nbd2 e6 6. O-O Nbd7 7. b3 Bd6 8. c4
{ This is another way of meeting this setup. White hurriedly attacks the centre, delaying the development of his dark-squared bishop. }
8... Qe7
{ A.   8...e5  9.cxd5  cxd5  10.dxe5  Bxe5   10...Nxe5  11.Be2  →  11.Rb1  O-O  12.h3  Bh5  13.b4  a5  14.bxa5  Rxa5  15.Bf5 !?  Bd6  16.Bb2  Bg6  17.Nh4 !?  Rxa2  18.Qb3  Ra8  19.Qxb7  White preserves some edge.  B.   8...O-O  9.Qc2 !?  The idea is to discourage a fast ...e5.  e5  10.cxd5  cxd5  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Nxe5  Bxe5  13.Bb2  Rc8  14.Qb1  Qd6   14...d4  15.Nc4  ±  15.h3  Bh5  16.a4  Rfe8  17.Rc1  White's knight cannot reach f3 immediately. But Black will eventually have to allow it, after which White will achieve a slight edge. }
9. h3
{ The alternative is also OK but probably Black can equalize:   9.Bb2  e5  10.e4 !?  An interesting reaction that deserves attention.   10.dxe5  Nxe5  11.Be2  Nxf3+  12.Bxf3  Bxf3  13.Qxf3  Be5  14.Bxe5  Qxe5 =  10...dxe4  11.Bxe4 !?  We have already seen this theme.  O-O  12.Bc2  Ba3  13.Qc1  Bxb2  14.Qxb2  Bxf3  15.Nxf3  exd4  16.Nxd4  Rfe8  17.Nf5  Qe5  18.Qxe5  Rxe5  19.Nd6  b6  20.f4  Re6  21.Rad1  Kf8 = }
9... Bxf3
{ 9...Bh5  10.Bb2  e5  11.e4 !  dxe4  12.Bxe4  O-O  13.Bf5 !?  This is one of the possible differences.  exd4  14.Re1  Qd8  15.Bxd4  White has a more active position. }
10. Nxf3 e5 11. cxd5 e4 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Nh4 { Interesting tactical motive. }
13... exd3 14. Nf5 Qf8 15. e4 O-O-O 16. Qxd3 Kb7 17. b4
{ White has decent compensation for the sacrificed piece, reminiscent of many Sicilians ! }
*

