[White "Systems with ...d5: 3.e3 c5"]
[Black "3.e3 c5 4.dxc5!? - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. dxc5
{ Black really has to be ready for such a reaction as it can lead to very sharp positions. }
4... e6
{ 4...Qa5+  5.Nbd2  Qxc5  6.c4  e6  7.b3  Be7  8.Bb2  O-O  9.Bd3  Nc6  10.a3  a5  11.Rc1  Qd6  12.Qc2  h6  13.O-O  White has very good chances. }
5. b4
{ One can notice similarities with the Noteboom line and some other reversed Slav lines, with the f3-knight being White's extra tempo. As previously mentioned in the book, having an extra tempo in sharp positions cannot be neglected, as may be the case with more solid  (closed)  positions, where tempi have less of an effect. }
5... a5
{ Complicated but playable:   5...b6  6.cxb6  Bxb4+   6...axb6  7.c3  Bd7  8.b5  Bc8  9.Bd3  Nbd7  10.Bb2  Nc5  11.Bc2  Qc7  12.Nbd2  Bb7  13.O-O  White is a pawn up.  7.c3  Bc5  8.Bb5+  Nbd7  9.Bc6 !?   9.bxa7  Rxa7  10.O-O  Ba6  11.c4  dxc4  12.Qa4  Qb6  13.Bxc4  O-O  14.Bxa6  Rxa6  15.Qc2  Rc8  16.Bb2  Nd5  17.Qe2  Rca8  18.Nc3  +=  A.  9...Ba6 !?  A tough move to play but possible.  B.   9...Rb8  10.bxa7  Bxa7  11.Ba3  Rb6  12.Ba4  Qc7  13.Nbd2  Ba6  14.Rc1  Rb8  15.c4  A complicated line. In this particular position, White has the better chances.  10.Qa4  axb6  11.Bxa8  Qxa8  12.Na3  O-O  13.Nb5  Rc8  14.Qb3  Ne4  15.a4  Be7  16.Ba3  Ndc5  17.Qc2  Bf6  18.Nfd4  e5  19.Nf5  Nxc3  20.Nfd6  Black can probably draw, but it is not easy to play all of these moves unless they are committed to memory. White, on the other hand, doesn't risk much. }
6. c3 axb4
{ Black has another option, though it looks more passive:   6...b6  7.Bb5+  Bd7  8.Bxd7+  Nfxd7  9.O-O  bxc5  10.b5  Be7  11.a4  O-O  12.Nbd2  with the idea of c4 and the potential for a slight advantage. }
7. cxb4 b6 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4 bxc5 11. b5 Bd6
{ We have reached a highly unbalanced position. White has passed pawns on the queenside but Black has strong control over the centre and a passed c-pawn. White does have the e4-break up his sleeve, if necessary. But again, alternatives exist.  A. Black can also try to be even more active:   11...c4 !?  12.O-O  Nc5  13.Nd4  Bd6  14.Ba3 !?  O-O   14...Rxa4  15.Nc6  Qc7  16.Nc3  is better for White.  15.Nc6  Qc7  16.Bxc5  Bxc5  17.Nc3  Nd7  18.a5  Bd6  19.g3  Nb8  20.Nxb8  Rfxb8  21.Qa4  Be5  22.Rfc1  h5  With balanced play.  B.   11...Ne4  12.O-O  Be7  13.Bb2  O-O  14.Nbd2  Bf6  15.Bxf6  Nexf6  16.Qc2  Qb6  17.Qc3  h6  18.Ra2  Ra7  19.Rfa1  Rb8  20.Ne5  Nxe5  21.Qxe5  Rba8  22.Qc3  Nd7  23.Qc2  Unclear but balanced. }
12. O-O O-O
{ Black can try an early endeavour:   12...Qc7  13.Nbd2  e5  14.e4  c4  15.exd5  c3  16.Nb3  e4  17.Nfd4  Bxh2+  18.Kh1  Be5  19.a5  O-O  20.Nc6  Rfe8  21.Ra4  The position is complicated. }
13. Nbd2 Qc7 14. Bb2 c4
{ 14...Rfd8  15.Qc2  c4  16.Bc3  e5  17.h3  Nc5  18.a5  Although these positions are rather complex, it is completely possible to play like this as White. }
15. Qc2 Nc5 16. h3
{ 16.Bc3  Rfb8  17.Rfb1  Ng4  18.h3  Ne5  19.Nxe5  Bxe5  20.a5  Bxc3  21.Qxc3  Qd7  22.b6  Ra6  23.Nxc4 !   23.Qb4  Nb7  24.Rd1  +=  1/2-1/2, 35 moves, Boehm, T. 2148 - Karpatchev, A. 2489, Lueneburg 2016.  23...dxc4  24.Qxc4  Rc8  25.b7  White should win. }
16... e5 17. Rfb1 Nd3 18. Ba3 Bxa3 19. Rxa3 Qa5
{ 19...Qe7  20.Raa1  Nd7  21.a5  Qc5  22.Ra4  Rfb8  23.Nxc4 !  Also leads also to a better game for White. }
20. b6
{ White managed to start pushing his pawns. 1-0, 29 moves, Morovic Fernandez, I. 2527 - Slipak, S. 2465, Buenos Aires 2017. }
*

