[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 3.e3 c5"]
[Black "4.Nbd2 And Others - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nbd2
{ A solid and flexible approach from White. All options are still on the table and though it may seem like a bit of a slow system, we will see that there is a plethora of possibilities here. }
4... e6
{ A. Also deserving of attention is:   4...Nc6  5.c3 !?   5.dxc5 !?  e6  6.a3  a5  7.Bb5  Bxc5  8.b3  O-O  9.O-O  Qc7  10.Bb2  Rd8  11.Qb1 !?  b6  12.c4  Bb7  13.cxd5  Rxd5  14.Rc1  Ng4  15.Nf1  with a very interesting game.  5...e6   5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bf5  transposes to the next subchapter.  6.Bd3  Transpose to Colle.  B.   4...Nbd7  5.b3  g6   5...e6  6.Bb2  transposes to given lines in the Zukertort.  6.Bb2  Bg7  7.Be2  O-O  8.O-O  b6  9.a4 !?  a6  10.c4  Bb7  11.Qc2  e6  12.a5  bxa5  13.Bc3  White has easier play in this rather complex position. I will add that position actually is a reversed Queen's Indian in which Black didn't adopt best plan. }
5. b3 { Transposing to the Zukertort. } 5... cxd4
{ A.   5...Nc6  6.Bb2  Bd6  7.Bd3  Qc7 !?  With the idea of ...cxd4 followed by ...Nb4.  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.O-O  e5  10.c4 !  ±  B.   5...Nbd7  6.Bb2  Bd6  7.Bd3  Qc7  8.c4 !  A thematic approach we've seen many times when queen comes to c7.   8.O-O  e5  9.dxe5  Nxe5  is the kind of position we have already analysed. }
6. exd4 Bb4 { With the idea to create early disturbances in White's position. }
7. Bb2 Ne4
{ I cannot resist including an old game here, in which we can clearly see that famous old players already knew it all !   7...Qa5  8.c3 !  Bd6  9.Bd3  Nc6  10.O-O  Bd7  11.Qe2  a6  12.Ne5  White has already achieved his dream position with f2-f4 to come !  Ba3 ?  13.Ndc4 !  dxc4  14.Nxc4  Bxb2  15.Nxa5  Bxa1  16.Nxc6  Bxc3  17.Ne5  Rd8  18.Qe3  +-  1-0, 49 moves, Marshall, F. - Duras, O., Karlsbad 1911. }
8. Bd3 Nc6
{ 8...Qa5  9.c4 !  O-O   9...Nc6  10.a3  Bxd2+  11.Nxd2  Nxd2  12.Qxd2  Qxd2+  13.Kxd2  Na5  14.Kc2  dxc4  15.bxc4  Bd7  16.Bc3  White has the better endgame.  10.a3  Bxd2+  11.Nxd2  Qxd2+  12.Qxd2  Nxd2  13.Kxd2  Nc6  14.c5 !  White is simply better due to the pair of bishops and queenside majority. }
9. O-O Bc3 10. Bxc3 Nxc3 11. Qe1
{ 11.Qc1 !?  I tried to improve on one of Kramnik games and came up with this idea.  Nb4  12.Qb2  Nxd3  13.Qxc3  Nf4  14.Qe3  Ng6  15.c4  dxc4   15...O-O  16.c5  +=  16.bxc4  O-O  17.a4  Bd7  18.a5  Rc8  19.Rfd1  Bc6  20.Ne5  Nxe5  21.Qxe5  An imbalanced position with a knight versus bishop. White will attempt to transfer his cavalry to the strong e3-square, thus supporting the d5-thrust. }
11... Nb4 12. Qe5
{ An interesting tactical idea.  Kramnik reacted in a normal way but allowed Black to reach level play:   12.Nb1  Nxd3  13.Qxc3  Nf4  14.Qe3  Ng6  15.c4  dxc4  16.bxc4  O-O  17.Nc3  Bd7  18.Rfd1  Rc8  19.Nd2  Nh4  20.Qd3  Nf5  ∞  Black achieved good counterplay. 0-1, 64 moves, Kramnik, V. 2792 - Giri, A. 2782, Dortmund 2018. }
12... Qf6
{ The most logical.  A.   12...O-O ?  13.Bxh7+ !  Kxh7  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Ng5  wins for White.  B. If   12...Kf8  I guess we have improved on Kramnik's position as the Black king is stuck in the centre, at least momentarily.  13.Qe3  Bd7  14.Nb1  Qc7  15.Nxc3  Qxc3  16.Qf4  Kg8  17.Rfc1  White is better here. }
13. Qc7 Nxd3 14. Qxc3 Nf4 15. Rae1 O-O 16. Ne5 Qd8 17. Qg3 Ng6 18. Nxg6 hxg6
19. Nf3
{ The doubled pawns on the g-file help White in this case, making the knight better than the bishop. }
*

