[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems with ...d5: 3.e3 c5"]
[Black "4.Nbd2 cxd4 5.exd4 Nc6 6.c3 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nbd2 cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6
{ Simplifying the situation in the centre helps Black develop his pieces without having to worry about potential dxc5 ideas. Black is now ready to go for ...Bf5 or ...Bg4. }
6. c3 { One of the main aspects of White's play; now Bd3 is in the air. } 6...
Bf5 7. Be2
{ A modest approach but a very solid one. We will see that White has a couple of interesting hidden ideas in this position. }
7... e6
{ 7...h6  It is possible to lose another move on defending the bishop:  8.O-O   8.Nb3 !?  e6  9.Bf4  Bd6  10.Bxd6  Qxd6  11.O-O  O-O  12.Re1  White has a solid position.  8...e6  9.Re1  Bd6  10.Nf1  O-O  11.Ng3  Bh7  12.Bd3 !  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Qc7  14.Qe2 !?  Rab8  15.Ne5  b5  16.Qf3 !  The key idea here !  Bxe5  17.dxe5  Nd7   17...Nxe5 ?  18.Rxe5  Qxe5  19.Bf4  wins a queen. A trick worth noting.  18.Nh5  Ne7 !  19.Qh3 !  with unclear play. Black has to watch out for Nxg7. }
8. Nh4
{ The main idea here, but there are other motives as well.   8.Nf1  Bd6  9.Ng3  Bg6  10.O-O  O-O  11.Nh4  Nd7  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Bd3  Qh4  14.f4 !  White must take control of the centre.  f5 !?  15.Rf3  Nf6  16.Nf1 !  The knight on g3 is bad and must be transfered to a better square.  Ne4  17.g3  Qf6  18.h4  a6  19.Kg2  b5  20.a3  Rab8  21.Nh2  a5  22.Re3  b4   22...Rfc8  23.Nf3  b4  24.axb4  axb4  25.c4 !  +=  23.axb4  axb4  24.Bxe4  fxe4  25.Ra6  White is better. A highly interesting and instructive game. 1-0, 34 moves, Jussupow, A. 2640 - Goldin, A. 2575, Tilburg 1992. }
8... Bg6 9. O-O Bd6 10. g3 O-O 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. f4
{ Proceeding without f4 is also possible:   12.Nf3  Qc7   12...Ne4  13.Bd3  f5  14.Bxe4 !  fxe4  15.Ng5  Rf6  16.Qg4  White wins as Qh4 is an unstoppable threat.  13.Re1  Rab8  14.Bd3  b5  15.a3  a5  16.Bg5  b4  17.axb4  axb4  18.c4  White has good play here. }
12... Rb8 13. a4 a6 14. Bd3 b5 15. b4
{ A thematic approach borrowed from the QGD, which is valid here too. Now White also has assets as the knight can jump to the strong c5-square.   15.Qe2  Qb6  16.Kg2  It is also possible to play like this. }
15... Qb6 16. Kg2 Ne7 17. axb5 axb5 18. Qe2 Rfc8 19. Bb2
{ Temporary only - when the white knight reaches c5, the dark-squared bishop will be free to change its diagonal again. }
19... Nf5 20. Nb3
{ The position is complex but extremely unpleasant for Black. } *

