1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nbd2 cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb5
{ The current World Champion's favorite idea. } 6... e6
{ A.   6...Bg4  7.c4 !?  It is possible to play less sharp:   7.c3 !?  a6  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.Qa4  Qc7  10.Ne5  Bd7  11.c4 !?  e6  12.c5  Be7  13.O-O  O-O  14.Re1  White has a decent position.  7...dxc4  8.Qa4  Bd7  9.Ne5  Nxe5   9...Nxd4  10.Qxc4  Ne6  11.O-O  =∞  10.dxe5  Bxb5  11.Qxb5+  Qd7  12.Qxc4  Nd5  13.O-O  Rc8  14.Qd4  e6  15.Ne4  →  a6  16.Bg5 !  h6  17.Bh4  Nf4  18.Nf6+  gxf6  19.Qxf4  fxe5  20.Qxe5  ±  1-0, 27 moves, Carlsen, M. 2832 - So, W. 2815, Chess.com 2017.  B.   6...Bd7  This may lead to a similar play as in 6... e6.  7.c3  e6  8.Bd3  Bd6  9.O-O  O-O  10.Re1  Qc7  11.Qe2  Nh5   11...Rfc8  12.Ne5  Be8  13.Ndf3  h6  14.Bd2  a6  15.h3 !  b5  16.Ng4  White tries to establish an attack with the same motif.  12.g3  Nf6  By provoking g3, Black has managed to sidestep certain attacking ideas, such as the possible use of the third rank.  13.Ne5  h6  14.Ndf3  Rac8  15.h3 !?  A good idea, as seen in previous analysis.  a6  16.Bf4  Nh5  17.Bd2  Nf6  18.Nh2 !  White is able to carry out attacking ideas. }
7. O-O
{ 7.Ne5 !?  Bd7  8.Nxd7 !?  This is what Carlsen wants: to take the bishop.  Qxd7  9.c3  Now that White has the pair of bishops, he can safely go back to d3 and try to create strong play on the kingside.  Bd6  10.O-O   10.Bd3  e5 !?  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Nf3  O-O  13.O-O  Nxd3  14.Qxd3  h6  15.Re1  Rfe8  16.Be3  a6  17.Bd4  Ne4  18.Rad1  Qc6  19.g3  +=  10...Qc7   10...O-O  11.f4 !?  This is very much possible and similar to the game.  11.g3  O-O  12.f4  We have already seen something similar in a different line.  a6  13.Bd3  b5  14.a3  Qb6  15.Nf3  a5  16.Qe2  b4  17.a4 !  When having a light-squared bishop, this is a thematic approach.  Qc7  18.Ne5  Rab8  19.Ra2 !?  Ne7  20.Bd2  Qb7  21.Re1  bxc3  22.bxc3  Qc7  23.Qf3  Rb3  24.g4  with rather complex and highly interesting postion. 1-0, 61 moves, Mueller, K. 2515 - Naumann, A. 2548, Germany 2008. }
7... Bd6 8. c3 O-O 9. Re1
{ The point of White's play in this case is that the c8-bishop is behind its pawn chain. Hence, the b5-bishop will return to d3 and, with that, White will attain his dream postion. }
9... Qc7 10. Qe2 Nd7
{ A.   10...Re8  11.Ne5  Nd7  12.Ndf3  An illustration of how the game could develop:  f6  13.Ng4  e5  14.dxe5  fxe5  15.Ne3  Nb6  16.Rd1  d4  17.Nf1  Bg4  18.Bd3  Qd7  19.a4  Nd5  20.Bc4  Be6  21.Ng5  White is better.  B.   10...b6  11.Ne5  Bb7  12.Nb3 !?  Anticipating a potential capture on e5, when the knight would be ready to land on d4.  h6  13.Bf4  Ne4  14.f3  Nf6  15.Rac1  Ne7  16.Bd3  a5  17.a4  with a complicated game ahead. }
11. Nf1 h6 12. Bd2 Rd8 13. Rad1 a6 14. Bd3 b5 15. Ne3 Nf6 16. h3 Bb7 17. Ng4
