1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5
{ is a logical response.  Black is playing actively and brings another pawn to the centre. White does have a few interesting ideas though:   A.  4.dxc5!?  A slightly controversial idea, leading to sharp positions. Not much investigation has been carried out here.   B.  4.Nbd2  Logical play. After  4...cxd4  Another chapter contains other ideas, too.  5.exd4  Nc6  , White has two compelling ideas.  6.c3  is the more solid attempt.   And  6.Bb5!?  is the more aggressive option.  In both cases, complex positions will ensue in which White will try and get an attack going. }
*

