[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems without ...d5: 1...Nf6 2.Nf3 c5"]
[Black "1...Nf6 2.Nf3 c5 3.d5 g6 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5
{ Of course, White can go 3 e3 here, which would probably transpose to some of the positions given in other chapters. However, I decided to give a fresh look at offbeat lines such as the Schmidt Benoni. }
3... g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 d6 6. h3 O-O 7. a4
{ White's moves are not so well known, but the ensuing positions are interesting. Of course, playing two consecutive pawn moves in the opening is not ideal as it is important to develop the pieces first. In this case, however, as the position is closed and Black's pieces don't have many active squares, the rule can be broken. }
7... Na6
{ This is the usual response in this system, Black looks for long-term play on the queenside, which will be facilitated by a knight on c7.  Another critical line here is:   7...e6  8.Bc4  exd5  9.Bxd5 !?  An unusual reaction that deserves attention.  Nxd5   9...Nc6  10.O-O  Nb4  11.Bb3  Be6  12.Bxe6  fxe6  13.Bg5  transposes to 7... Na6 8 Bc4 9 Nb4 below.  10.Nxd5  Re8  11.O-O !  h6   11...Rxe4 ?  12.Bg5  f6  13.Nxf6+  Bxf6  14.Qd5+  Re6  15.Rae1  Qe7  16.Bxf6  Qxf6  17.Ng5  +-  12.Re1  Na6  13.Bf4  White applies the simple strategy of attacking the d6-pawn.  Nb4  14.c3  Nxd5  15.Qxd5  Bf8  16.Qd2  White seems to maintain some pressure.  A.  Kh7  B.   16...g5  17.Bg3  Be6  18.h4  f6  19.Qc2  Qe7  20.c4  Rad8  21.b3  Qf7  22.Rad1  Qg6  23.Nh2  intending to bring the knight to e3.  17.Nh2 !  Be6  18.Ng4  Bxg4   18...h5  19.Ne3  White has managed to control the d5-square, and hence, has a slight edge.  19.hxg4  Qc7  20.f3  Rad8  21.Red1  White has firm control over the d5-square. }
8. Bc4
{ This is the main idea behind White's play. The bishop goes to c4 in one move, helping White keep control of the centre, which will be further supported by a rook on e1 and bishop on f4. The most famous game in this system must be Karpov-Korchnoi, from the Baguio match. }
8... Nc7
{ 8...Nb4  9.O-O  e5   9...e6  will transpose.  10.dxe6  Bxe6  11.Bxe6  fxe6  12.Bg5  h6  13.Bxf6  Qxf6  14.e5 !  A typical central break that mustn't be overlooked !   14.Qxd6  Nxc2  15.e5  Qf5  16.Rad1  Nd4  17.Nxd4  cxd4  18.Qxd4  Bxe5  Black had enough play. 1/2-1/2, 21 moves, Pereyra Arcija, D. 2290 - Panno, O. 2530, Buenos Aires 1995.  14...dxe5  15.Ne4  Qe7  16.Qe2  Black's bishop is bad, his structure is fragile, and White has firm control of the light squares. }
9. O-O e6
{ 9...b6  10.Qd3 !?  Bb7  11.Bf4  gives White a much better version compared to the classical main line.  Nd7  12.Rfe1  f6  13.Ra3  Kh8   13...a6  14.h4  ±  14.a5  a6  15.axb6  Nxb6  16.Nd2  Rb8  17.Rb3  Nd7  18.Bh2  1/2-1/2, Valerga, D. 2375 - Panno, O. 2520, Buenos Aires 1994. This early draw is misleading and certainly doesn't mean that Black has equalised. Actually, I would say that White is better here. }
10. Bf4
{ 10.dxe6  Bxe6  11.Bxe6  Nxe6  12.Qd3  Qc7  13.Rd1  Rad8  14.Be3  Rfe8  15.Nd2  ∞  With unclear play. }
10... exd5 11. Nxd5
{ My idea is to take back on d5 with pieces. It may not be much, but at least it is a new challenge for Black to face.   11.exd5  Rb8  12.Re1   12.Qd2  a6  13.a5  b5  14.axb6  Rxb6  15.b3  Nb5  16.Na4  Rb7  Unclear. 1-0, 50 moves, Andres Gonzalez, A. 2485 - Mate Adan, C. 2277, Ourense 2009.  12...a6  13.a5  b5  14.axb6  Rxb6  15.Rb1  Nb5  16.Bxb5 !?  axb5  17.b4  Bd7  18.Qd2  Re8  19.Rxe8+  Bxe8  20.Bh6  Bh8  21.Bg5  White's chances are preferable. }
11... Ncxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Be6 14. Qxd6 Qa5 15. Be5 Rad8 16. Qe7 Rfe8
17. Qh4 Bxe5 18. Nxe5 Rd4 19. Nf3 Rxa4 20. Rad1
{ White is more comfortable here. } *

