[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5
{ A reaction typical of Benko players. I decided to suggest something new against this system, that recently caught my eye. }
4. c3
{ A highly interesting and relatively new idea. White wants to trade his e-pawn for Black's b-pawn.Though this exchange may seem antipositional, it yields White harmonious play and fast development.   4.Bg5  is the main move. }
4... g6
{ A.   4...a6  5.Bg5  Qb6   5...Bb7  6.Bxf6  gxf6  7.e4  e6  8.a4  White's chances are preferable.  6.Bxf6  Qxf6  7.Nbd2  e6   7...g6  8.a4  b4  9.cxb4  cxb4  10.Qc1  White wins.   7...d6  8.a4  White is better.  8.e4  Bb7  9.Bd3  exd5  10.O-O  with initiative.  B.   4...Bb7  5.e4 !  Nxe4  6.Bxb5  Nf6   6...Qa5  7.Na3  Nf6  8.d6  Ne4  9.Bf4  Qb6  10.dxe7  Bxe7  11.Bxb8  Rxb8  12.Qxd7+  Kf8  13.Nc4  Qd8  14.Nfe5  Nf6  15.Qxd8+  Bxd8  16.O-O  White was better. 1-0, 47 moves, Berkes, F. 2648 - Esipenko, A. 2492, Zurich 2017.  7.c4  g6  8.Nc3  Bg7  9.Be3  Qc7  10.O-O  O-O  11.Re1  d6  12.Bg5  Black's e7-pawn makes his position rather unpleasant.  a6  13.Ba4  Bc8  14.h3  Ra7  15.Qd2  Qb6  16.Rad1  White simply doesn't allow ...e6 or ...e5.  Rb7  17.Re2  Qb4  18.a3 !  Qb6   18...Qxc4 ?  19.b3  Rxb3  20.Bxb3  Qxb3  21.Rb1  +-  19.Bh6  This game shows White's plan and how to achieve an advantage. 1-0, 42 moves, Hillarp Persson, T. 2543 - Risting, E. 2308, Kragero 2018.  C. A recent game was played in this line:   4...Qb6  5.a4  b4  C1. White played:  6.c4  C2. Another possible idea is:   6.Nbd2 !?  Nxd5  7.Nc4  Qc6  8.Nce5  Qb7  9.e4  Nf6  10.Ng5  and White is better.  C3.   6.Bg5 !?  C.3.1.  Ne4  C.3.2.   6...g6  7.a5  Qd6  8.cxb4  Qxd5   8...cxb4  9.Qc2  Na6  10.e4  leads to better play for White.  9.Nc3  Qxd1+  10.Rxd1  cxb4  11.Nb5  Na6  12.Nd6+  exd6  13.Bxf6  Rg8  14.Ng5  h6  15.Nh7  Be7  16.Bd4  f5  17.Nf6+  Bxf6  18.Bxf6  Bb7  19.Rxd6  Rc8  20.e3  Nc5  21.f3  Nb3  22.Be2  After this unforced sequence of moves, White may have slighlty better chances in the endgame.  7.Bf4  e6  8.e3  Bb7   8...exd5  9.Qxd5  Bb7  10.a5  Qc6  11.Qxc6  Nxc6  12.a6  Bc8  13.Bc4  White has a strong position.  9.a5  Qd8  10.Bc4  Nf6  11.e4 !  Nxe4 ?  12.a6  Bc8  13.O-O  White wins.  6...g6  7.Nbd2  Bg7  8.e4  d6  9.Bd3  O-O  10.O-O  e6  11.dxe6 ?!  Bxe6  12.Ra2  Nc6  13.b3  Ng4  14.h3  Nge5  and Black was fine. 0-1, 36 moves, Houska, J. 2402 - Gelfand, B. 2701, Douglas ENG 2018. }
5. e4
{ White's main and somewhat unusual idea is to trade e-for b-pawns, speeding up his development and opening the e-file. It has similarities to the line 1 b4 e5 2 Bb2 Bxb4, which is known to be good for Black. }
5... Nxe4 6. Bxb5 Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ 7...Nd6  8.Bd3  O-O  9.Re1  Bb7  10.Bg5  Re8  11.Na3  f6  12.Bf4  Nf7  13.h4 !   13.Qb3  Qc8  14.Bc4  a6  15.Re3  d6  16.Rae1  Ne5  17.Bxe5  fxe5  18.Ng5  →  1/2-1/2, 79 moves, Schleining, Z. 2382 - Fuchs, J. 2286, Vysoke Tatry 2018.  13...d6  14.h5  g5  15.Bg3  Nd7  16.Be4  White is clearly better. }
8. Re1 Nf6 9. c4 d6 10. Nc3
{ White has a good central structure and easy development. Black would like to reduce the pressure along the e-file by playing ...e5, but this is easier said than done ! }
10... Nbd7
{ 10...e5  11.dxe6  Bxe6  12.Bf4  d5  13.Bg5 !  d4  14.Ne4  White is better. }
11. Bg5 Nb6 12. Bc6 Rb8 13. b3 h6 14. Bd2 e6 15. dxe6 Bxe6 16. Rc1 Rc8 17. Bb7
Rc7 18. Ba6 Qa8 19. a4 g5 20. a5 Nbd7 21. Be3 Nb8 22. Bb5
{ White's position is slightly more favourable. 1-0, 89 moves, Sedlak, N. 2608 - Milanovic, D. 2454, Valjevo 2018. }
