[Black "Chapter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5
{ Variation 1  6.Nbd2   Variation 2  6.c4 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems without ...d5: 2...e6 3.e3 b6"]
[Black "The Flexible 6.Nbd2 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5
{ A very popular idea amongst the Queen's and Nimzo-Indian players with Black. Its a flexible and solid system, which can also give Black good chances to play for the win. Having a pawn on d6,Black deprives White of typical attacking Colle-Zukertort ideas involving Ne5. In my personal tournament practice, I have faced this system as White a number of times.   5...d5  transposes to Chapter 4. }
6. Nbd2
{ Non-committal. No decision is made between c3 or b3 yet. Therefore, White simply develops the knight while fighting for the e4-square.  For   6.c4  see the next subchapter. }
6... Be7 { 6...d5  7.b3  transposes to Zukertort lines. } 7. c3
{ The e4-push is in the air. } 7... Nc6
{ Other possible ideas are: A.   7...O-O  8.e4  d6  9.Re1  Nc6   9...cxd4  10.cxd4  Nbd7  11.Nf1  Re8  12.Ng3  a6  13.Bd2  Nf8  14.Rc1  +=  An example of typical play in this line. White has more space and easy development, while Black has a solid but slightly passive position.  10.Nf1  Rc8  11.a3 !  +=  Not only taking control of the b4-square but also preparing a potential queenside expansion with b4.   11.Ng3 ?  cxd4  12.cxd4  Nb4  13.Bb1  Qc7 !  =+  A key idea worth remembering, where Black get goods play.  B.   7...cxd4  8.exd4  O-O  9.Qe2  d6  10.Nc4  Nbd7  11.Bf4  I know this book is not about the London System, but similarities are often apparent and the different positions can seem to switch from one system to the other.  Qc7  12.h3  a6  13.a4  Rfe8  14.Bh2  Bf8  15.Ne3  g6  16.Rfd1  The idea is Ne1, heading to b4. That's just one of the many possible plans here.  C. Another idea is:   7...d5 !?  8.Ne5  O-O  9.Qe2  Nbd7  10.f4  Ne4  11.Nxe4 !?  dxe4  12.Bc4 !  This motif is starting to look familiar, and here again, it is White's best choice.  Nf6   12...Nxe5  13.fxe5  Rc8  14.b3  Rc7  15.Bb2  Qc8  16.Rac1  a6  17.a4  h6  with complex play.  13.f5  exf5  14.Rxf5  Bd5  15.Bxd5 !?   15.Bd2  Rc8 ?!  16.Bxd5  Qxd5  17.c4  Qe6  18.Raf1  b5 ?!  19.d5  Qd6  20.cxb5  +-  1-0, 29 moves, Kristiansen, J. 2419 - Hansen, J. 2041, Aalborg 2012.  15...Qxd5  16.Bd2  Rac8   16...cxd4  17.exd4  ±  17.c4  Qd6  18.Bc3  += }
8. e4 { Uncharacteristically, we ignore Black's ...Nb4 idea here. } 8... cxd4
9. cxd4 Nb4
{ An alternative is:   9...O-O  10.Re1  Nb4   10...Rc8  11.a3 !  Once again, we make use of this waiting move.  11.Bb1  Ba6  12.Nf1  d5  13.e5  Ne4  This apparent activity is easily extinguished:  14.a3  Bxf1  15.Kxf1  Nc6  16.Qe2  f5  17.exf6  Bxf6  18.Bxe4  dxe4  19.Qxe4  Nxd4  20.Rd1  ±  White is better. }
10. Bb1 Ba6 11. Re1 Nd3
{ A.   11...Bd3  12.a3  +-  B.   11...Rc8  12.d5 !  A crucial idea in this line.  exd5   12...O-O  13.d6  Bxd6  14.e5  +-  13.e5  Nh5  14.Nb3  g6  15.a3  Nc6  16.Bh6  White clearly has the upper hand. }
12. Bxd3 Bxd3
{ Black has the bishop pair and even a strong bishop on d3. Here, though, time is of the essence. White wastes none and grasps the initiative. }
13. d5 { Threatening d6 ! } 13... Qc8
{ 13...Bc5  14.b4 !  Bxb4  15.Qb3  Bxd2  16.Nxd2  Ba6  17.Ba3  Rc8  18.Rac1  +-  White has winning attack. }
14. d6 Bd8 15. Ne5 Ba6
{ 15...Bc2  16.Qf3  O-O  17.b3  ±  The c2-bishop is simply a bad piece. } 16.
Ndf3 O-O 17. b3 Ne8 18. Ba3 Qb7 19. Nd4 Rc8 20. Qd2 f6 21. Nef3 Rf7 22. Rad1
{ White's position is preferable as the Black pieces are rather passive. } *

