[Black "The Energetic 6.c4 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. c4
{ The most energetic reply, transposing to Queens Indian lines. Though it is no longer a Colle-Zukertort, it is still important to understand such positions, so Ive decided to include it in this book. }
6... Be7
{ A.   6...d6  7.Nc3  Nbd7  8.Bc2 !?  N  The idea is d5.  cxd4  9.exd4  Rc8   9...d5  10.Ba4  dxc4  11.d5 !  a6  12.dxe6  fxe6  13.Ng5  e5  14.Be3  b5  15.Bc2  Despite being a pawn down, White has ample compensation.  10.d5 !  →  B.   6...g6  7.d5 !?  exd5   7...Bg7  8.e4  +=  8.cxd5  Bxd5   8...Nxd5  9.Be4  Nxe3  10.Bxe3  Bxe4  11.Re1  Be7  12.Nc3  Bf5  13.Bh6  Be6  14.Qa4  Nc6  15.Rad1  Black is feeling the pressure.  9.e4  Bc6  10.e5  Nd5  11.Nbd2   11.Bc4 !?  may be even stronger:  Nc7  12.Ng5  Ne6  13.f4  Bg7  14.Nxf7 !  Kxf7  15.f5  White has a very strong attack.  11...Nc7  The idea is to transfer the knight to the strong e6-square, from where it becomes a great defensive piece.  12.b4 !?  This may initially look like an unusual move, but White opens the long diagonal and may obtain the d4-square in case of...cxb4.  d6  13.exd6  Bxd6  14.Bb2  O-O  15.Ne4  Be7  16.Qd2 !  N   16.Ne5  Ne6  17.bxc5  bxc5  18.Rc1  Qb6  19.Qc2  1-0, Vaganian, R. 2640 - Stohl, I. 2561, Izmir 2004.  16...Ne6  17.Rfd1  Nd7  18.Qc3  +- }
7. Nc3 cxd4
{ 7...d6  8.d5 !  Intrinsic to White's play, transposing to favourable forms of the Benoni. Sometimes, positions can resemble the Ruy Lopez, too.  exd5   8...e5  9.Ng5 !?  h6  10.Nge4  Nbd7  11.f4  a6  12.a4  Nxe4  13.Nxe4  Nf6  14.fxe5  Nxe4  15.Bxe4  dxe5  16.b3  Qd6  17.Bb2  Bf6  18.Qh5  Rd8  19.Rf3  Bc8  20.Raf1  ±  White has a crushing advantage. 1-0, 30 moves, Hoi, C. 2445 - Christensen, T. 2255, Copenhagen 1990.  9.cxd5  O-O  10.e4  We have reached a strange Benoni, where White has lost a tempo with e3-e4, but Black has misplaced bishops on b7 and e7.  Ba6  11.a4  Bxd3  12.Qxd3  Nbd7  13.Nd2  Re8  14.a5  Bf8  15.f3  Ne5  16.Qe2  bxa5  17.Nb3  a4  18.Rxa4  Rb8  19.Na5  Rb4  20.Ra2  Qc7  21.Bf4  ±  Naturally, it was difficult to defend Benoni type positions against Tigran Petrosian. 1-0, 42 moves, Petrosian, T. - Golombek, H., Budapest 1952. }
8. exd4 d5 { A very popular line that's been around for a while now. } 9. cxd5
Nxd5 10. Ne5 O-O 11. Qg4
{ White also has another interesting queen move at his disposal, though it is a little underestimated by current theory:   11.Qh5  g6  12.Qh3  Nc6  13.Bh6  Nxd4 !?  14.Rfe1 !?  A new idea, at least to me. Here are a few examples of how play could proceed:  Bg5   14...Qd6  15.Rad1  Rfd8  16.Bxg6  hxg6  17.Rxd4  Bf6  18.Qg3  White has the initiative.   14...Re8  15.Rad1  Bf6  16.Bxg6  hxg6  17.Rxd4  with some pressure.   14...Qc7  15.Qg4 !  Nf5  16.Bxf5  exf5  17.Qd4  Qc5  18.Qxc5  Bxc5  19.Bxf8  Bxf8  20.Rad1  ±  15.Bxf8  Nf4  16.Qg3  f6 !!  17.Be4  Bxe4  18.Rxe4  fxe5  19.Ba3  Although Black has displayed an impeccable defence thus far, it is not clear that equality has been achieved. White wants to play Qg4 followed by g3. }
11... f5
{ 11...Nf6  12.Qh4 !  Nc6   12...Ne4  13.Qh3  Qxd4  14.Bf4  Nf6  15.Ne2  Qa4  16.Rfd1 !?  Ba6  17.Nd4  Bxd3  18.Rxd3  Qe8  19.Re1  Nbd7  20.Rg3  Nxe5  21.Bxe5  Black will struggle to defend such a position.  13.Bg5  Black is already in deep trouble here.  Re8 ?   13...Nxe5  14.Bxf6  Nxd3  15.Bxe7  ±   13...g6 ?  14.Ba6 !  +-  A beautiful pattern.  14.Bxf6  Bxf6  15.Qxh7+  Kf8  16.Be4  +-  An easy win for a famous English GM: 1-0, 24 moves, Hebden, M. 2494 - Speelman, J. 2511, St Clement Bay 2017. }
12. Qe2 Bf6
{ 12...Nc7  13.Rd1  Nc6  14.Nxc6  Bxc6  15.Bf4  Bd6  16.Be5  Bxe5  17.Qxe5  Rc8  18.Rac1  Qd7  19.Bc4  Bd5  20.Nxd5  Nxd5  21.Rc2  Kh8  22.Rdc1  +=  Indeed, White is having a better time. Another victory for Mark Hebden ! 1-0, 54 moves, Hebden, M. 2477 - Gormally, D. 2462, Dundee 2017. }
13. Bc4 Re8 { 13...Kh8  14.Rd1  +=  White retains an edge. } 14. Rd1 Nd7
{ 14...a6  15.Qh5  Rf8  16.Qf3  Ra7  17.Re1 !  Ba8  18.Bd2  Re8  19.Rac1  Rae7  20.Nxd5  Bxd5  21.Bxd5  Qxd5  22.Qxd5  exd5  23.f4  White is better. }
15. Bb5 Bxe5 16. dxe5 Qe7 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Qh5 g6
{ 18...h6  19.Bxh6 !  gxh6  20.Qg6+  Kf8  21.Qxh6+  Kf7  22.Rxd5 !  exd5  23.Qh7+  Kf8  24.Qxf5+  Qf7  25.Bxd7  Qxf5  26.Bxf5  Rxe5  27.Bd3  White is better here. The bishop is very strong as it controls the critical e2- and c2-squares while supporting its pawns on the kingside. }
19. Qh6 Rec8 20. Bg5 Qf7 21. Bxd7 Qxd7 22. Bf6 Qf7 23. b3 Qf8 24. Qf4 Rc2 25.
h4
