[White "Systems without ...d5: 2...g6"]
[Black "5...d6 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3
{ White combines various plans, but mainly refrains, at least momentarily, from playing an early c4. Naturally, such an approach gives rise to new possible ideas. }
6... e5
{ A.   6...b6  7.Bb2  A solid approach from both sides.  Bb7  8.c4  Nbd7  9.Nc3  e5  10.d5 !  We are now in completely unexplored territory. We have reached some strange King and Queen's Indian hybdrid. In any case, it is fully playable for White.  B.   6...c5  7.Bb2  cxd4  8.exd4  White wants to be proactive here with c4, Nc3, d5 and so on. If, 8... d5, we have a Queens Indian reversed where White is up two tempi, a considerable asset. Let's examine a few ideas:  d5  9.Nbd2  Nc6  10.Re1  Bf5  11.Nf1  Rc8  12.Ne3  White has managed tor regroup in the best way possible due to the two extra tempi.  C.   6...Nc6 !?  7.Bb2  e5  8.dxe5  Nd7  9.Qc1 !?   9.Nc3 !?  9...dxe5   9...Ndxe5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.c4 !  transposes to systems under 6... e5. Only now, once Black has taken with the knight, White goes c4. This is a well-known rule in such positions.  10.Nc3  gives similar positions as 6... e5.  D.   6...Nbd7 !?  7.Bb2  Re8  8.c4  c6  Black waits before playing ...e5. White, on the other hand, doesn't have much choice but to develop further.   8...e5  Direct play doesn't work:  9.dxe5  dxe5  White can simply win a pawn.  10.Nxe5  Ne4  11.Nd3  Bxb2  12.Nxb2  Black doesn't have enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn.  9.Nc3  e5  10.dxe5  dxe5  The main idea c6 was useful as it prevents Nd5, and Black wants to proceed with ...Qe7, ...a5, and ...Nc5, following a usual King's Indian plan.  11.b4 !  A key concept for White here, taking space and preparing a strategical plan: c5 followed by Nd2-c4, landing on the strong d6-square. A principled manoeuvre.  D1.  Qe7  D2.   11...e4  12.Nd2  b6   12...Ne5 ?!  The World Champion was obviously not familiar with this position:  13.Ndxe4  Nxe4  14.Nxe4  Nf3+  15.Bxf3  Bxb2  16.Nd6 !  +-  1/2-1/2, 40 moves, Nakamura, H. 2786 - Carlsen, M. 2832, Chess.com INT 2018.  13.Qc2  Qe7  14.Rad1 !  Nf8   14...Bb7  15.Ndxe4 !  Nxe4  16.Nxe4  +-   14...Qxb4  15.Ncxe4  Nxe4  16.Bxg7  ±  15.b5 !  It is important to understand where to turn for activity. With this move, we are fighting for the d5-square.  Bb7   15...c5  16.Nd5  Nxd5  17.cxd5  Bxb2  18.Qxb2  White is ready to land on c4 square with the knight.  Qg5  19.Kh1  Qxd5  20.Nxe4 !  ±  16.bxc6  Bxc6  17.Nb3  We are faced with another complex position, but White's play certainly seems easier.  12.c5  e4  13.Nd2  b6   13...b5  14.a4  ±  14.Qc2 !!  A tough move to make, but a thematic one nonetheless. White sacrifices a pawn in order to speed up his play.  bxc5  15.bxc5  Qxc5   15...Nxc5  16.Ba3  Qe5  17.Nc4  +-  16.Rac1  Rb8  17.Nc4  =∞  Ba6  18.Ba3  Qg5  19.Bd6  Bxc4  20.Bxc4  ± }
7. dxe5
{ This is White's normal reaction, not to allow further expansion with ...e4. This is like when Black plays ...dxe4 in the French in order to prevent White from pushing e5. Some players do it as early as move 3! }
7... Ng4 8. Bb2 Nc6
{ 8...Nd7  A.  9.c4  This would be an ideal response, but the problem is that Black can take on e5 with a pawn.  B. Kramnik had a different approach:   9.Nc3 !?  dxe5   9...Ngxe5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Qd2  Re8  12.Rad1  transposes to Kramnik-Vachier Lagrave game which featured 8... Nc6.  10.Nd2 !?  Ngf6  11.Nc4  +=  C.   9.Qc1 !?  A useful move, defending the bishop while vacating the d1-sqaure for the rook in case Black goes dxe5. If a knight recaptures, then White is ready for c4 !  Ngxe5   9...dxe5  10.h3  Nh6  11.Rd1  f6  12.Nc3  Nf7  13.Bc4 !?  Kh8  14.Ba3  Nd6  15.Bxd6  cxd6  16.Rxd6  ±  10.Nxe5  dxe5   10...Nxe5  11.c4 !  as previously mentioned.  11.Nc3  Nf6  12.Ba3  Re8  13.Rd1  Bd7  14.e4  Qc8  15.Qe3  White's chances are preferable. }
9. Nc3 Ngxe5
{ 9...dxe5  10.Qc1  Nf6  11.Rd1  Bd7  12.Nd2 !  +=  Using the c4-square for pieces, as we have seen is often the case in this line. }
10. Qd2 Re8
{ 10...Nxf3+  11.Bxf3  Ne5  12.Be2  c6  13.Rad1  d5  14.e4  d4  15.Na4  +- }
11. Rad1 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Ne5 13. Be2 Be6 14. Nb5
{ Relocating the white knight to a more comfortable square. } 14... a6 15. Nd4
Bd7 16. c4
{ We have reached a typical position which can also arise from the King's Indian Defence. White has a slighly better pawn structure andBlack is forced to remain a little passive. 1/ 2-1/2, 59 moves, Kramnik, V. 2792 - Vachier-Lagrave, M. 2789, Paris 2018. }
