1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3
{ White combines various plans, but mainly refrains, at least momentarily, from playing an early c4. Naturally, such an approach gives rise to new possible ideas. }
6... Nbd7 7. Bb2 Re8 8. c4 c6
{ Black waits before playing ...e5. White, on the other hand, doesn't have much choice but to develop further. }
9. Nc3 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5
{ The main idea c6 was useful as it prevents Nd5, and Black wants to proceed with ...Qe7, ...a5, and ...Nc5, following a usual King's Indian plan. }
11. b4
{ A key concept for White here, taking space and preparing a strategical plan: c5 followed by Nd2-c4, landing on the strong d6-square. A principled manoeuvre. }
11... e4 12. Nd2 Ne5
{ The World Champion was obviously not familiar with this position: } 13. Ndxe4
