[White "Systems without ...d5: 2...g6"]
[Black "5...d6 Variation 20"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3
{ White combines various plans, but mainly refrains, at least momentarily, from playing an early c4. Naturally, such an approach gives rise to new possible ideas. }
6... e5 7. dxe5
{ This is White's normal reaction, not to allow further expansion with ...e4. This is like when Black plays ... dxe4 in the French in order to prevent White from pushing e5. Some players do it as early as move 3! }
7... Ng4 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. Nc3 Ngxe5 10. Qd2 Re8 11. Rad1 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Ne5 13.
Be2 Be6 14. Nb5 { Relocating the white knight to a more comfortable square. }
14... a6 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. c4
{ We have reached a typical position which can also arise from the King's Indian Defence. White has a slighly better pawn structure and Black is forced to remain a little passive. 1/2-1/2, 59 moves, Kramnik, V. 2792 - Vachier-Lagrave, M. 2789, Paris 2018. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems without ...d5: 2...g6"]
[Black "5...c5 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5
{ Another usual reaction. Black undermines the centre in Benoni fashion. White has many options but I decided to go for the Colle formation here. }
6. c3
{ This may look passive, but appearances can be deceptive. Black has to decide what to do with the c-pawn, to take on d4 or to keep the game closed. In both cases, White has the opportunity to reach a promising middlegame. }
6... d5
{ The most ambitious approach.  A.   6...d6  7.Nbd2  b6  8.b4  Nbd7  9.a4  Bb7  10.Qb3  cxb4  11.cxb4  Qc7  12.Bb2  Rac8  13.Rfc1  Qb8  14.b5  +=  It looks drawish, but White faces no risk and his extra space provides him with some winning chances.  B.   6...cxd4  7.cxd4 !?   7.exd4  d6  8.Bg5  Be6  9.Nbd2  Nc6  A transposition to Torre systems.  7...d5  8.Nc3  Nc6  9.b3  A solid way to develop: White wants to play with Ba3 or Bb2, followed by Rc1. The position may look a little dry, but Black's fianchettoed bishop is seriously misplaced in these structures, targeting a rock on d4.  Bf5  10.Bb2  Rc8  11.Rc1  Ne4  12.a3  Nxc3  13.Bxc3  Be4  14.b4  Bxf3  15.Bxf3  e6  16.b5  Na5  17.Bb4  Though this was just an illustrative example, White has some pressure. }
7. dxc5 Ne4 8. b4
{ Now it starts to become very sharp. White hangs on to the c5-pawn, at least for a moment. }
8... a5
{ There are alternatives, but they do not promise much.   8...Nxc3  9.Nxc3  Bxc3  10.Rb1  a6  Black is trying to prevent further expansion on the queenside.   10...Nc6  11.b5  Na5  12.Bb2  Bxb2  13.Rxb2  White is better.   10...Bf5  11.Rb3  Bf6  12.Bb2  Bxb2  13.Rxb2  and White has the advantage.  11.Bb2  Bxb2  12.Rxb2  Nc6  A.  13.a3  B.   13.a4 !?  a5  14.b5  Nb4  15.Qd4  f6  16.Nd2  e5  17.Qc3  Be6  18.Nb3  with the initiative in White's hands.  C.   13.Qb3  e5  14.Rd2  Be6  15.Qb2  f6  16.Bc4 !?  Kg7   16...dxc4  17.Rxd8  Rfxd8  18.Nd2  Rd3  19.Ne4  +-  17.Bxd5 !  Bxd5  18.Rfd1  Ne7  19.e4  ±  13...e5   13...Bg4  14.Rd2  e6  15.e4  +=  14.Rd2  e4  15.Nd4  Qg5  16.Kh1  Be6  17.Qa1  h5  18.Qc3  White's chances are slightly preferable. }
9. Nd4 e5 { 9...Nc6  10.b5  Ne5  11.Ba3  leads to a complicated position. } 10.
Nb5 Nc6 11. Nd2 axb4
{ Black had another intriguing option:   11...Nxd2  12.Bxd2  d4  13.a3 !  d3  14.Bf3  f5   14...Qe7  15.Nd6  ±  15.Qb3+  Kh8  16.e4  with the idea of Rad1. White seizes a significant advantage. }
12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. cxb4 Nxb4 14. Nd6 Qc7 15. a4
{ Great idea, it seems that it is only White who can play for advantage here.   15.Nxe4  Bf5  =∞ }
15... Qxc5 16. Bc4 { White wants to play Ba3.   16.Nxe4  Qc6  ∞ } 16... Rd8
{ B.   16...Be6  17.Bxe6  fxe6  18.Nxe4  Qc6  19.Qg4  += } 17. Bxf7+ Kh8
{ 17...Kf8 ?!  18.Qb3  Rxd6  19.Bg8  +- } 18. Nxe4 Qe7 19. Qb3 Bf5 20. Ba3 Bxe4
21. Qxb4
{ White is better.  @@HeaderStart@@Conclusion@@HeaderEnd@@  Here we have dealt with the ...g6 system which is, of course, one of the most popular replies. Hence, I divided the task into two parts:A. 5... d6 6. b3 !? A rare idea, full of possibilities but seldom seen in tournament practice.B. 5... c5 6. c3 !? Yet another interesting and rare line into which I am trying to inject a worthy breath of fresh air. }
*

