*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems without ...d5: Rare First and Second Move"]
[Black "1...Nf6 2.Nf3 d6 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Bg4
{ In today's chess, we often see such an approach, and it is also recomended in books  (not without good reason)  as a very practical solution for tournament play. Therefore, I decided to include it here and offer a line that goes with the rest of the book. }
4. Be2 Nbd7 5. c4 e5 6. Nc3 Be7
{ A schema that has become commonplace, so I will present here one of many possible ideas, in conjuction with the Colle-Zukertort. }
7. O-O O-O 8. b3
{ This move again, in Zukertort style. We will see many rare lines that are actually rather underestimated. }
8... c6 9. Qc2 Re8 10. Bb2 Bf8 11. dxe5
{ This is a principled reaction, reminiscent of King's Indian lines. } 11...
dxe5 12. Rad1
{ It would be a mistake to go h3 at this point. The e3-pawn  (rather than being on e4)  makes a huge difference as it restricts Black's dark-squared bishop and allows White to use the e4-square to manoeuvre his pieces, as will soon become apparent. }
12... Qc7
{ A. An alternative was seen in tournament practice:   12...e4  13.Nd4  Qc7  14.h3  Bxe2  15.Ndxe2 !   15.Ncxe2  g6  16.Bc3  Bg7  17.Nf4  a6  18.Qb2  Re7  19.Rd2  Rae8  20.Rfd1  Ne5  21.Nc2  g5  22.Ne2  ∞  1/2-1/2, 51 moves, Pfleger, H. 2485 - Lobron, E. 2570, Germany 1994.  15...Bd6  16.Rd2  Be5  17.Rfd1  Nc5  18.Nd4  a5  19.Nf5 !  →  +=3 Ba3  Rad8 ?  The proof that logical moves are not always good ones.  20.Rxd8  Rxd8  21.Rxd8+  Qxd8  22.Na4 !  Bxb2  23.Nxc5  Be5  24.g3  g6  25.Nh6+  Kg7  26.Ng4  Nxg4  27.hxg4  +-  B.   12...Qa5  13.a3 !  e4  14.Nd2  Bxe2  15.Nxe2  Qf5  16.b4  a5  17.Bc3  axb4  18.axb4  h5  19.h3  h4  20.f3  +=  It seems that Black is unable to equalise with such a strategy. }
13. h3
{ The right timing for this move.   13.Ng5  Bxe2  14.Nxe2  h6  15.Nf3  a5  16.Ng3  ∞ }
13... Bh5
{ 13...Bxf3  14.Bxf3  a5  15.g3  Nc5  16.Bg2  +=  At the moment, Black is doing OK. However, if White manages to obtain more space on the queenside with a3 and b4,then the two bishops may turn into a big asset for White. }
14. Ng5
{ As previously mentioned, we want to exchange the light-squared bishops and use the e4-square as a stepping stone for our pieces. }
14... Bg6
{ 14...Bxe2  15.Nxe2  h6  16.Nf3 !  An important move in order to realise the plan that follows.  Rad8  17.Ng3  g6  18.Bc3  Bg7  19.Qb2 !  Rc8  20.b4  Re7  21.e4 !  Rce8  22.Rd3  Nh7  23.Rfd1  Ndf8  24.Rd6  White has the initiative.  Ng5  25.Nxg5  hxg5  26.c5  +=  1/2-1/2, 43 moves, Vogt, L. 2490 - Bielczyk, J. 2390, Polanica Zdroj 1982. }
15. Bd3 Bxd3 { Both recaptures are now possible. } 16. Qxd3
{ 16.Rxd3 !?  Nc5  17.Rd2  With the obvious idea of doubling the rooks on the d-file.  A.  a5  B.   17...e4  18.b4  h6   18...Nd3  19.Ngxe4  +-  19.bxc5  hxg5  20.Na4   20.Ne2  Nd7  21.Bd4  Bxc5  22.Ng3  Bxd4  23.Rxd4  Nf6  24.Nxe4  Rxe4  25.Rxe4  Nxe4  26.Qxe4  Rd8  Black is fine here.  20...Rad8  21.Rxd8  Qxd8  22.Rb1  Qc7  23.Bd4  +=  C.   17...Rad8  18.Rfd1  Rxd2  19.Rxd2  Rd8  20.Nb1 !!  A marvelous positional idea.  Rxd2  21.Nxd2  h6  22.Ngf3  Ncd7  23.g4  +=  As is clearly visible in this example, the e5-pawn has become a target. Needless to say, none of this would be of any interest if White's pawn were on e4.  18.Nce4  Ncxe4  19.Nxe4  Nxe4  20.Qxe4  f6  21.Rfd1  Rad8  22.Qf5  +=  Due to pressure along the d-file, we can say that White enjoys slightly better chances. }
16... Nc5 17. Qb1
{ Due to tactical ideas further down the line, we will see that the queen is better off here than on c2.   17.Qf5  Qc8  18.Qxc8  Raxc8  19.b4  Ncd7  The tables are turning. }
17... e4
{ A. Due to this simple move, 16 Rxd3 might have been the better try.   17...h6  18.Nge4  Ncxe4  19.Nxe4  Nxe4  20.Qxe4  f6  and despite White's control of the light-squares, Black will play ... Rad8 and equalise.  B.   17...a5  18.Ba3 !?  Another important positional feature here. With the pawn being on e3, White simply wants to play a queen and knight versus queen and bishop endgame, with firm control overthe e4-square.  h6  19.Bxc5  Bxc5  20.Nge4  Nxe4  21.Nxe4  Be7  22.g4 !  This is it ! }
18. Ne2 { The beginning of a creative idea. } 18... h6
{ 18...a5  19.Ng3  Qe7  20.Qa1  h6  21.Nf5  Qc7  22.Bxf6  gxf6  23.Qxf6  hxg5  24.Qxg5+  Kh7  25.f3 !  ± }
19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. b4 fxg5
{ 20...hxg5  21.bxc5  Bxc5  22.Ng3  →  Qe7  23.Nf5  Qe6  24.g4  b6  25.Qc2  ±  With the idea of Kg2 and h4, leading to a strong attack along the h-file ! A fine example of how a knight can dominate a bishop.  Rad8  26.Kg2  Kh7  27.Rh1  Rxd1  28.Qxd1  Kg6  29.h4  Rh8  30.hxg5  +- }
21. bxc5 f5
{ 21...Bxc5  22.Ng3  Qe7  23.Nf5  Qe6  24.g4  b6  25.Qb2  The strong f5-knight guarantees White a long-term initiative. }
22. Nd4
{ The knight can take a different route:   22.Ng3  Qh7  23.f3  Bxc5  24.Kh1  Bxe3  25.fxe4  f4  26.Nf5  Here, too, the strong outpost on f5 gives White good play. }
22... Qh7 23. f4 exf3
{ 23...Bxc5  24.fxg5  Bxd4  25.Rxd4  hxg5  26.Qb3  With compensation. } 24.
Nxf5 fxg2 25. Kxg2 Bxc5 26. Rd2
{ White has compensation for the sacrificed pawn. The f5-knight dominates the board.@@HeaderStart@@Conclusion@@HeaderEnd@@ This system has a reputation as a very practical line for Black, tailored for tournament chess. Therefore, I decided to meet it in practical terms too: fighting fire with fire. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Systems without ...d5: Rare First and Second Move"]
[Black "1...Nf6 2.Nf3 d6 Variation 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Bg4
{ In today's chess, we often see such an approach, and it is also recomended in books  (not without good reason)  as a very practical solution for tournament play. Therefore, I decided to include it here and offer a line that goes with the rest of the book. }
4. Be2 Nbd7 5. c4 e5 6. Nc3 Be7
{ A schema that has become commonplace, so I will present here one of many possible ideas, in conjuction with the Colle-Zukertort. }
7. O-O O-O 8. b3
{ This move again, in Zukertort style. We will see many rare lines that are actually rather underestimated. }
8... c6 9. Qc2 Re8 10. Bb2 Bf8 11. dxe5
{ This is a principled reaction, reminiscent of King's Indian lines. } 11...
dxe5 12. Rad1
{ It would be a mistake to go h3 at this point. The e3-pawn  (rather than being on e4)  makes a huge difference as it restricts Black's dark-squared bishop and allows White to use the e4-square to manoeuvre his pieces, as will soon become apparent. }
12... e4 13. Nd4 Qc7 14. h3 Bxe2 15. Ndxe2 Bd6 16. Rd2 Be5 17. Rfd1 Nc5 18. Nd4
a5 19. Nf5 { ∆ Ba3 } 19... Rad8
{ The proof that logical moves are not always good ones. } 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21.
Rxd8+ Qxd8 22. Na4 Bxb2 23. Nxc5 Be5 24. g3 g6 25. Nh6+ Kg7 26. Ng4 Nxg4 27.
hxg4 *

