[Round "?"]
[White "Systems without ...d5: Rare First and Second Move"]
[Black "1...Nf6 2.Nf3 b6 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 b6
{ An offbeat reaction, but considering the rise of 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 b6, this has to be given some attention. It is an elastic approach; Black keeps his options open. Here, we will deal with some unusual setups and ideas. }
3. e3
{ For obvious reasons, I will gravitate towards Colle-Zukertort ideas as much as possible, which explains 3 e3. It is true that 3 Bg5 is also a serious contender, but I have decided not to include the Torre in this book. }
3... Bb7 4. Bd3 c5
{ Black can also try another rare idea:   4...g6  5.c4  Bg7  6.Nc3  In the style of the Grunfeld.  d5 !?   6...O-O  7.e4  e6 ?!  Some strange mix kind of experimental chess.  8.O-O  d5  9.cxd5  exd5  10.e5  Ne4  11.Re1  Nxc3  12.bxc3  gives White easier play. Bg5 and h4 will follow.  A.  7.cxd5  B.   7.Qa4+  Qd7  8.Qb3  O-O  9.Ne5  Qd8  10.O-O  c5  11.dxc5  Ne4 !  12.c6  Nxc6  13.Nxc6  Bxc6  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Be2  Be5  16.Rd1  Qc7  17.h3  Rfd8  18.Bd2  a5  19.Bc3  with an unclear middlegame.  C.   7.O-O  White has little else.  O-O  8.Qe2  e6  9.b4  Nbd7  10.cxd5 !  This is an important intermediate move. White transposes to a mix of Queen's Indian and Grünfeld hybrid line.  exd5  11.b5  Re8  12.Bb2  Ne4  13.Rfc1  A long positional battle awaits us. White will try touse the c-file in order to put pressure on the c7-pawn. Black, on the other hand, wants to use the semi-open e-file as his source of play.  7...Nxd5  8.Nxd5 !?   8.e4  Nxc3  9.bxc3  O-O  10.O-O  c5  leads to reasonable versions of the Grunfeld for Black, which is the exact idea behind 6... d5.  8...Qxd5  9.e4  Qd7  10.O-O  O-O  11.Be3  A1.  e6  A2.   11...Nc6 !  12.d5  Ne5  13.Nxe5  Bxe5  14.Qe2  c6  15.f4  Bg7  16.dxc6  Bxc6  17.e5  e6  18.Rfd1  Qe7  leads to balanced play.  12.Qe2  Nc6  13.Rfd1  Kh8 !?  with the idea of .. .f5.   13...f5  14.Bc4 !  →  14.Bc4 !  White has better chances. }
5. O-O g6
{ A surprise that serves the purpose of confusing the opponent. But I question the move's objective validity.   5...e6  transposes to Chapter 8. }
6. Re1 Bg7
{ 6...cxd4 !?  7.exd4  Bg7  8.c3  O-O  9.Bg5  d6  10.Nbd2  Nbd7  Probably Black's best bet, though it still isn't ideal as we have entered a Torre line that is considered good for White. }
7. e4 cxd4
{ A.   7...c4  8.Bxc4  Nxe4  9.d5  Nd6  10.Bf1  O-O  11.Nc3  Na6  12.Bf4  White's play is easy.  B.   7...O-O  8.d5  e6  9.c4  A very good version of the Benoni for White due to the misplaced b7-bishop. }
8. e5 { As far as I know, this is a new idea. } 8... Nd5 9. Be4 Qc8 10. Qxd4
Nc7 11. Bxb7 Qxb7 12. Qh4 Nc6 13. Bh6 O-O 14. Nc3 Ne6 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Rd3
{ White is having more fun here.@@HeaderStart@@Conclusion@@HeaderEnd@@ 2... b6 is a popular option for Black nowadays, so I have given specific lines here that dont stem from regular positions where Black plays with the natural ...e6. }
