1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 b6
{ An offbeat reaction, but considering the rise of 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 b6, this has to be given some attention. It is an elastic approach; Black keeps his options open. Here, we will deal with some unusual setups and ideas. }
3. e3
{ For obvious reasons, I will gravitate towards Colle-Zukertort ideas as much as possible, which explains 3 e3. It is true that 3 Bg5 is also a serious contender, but I have decided not to include the Torre in this book. }
3... Bb7 4. Bd3 { Black can also try another rare idea: } 4... g6 5. c4 Bg7 6.
Nc3 { In the style of the Grunfeld. } 6... d5 7. O-O { White has little else. }
7... O-O 8. Qe2 e6 9. b4 Nbd7 10. cxd5
{ This is an important intermediate move. White transposes to a mix of Queen's Indian and Grunfeld hybrid line. }
10... exd5 11. b5 Re8 12. Bb2 Ne4 13. Rfc1
{ A long positional battle awaits us. White will try to use the c-file in order to put pressure on the c7-pawn. Black, on the other hand, wants to use the semi-open e-file as his source of play. }
