[Black "1...e6 2.Nf3 f5 - Theory"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5
{ A typical move order for Dutch players, which makes it an important line to address. The idea I have analysed is as sharp as it is rare. }
3. Bf4 { No Colle-Zukertort resemblance this time. } 3... Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. h3
O-O 6. Nbd2 b6 7. Bd3
{ The starting point of the line. White will soon have to decide where to put the queen. }
7... Bb7 8. c3 Ne4 9. Qe2
{ 9.Rg1 !?  A cunning move. White waits before committing the queen to a square and decides to open the g-file first.  A.  d6  B.   9...Kh8 !?  is probably best as the king will most likely end up on h8 anyway.  10.g4  d6  11.gxf5  exf5  12.Qc2 !?  Now that the structure is a little weakened, White forces Black to choose between d5 or taking on d2.   12.Qe2  Nd7  13.O-O-O  Qe8  transposes to the main line.  12...Nxd2  13.Nxd2  Qd7  14.O-O-O  Na6 !  Black must react fast.   14...c5  15.dxc5 !  →  15.h4   15.Bg5 !?  Rae8  16.Qb3  Nb8  17.Bb5  Bc6  18.Bxc6  Nxc6  19.h4  d5  20.Nf3  Bxg5  21.hxg5  f4  ⇆  15...c5 !  B1.  16.Nb3 !?  B2. Also very interesting is:   16.h5  cxd4  17.exd4  Nc7  18.Kb1  Ne6  19.Bh2   19.Bxf5 ?!  Rxf5 !  20.Qxf5  Rf8  21.Qh3  Rxf4  Black is better.  19...Ng5  with balanced but complicated play.  16...Rac8  17.dxc5  Nxc5  18.Nxc5  Rxc5  19.h5  b5  with mutual chances.  10.Qc2 !  d5  11.g4  c5  12.gxf5  exf5  13.dxc5 !!  Unorthodox but strong ! White opens the position up in order to create threats.  bxc5  14.O-O-O !  Qb6   14...Nxf2  15.Bxf5  Nxd1  16.Bxh7+  Kh8  17.Qg6  +-  15.Ne5  White is better here. }
9... d6 10. O-O-O Nd7 11. Rhg1
{ Suprisingly, it is possible to sacrifice the exchange here, although it is probably White who is taking more risks:   11.g4  Nxd2 !  A.  12.Nxd2 !?  B.   12.Kxd2  e5 !  -+  C.   12.Rxd2  g5 !  A critical move, Black is ready to gain material. Now it gets sharp.  13.gxf5   13.Bg3  fxg4  Black wins.  13...gxf4  14.fxe6  Bxf3  15.Qxf3   15.Rg1+  Kh8  16.Qxf3  fxe3  17.Qxe3  Nf6  18.Qh6  Rg8  19.Rdd1  d5  Black is fine.  15...fxe3  16.Qxe3  Kh8 !?  17.exd7   17.f4  Nf6  18.f5  d5  Black's control over the dark-squares simply blocks White's play.  17...Bg5  18.Qe6 !?  Rxf2  19.Be2 !!  Thank the engine ! It seems as though White can keep his d7-pawn.  Qg8  20.Qxg8+  Rxg8  21.h4 !   21.Kd1  Bxd2  22.Kxd2  Rd8  23.Ke3  Rf6  24.Bg4  h5 !  ∓  is very good for Black.  21...Bxd2+  22.Kxd2  Rd8  23.Ke3  Rf7  24.Bg4  Kg7  25.Ke4  c6  26.d5  Re7+  27.Kd4  c5+  28.Kd3  Kf8  29.Be6  Rg7  30.Kc4  a6  31.Re1  Ke7  with a more or less balanced play.  12...Bxh1  13.Rxh1  Kh8  14.gxf5  exf5  15.h4   15.Nf1  Bg5  Black is better.  15...d5  16.Nf1  intending to bring the knight to g3 and attack the weak f5-pawn.  Bd6 !  17.Bxd6   17.Bg5  Qe8  ⇆  17...cxd6  18.Ng3  f4  with an edge for Black. }
11... Kh8 12. g4 Qe8
{ The queen on e8 is important as it may end up on a4 to create an attack. As will become clear, it also supports the e5 push ! }
13. gxf5
{ A.   13.Kb1  Ndf6 !  14.g5  Nd5  with the annoying threat of Nxc3.  B.   13.h4  e5 !  It is important to be aware that this can be a vital asset for Black.  14.dxe5  Nxc3 !  15.bxc3  dxe5  16.Bh2  e4  17.Bb5  exf3  18.Nxf3  Ba3+  19.Kb1  Be4+  20.Ka1  c6  Black is better.  C.   13.Bc2  a5 !?  This entire line is full of such creative and sharp ideas.  A premature knight move can give White the initiative:   13...Ndf6  14.g5  Nd5  15.g6 !?  14.h4  a4  15.a3  Ra5 !?  16.gxf5  exf5  17.Ng5   17.Nc4  Ra8  ∞  17...Nxd2  18.Kxd2  Bd8  19.h5  Nf6  would lead to a very complex game. }
13... exf5 14. h4
{ 14.Rg2  Ndf6  15.Rdg1  Nxd2  16.Kxd2  Qh5  17.Rg3  Rae8  ⇆  could go both ways. }
14... Ndf6 15. Ng5
{ Also possible is:   15.h5  Nd5  16.Bc2  In order to prevent ideas involving ...Qa4.  b5  17.Rg2   17.Ng5  Nxf4 !  18.exf4  Nxg5  19.fxg5  Bxg5  Black is clearly better.   17.h6  g6  18.Nxe4  fxe4  19.Ng5  Nxf4  20.exf4  Bxg5  21.fxg5  d5 =  with equal chances.  17...b4  18.c4  Nxf4 !  Only now, after provoking c4, is this good.  19.exf4  Nxd2  20.Rxd2  Bf6  =+  Black has seized the initiative. }
15... Nd5 16. Ne6 { 16.Qf3  Bxg5  17.hxg5  g6  is unclear. } 16... Ndxc3
{ A very important theme in this line; Black simply must create threats. } 17.
bxc3 Nxc3 18. Qf1 Qa4 19. Rxg7 Bd5
{ This leads to a draw, which, of course, takes nothing away from the overall richness of the line. }
20. Rxe7 Nxa2+ 21. Kb2 Qb4+ 22. Ka1 Qc3+ 23. Kb1 Qb4+
{ 23...Nb4  24.Bc4  Qc2+  25.Ka1 =  @@HeaderStart@@Conclusion@@HeaderEnd@@ Although the London System is not part of this book, it does look promising against the Dutch, so I decided to give it some spotlight. Many of the unfolding positions are unclear, but I like White. }
